{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_49228", "question": "How does the formation of a complex ion, such as Fe(OH)3, change when the pH of the solution is increased or decreased? Provide an explanation of the chemical equilibria involved in the formation of complex ions and use the appropriate chemical equations to support your answer.", "answer": "The formation of a complex ion, such as Fe(OH)3, is affected by the pH of the solution. When the pH of the solution is increased or decreased, the equilibrium of the complex ion formation shifts accordingly. To understand this, let's first look at the chemical equilibria involved in the formation of Fe(OH)3.\n\nFe(OH)3 is formed from the reaction of Fe3+ ions with OH- ions in solution:\n\nFe3+ + 3OH- <=> Fe(OH)3 (s)\n\nThis reaction is an equilibrium, meaning that the concentrations of the reactants and products can change depending on the conditions of the system. The equilibrium constant, Ksp, for this reaction is given by:\n\nKsp = [Fe3+][OH-]^3\n\nNow, let's consider how the pH of the solution affects the formation of Fe(OH)3.\n\n1. Increasing the pH of the solution:\n\nWhen the pH of the solution is increased, the concentration of OH- ions in the solution increases. According to Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium will shift to counteract this change. In this case, the equilibrium will shift to the right, favoring the formation of Fe(OH)3:\n\nFe3+ + 3OH- <=> Fe(OH)3 (s) (shifts to the right)\n\nAs a result, more Fe(OH)3 will be formed, and the solubility of Fe3+ ions in the solution will decrease.\n\n2. Decreasing the pH of the solution:\n\nWhen the pH of the solution is decreased, the concentration of H+ ions in the solution increases. This leads to a decrease in the concentration of OH- ions due to the equilibrium between H+ and OH- ions:\n\nH2O <=> H+ + OH-\n\nAccording to Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium of the Fe(OH)3 formation will shift to counteract the decrease in OH- ions. In this case, the equilibrium will shift to the left, favoring the dissociation of Fe(OH)3:\n\nFe3+ + 3OH- <=> Fe(OH)3 (s) (shifts to the left)\n\nAs a result, less Fe(OH)3 will be formed, and the solubility of Fe3+ ions in the solution will increase.\n\nIn summary, the formation of a complex ion, such as Fe(OH)3, is affected by the pH of the solution. Increasing the pH favors the formation of Fe(OH)3 and decreases the solubility of Fe3+ ions, while decreasing the pH favors the dissociation of Fe(OH)3 and increases the solubility of Fe3+ ions."}
