{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_235651", "question": "How can I use Paramiko to transfer complete directories? I'm currently trying to use the following code snippet:\n```python\nsftp.put(\"/Folder1\",\"/Folder2\")\n```\nHowever, I'm encountering the following error: `Error : [Errno 21] Is a directory`.", "answer": "The `sftp.put()` method in Paramiko is used for uploading a file from local to remote, not for entire directories. If you want to transfer an entire directory, you will have to recursively upload all files in the directory. Here is a function that does exactly that:\n\n```python\nimport os\nimport paramiko\n\ndef put_directory(path, sftp):\n    for item in os.listdir(path):\n        if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(path, item)):\n            sftp.put(os.path.join(path, item), '/remote/path/' + item)\n        else:\n            sftp.mkdir('/remote/path/' + item)\n            put_directory(os.path.join(path, item), sftp)\n\nssh = paramiko.SSHClient()\nssh.set_missing_host_key_policy(paramiko.AutoAddPolicy())\nssh.connect(hostname='hostname', username='username', password='password')\n\nsftp = ssh.open_sftp()\nput_directory('/local/path', sftp)\nsftp.close()\nssh.close()\n```\n\nThis code first checks every item in the directory, if it is a file, then it uploads it using `sftp.put()`. If it is a directory, it creates the directory on the remote side using `sftp.mkdir()` and then calls itself recursively to upload everything in that directory.\n\nJust replace '/local/path' and '/remote/path/' with your local directory path and remote directory path respectively and 'hostname', 'username', and 'password' with your SSH server's information."}
