{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_507100", "question": "Process: - The saliva breaks down the chemicals in the food a bit, which helps make the food mushy and easy to swallow - Your tongue helps out, pushing the food around while you chew with your teeth - The esophagus moves food from the back of your throat to your stomach - Strong muscles in the walls of the stomach and gastric juices break down food in your stomach - Your stomach moves the food into the intestines to complete digestion -   Question: suppose during dieting happens, how will it affect LESS digestion occuring.  How does the supposed perturbation influence the second effect mentioned. Answer by more, less or no effect", "answer": "The process of dieting refers to the management or alteration of food intake in order to control body weight. During dieting, you may consume less food, adopt a specific type of nutrition plan, or even intermittently fast. Different types of diets can have varying effects on digestion. \n\nNow let's see how dieting may influence digestion, and especially the second effect you mentioned - the role of the tongue in pushing the food around while you chew with your teeth:\n\n1. Less Food Consumption: When you eat less food while dieting, there will naturally be less material for the digestive system to process. Thus, overall digestion would likely be less intense as there is less food to break down. Regarding the specific role of the tongue, its job of moving food around during chewing would be 'less' affected. The tongue would still push food around while chewing, but there may be less food to move around and, therefore, the action may be less frequent or less intensive.\n\n2. Specific Nutritional Plans: Some diets emphasize specific types of food (e.g., high-fiber, low-carb, etc.). These might influence digestion depending on which nutrients are emphasized or minimized. For instance, a high-fiber diet could actually stimulate digestion by promoting the movement of food through the digestive tract. On the other hand, a low-carb diet might slow it. In these instances, the tongue's role in moving food around when chewing could be 'more' or 'less' affected depending on the type of diet and consistency of the eaten food.\n\n3. Fasting: In the case of intermittent fasting (not eating for a certain number of hours each day), digestion could be affected in various ways. On fasting periods, less food would be processed, decreasing the activities of digestion, including the tongue's action. While on eating periods, the tongue could work 'more' intensively as one might tend to eat larger meals within the limited eating time frame. \n\nTherefore, it is evident that dieting could result in both 'more,' 'less,' or 'no change' to the tongue's activity due to the complex influence of different diet types on the process of digestion. It’s difficult to identify a universal effect of dieting on this aspect of digestion, as this depends on the specific dieting strategy and the individual’s response to it."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_344945", "question": "I'm facing a situation where I have two threads in a cross-platform rendering library for iOS and Android, written in C++. Each thread needs its own EGLContext. The main thread, Thread A, renders to the Window while Thread B is a generator thread that performs calculations and renders the results into textures to be used by Thread A. \n\nIn the library, I use function pointers to static Obj.-C functions to create a new context and set it current since I can't use EGL on iOS. For Thread A, I create the context using:\n\n```c++\nEAGLContext *contextA = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2];\n```\n\nFor Thread B, I create the context using:\n\n```c++\nEAGLContext *contextB = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2 sharegroup:[contextA sharegroup]];\n```\n\nI can set either of the two contexts as the current context using:\n\n```c++\n[EAGLContext setCurrentContext:context];\n```\n\nNow, I want to achieve the same logic on Android using real EGL in the C side of the JNI bindings. I can create contextA using a WindowSurface and the native Window, and I can create contextB and pass contextA to the shareContext parameter of the eglCreateContext call. However, when I try to make contextB current, I need to pass a surface to the eglMakeCurrent call. I'm unsure about what kind of surface to pass here.\n\n<ul>\n<li>Using the WindowSurface I use for contextA is not an option as the spec states that \"At most one context for each supported client API may be current to a particular thread at a given time, and at most one context may be bound to a particular surface at a given time.\"</li>\n<li>Using EGL_NO_SURFACE will result in an EGL_BAD_MATCH error in the eglMakeCurrent call.</li>\n<li>According to the \"OpenGL ES 2.0 Programming Guide\" by Munshi, Ginsburg, and Shreiner, Pbuffers are commonly used for generating texture maps, but they recommend using framebuffer objects (FBOs) 