WORD(?)\"\n    err = db.QueryRow(query, username, password).Scan(&amp;id)\n\n    //error checking and return\n}\n\nfunc CreateBounce(userId int, bounce NewBounce) (bounceId int64, err error) {\n    //initialize some variables\n    query := \"INSERT INTO Bounces (.....) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\n    result, err := db.Exec(query, ......)\n\n    //error checking\n\n    bounceId,_ = result.LastInsertId()\n\n    //return \n}\n```", "answer": "The issue you are facing is related to managing the database connection pool in Golang. In Go 1.1, there is no convenient way to limit the number of open connections using the `database/sql` package. This means that under load, if there are no idle connections in the pool, a new connection will be created. This can lead to reaching the maximum number of connections for the database, resulting in the \"too many database connections\" error.\n\nTo resolve this, I would recommend upgrading to a newer version of Golang, such as Go 1.2 or higher. In Go 1.2+, you have access to the `SetMaxOpenConns` function in the `database/sql` package, which allows you to limit the maximum number of open connections. You can use it like this:\n\n```go\ndb.SetMaxOpenConns(100) // Adjust this value based on your requirements\n```\n\nAdditionally, make sure to check the MySQL documentation on connection settings and tuning for further optimization.\n\nIf you are unable to upgrade to a newer version of Golang, you will need to ensure in your code that the `*sql.DB` object is only being used by a limited number of clients at a time. This can be done by implementing a connection pool or using a semaphore to limit the number of concurrent connections."}
