dinburgh. found the risk of heart attack or stroke increases by 20 per cent when a person suffers from low-level stress. Mental illness has even more of a toll and is as bad as smoking, according to Oxford University research published last month. Serious. mental illness can reduce a person's life expectancy by 10 to 20 years,. when the average reduction in life expectancy for heavy smokers is. eight to 10 years. Across the globe, life expectancies are increasing with the highest male life expectancy being in Iceland - 81 - and the highest female life expectancy being in Japan - 87.\nWhat are the important parts of this article?", "answer": "1. The global life expectancy for girls born in 2012 is 73, and for boys, it's 68, with variations depending on the country.\n2. Poor lifestyle habits can reduce life expectancy and lead to premature death.\n3. Canadian medical experts created a life expectancy calculator, Project Big Life, to raise awareness on the risk factors for premature death.\n4. The calculator factors in height, weight, smoking and alcohol habits, fruit and vegetable intake, exercise, stress levels, health conditions, and household income.\n5. Research shows that obesity, sedentary lifestyles, and stress can have significant negative impacts on life expectancy, sometimes even more than smoking.\n6. Mental illnesses can reduce life expectancy by up to 20 years, which is more than the average reduction for heavy smokers.\n7. The highest male life expectancy is in Iceland (81 years) and the highest female life expectancy is in Japan (87 years)."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_116331", "question": "Create an original short story in the style of an epic poem using dactylic hexameter.", "answer": "A tale I shall tell of a man all unknown,\nFrail mortal whose fate in the hands of the gods\nIs cast, like the sand by the wind is blown,\nAnd scattered, and ground neath their iron-shod rods;\nA tale I shall tell of a man whose heart\nIs full of the strength that the gods have set\nIn the souls of the heroes, whose lives apart\nAre lived in the world, and whose eyes are wet\nWith the tears that are shed for the life that is lost\nIn the quest of the things that are passing away;\nA tale of the strife and the terrible cost\nOf a soul that is seeking the light of day.\n\nHis name have I said, yet again will I tell\nThat ye may remember the man of whom\nI sing, and the deeds that he did so well\nIn the days that are lost in the twilight gloom;\nHis name was Acrisius, and he was born\nIn the land where the sun in his golden car\nDoth sink in the sea, and the rosy morn\nDoth rise in the east and the silver star\nOf the dawn doth shine on the waters wide;\nAnd his father was mighty Poseidon, Lord\nOf the sea and the land, and his mother's side\nWas sprung from the race of the heroes of old.\n\nHe grew as a tree that is planted apace\nIn a garden where all things are fair and bright,\nAnd the winds of the earth do encircle the place,\nAnd the sun in the sky doth shed his light;\nAnd his limbs were strong as the iron bands\nThat gird the earth in their mighty hold,\nAnd his heart was as great as the sea that stands\nLike a wall of brass when the winds are bold;\nAnd he came to the age when the young men fight\nFor the love of the maidens and glory of war,\nAnd he sought to be known as a man of might,\nAnd he longed for a task that was worthy his power.\n\nThe gods looked down from their high abode\nOn the son of their brother, and saw that he\nWas strong as the winds that on earth are sowed,\nAnd bold as the waves of the restless sea;\nAnd Zeus, who is king of the gods, did say,\n\"What shall we do for this child of ours?\nShall we send him a task that will test his sway,\nOr shall we give him the golden hours\nThat are spent in the halls of the sons of light,\nWhere the days are as years, and the years as days,\nAnd the shadows that gather are chased away\nBy the glory that shines from the sun's bright rays?\"\n\nThen spake Athena, the wise and fair,\nAnd her voice was heard in the council of gods:\n\"Let us give him a task that is hard to bear,\nAnd a weight that is heavy to lift, and odds\nThat are hard to be met, and a strife that is stern,\nAnd a foe that is worthy his strength and skill;\nAnd if he shall conquer, and if he shall learn\nHow to fight and to suffer, and how to fulfill\nThe will of the gods, then his glory shall be\nAs a light that doth shine in the skies above,\nAnd his name shall be great in the years that flee,\nAnd his deeds shall be sung in the songs of love.\"\n\nThen Zeus, who is king, did regard her speech,\nAnd he said: \"O daughter of wisdom, speak\nWhat task thou hast set for the man, and teach\nUs how he may win what we all do seek\nIn the world that lies at our feet, and the strife\nThat is waged in the hearts of the sons of men,\nAnd the days that are darkened, and all the life\nThat is spent in the quest that is vain, and then\nLet us give him the gift of the gods, and the power\nTo win what he will, and to stand alone\nIn the midst of the storm, and the fiery shower\nThat falls on his head from the skies unknown.\"\n\nThen spake Athena again, and her eyes\nWere bright as the stars that are set in the sky,\nAnd her voice was clear as the wind that flies\nThrough the leaves of the trees when the storm is nigh:\n\"Let him go to the land where the sun doth sleep\nIn the bed of the ocean, and there let him find\nThe tree that is hid in the darkness deep,\nAnd the fruit that is golden, and there let him bind\nThe branches, and break the stem, and bear\nThe treasure away to the halls of the sun,\nAnd the gods shall be with him, and he shall share\nThe glory of those who have fought and won.\"\n\nSo spake the goddess, and all the gods\nDid agree to the task, and they called to them"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_55703", "question": "A right triangle has one leg of length 6 cm and another leg of length 8 cm. What is the length of its hypotenuse, according to the Pythagorean theorem?", "answer": "The Pythagorean theorem states that in a right triangle, the square of the length of the hypotenuse (c) is equal to the sum of the squares of the lengths of the other two sides (a and b). Mathematically, this can be written as:\n\nc^2 = a^2 + b^2\n\nIn this case, the length of one leg (a) is 6 cm, and the length of the other leg (b) is 8 cm. Plugging these values into the equation, we get:\n\nc^2 = 6^2 + 8^2\nc^2 = 36 + 64\nc^2 = 100\n\nNow, to find the length of the hypotenuse (c), we take the square root of both sides of the equation:\n\nc = √100\nc = 10\n\nSo, the length of the hypotenuse is 10 cm."}
