{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_19388", "question": "Design a SQL query that retrieves data from a hypothetical Employee database. The database consists of two tables - Employees (with fields: EmpID, Name, JobTitle, ManagerID) and Salaries (with fields: EmpID, Salary). The task is to retrieve the names of employees who earn more than their managers.", "answer": "To solve this task, we will need to join the two tables on EmpID and then compare the salaries of employees with their managers. Here is a possible SQL query:\n\n```sql\nSELECT E1.Name \nFROM Employees E1\nJOIN Salaries S1 ON E1.EmpID = S1.EmpID\nJOIN Employees E2 ON E1.ManagerID = E2.EmpID\nJOIN Salaries S2 ON E2.EmpID = S2.EmpID\nWHERE S1.Salary > S2.Salary;\n```\n\nIn this query:\n- E1 and S1 are aliases for the Employees and Salaries tables for the employee.\n- E2 and S2 are aliases for the Employees and Salaries tables for the manager.\n- The first JOIN clause connects the Employees and Salaries tables for the employee based on the EmpID.\n- The second JOIN clause connects the Employees table for the employee and manager based on the ManagerID.\n- The third JOIN clause connects the Employees and Salaries tables for the manager based on the EmpID.\n- The WHERE clause filters out the records where the employee's salary is greater than the manager's salary."}
