{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_98152", "question": "Consider the metric on $\\mathbb{R}^3$ given by $g = dx^2 + dy^2 + 2(dz - xdy)^2$. Calculate the Killing vector fields of $g$ and determine whether they form a Lie algebra.", "answer": "To find the Killing vector fields of the given metric, we need to solve the Killing equation:\n\n$\\nabla_\\mu X_\\nu + \\nabla_\\nu X_\\mu = 0$\n\nwhere $X_\\mu$ are the components of the Killing vector field, and $\\nabla_\\mu$ is the covariant derivative associated with the metric $g$. In our case, the metric components are:\n\n$g_{11} = 1, g_{22} = 1, g_{33} = 2, g_{12} = 0, g_{13} = -2x, g_{23} = 0$\n\nThe inverse metric components are:\n\n$g^{11} = 1, g^{22} = 1, g^{33} = \\frac{1}{2}, g^{12} = 0, g^{13} = x, g^{23} = 0$\n\nNow we compute the Christoffel symbols:\n\n$\\Gamma^\\alpha_{\\mu\\nu} = \\frac{1}{2} g^{\\alpha\\sigma} (\\partial_\\mu g_{\\nu\\sigma} + \\partial_\\nu g_{\\mu\\sigma} - \\partial_\\sigma g_{\\mu\\nu})$\n\nAfter computing the Christoffel symbols, we get:\n\n$\\Gamma^1_{13} = -1, \\Gamma^3_{11} = 1, \\Gamma^3_{13} = -x$\n\nAll other Christoffel symbols are zero. Now we can write down the Killing equations:\n\n1. $\\partial_1 X_1 + \\Gamma^1_{13} X_3 = 0$\n2. $\\partial_2 X_2 = 0$\n3. $\\partial_3 X_3 + \\Gamma^3_{11} X_1 + \\Gamma^3_{13} X_3 = 0$\n4. $\\partial_1 X_2 + \\partial_2 X_1 = 0$\n5. $\\partial_1 X_3 + \\partial_3 X_1 - X_3 = 0$\n6. $\\partial_2 X_3 + \\partial_3 X_2 = 0$\n\nSolving these equations, we find the following Killing vector fields:\n\n$X_1 = \\partial_x$\n$X_2 = \\partial_y$\n$X_3 = z\\partial_x + \\partial_z$\n\nNow we need to check if these Killing vector fields form a Lie algebra. To do this, we need to compute the Lie bracket of any two Killing vector fields and see if it is still a Killing vector field:\n\n$[X_i, X_j] = X_i X_j - X_j X_i$\n\nComputing the Lie brackets, we get:\n\n$[X_1, X_2] = 0$\n$[X_1, X_3] = X_1$\n$[X_2, X_3] = 0$\n\nSince the Lie brackets of the Killing vector fields are still Killing vector fields, they form a Lie algebra."}
