{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_901789", "question": "Q: Jack bought 55 apples. He wants to give 10 to his father and then equally share the remaining apples between him and his 4 friends. How many apples will each of them get?\nA: The number of apples remaining after Jack gave his father 10 is 55 - 10 = 45. The share each one of his friends including him will get is 45 / 5 = 9. The answer is 9.\nQuestion: Liz bought a recipe book that cost $6, a baking dish that cost twice as much, five ingredients that cost $3 each, and an apron that cost a dollar more than the recipe book. Collectively, how much in dollars did Liz spend?\nAnswer: The baking dish cost 6 * 2 = 12. The ingredients cost 5 * 3 = 15. The apron cost 6 + 1 = 7. Collectively, Liz spend 6 + 12 + 15 + 7 = 40. The answer is 40.\n[Question]Mr. Salazar had seven dozen oranges. He reserved 1/4 of it for his friend and was able to sell 3/7 of the remaining yesterday. Today, he saw four rotten oranges. How many oranges are left to be sold today?\n[Answer]Mr. Salazar had 7 x 12 = 84 oranges. He reserved 84 x 1 / 4 = 21 oranges for his friend. Ha had 84 - 21 = 63 oranges to be sold yesterday. But only 63 x 3 / 7 = 27 oranges were sold yesterday. So, he had 63 - 27 = 36 oranges left. Since four oranges are rotten, then only 36 - 4 = 32 oranges are left to be sold today. The answer is 32.\nQ: Inez has $150. She spends one-half on hockey skates and a certain amount on hockey pads. If Inez has $25 remaining, how much did the hockey pads cost, together, in dollars?\nA: She spent 150 / 2 = $75 on hockey skates. Let X be the amount Inez spent on hockey pads. 150 - 75 - X = 25. 75 - X = 25. X = 50. The hockey pads cost $50. The answer is 50.\nQuestion: There are 12 carpets in house 1, 20 carpets in house 2, and 10 carpets in house 3. If house 4 has twice as many carpets as house 3, how many carpets do all 4 houses have in total?\nAnswer: House 4 has 2 * 10 house 3 carpets = 20 carpets. The total number of carpets across all houses is 12 + 20 + 10 + 20 = 62. The answer is 62.\nQ: Jeanine bought 18 pencils and Clare bought half as many pencils. If Jeanine gave one third of his pencils to Abby, how many more pencils than Clare does Jeanine have now?\nA:", "answer": "Clare bought half as many pencils as Jeanine, so Clare bought 18 / 2 = 9 pencils. Jeanine gave one third of his pencils to Abby, which is 18 x 1 / 3 = 6 pencils. After giving pencils to Abby, Jeanine now has 18 - 6 = 12 pencils. Jeanine has 12 - 9 = 3 more pencils than Clare. The answer is 3."}
