{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_766606", "question": "Question: Read the following context and choose the correct option to answer the question. Context: \"They've got cameras everywhere, man. Not just in supermarkets and departments stores, they're also on your cell phones and your computers at home. And they never turn off. You think they do, but they don't. \"They're always on, always watching you, sending them a continuous feed of your every move over satellite broadband connection. \"They watch you fuck, they watch you shit, they watch when you pick your nose at the stop light or when you chew out the clerk at 7-11 over nothing or when you walk past the lady collecting for the women's shelter and you don't put anything in her jar. \"They're even watching us right now,\" the hobo added and extended a grimy, gnarled digit to the small black orbs mounted at either end of the train car. There were some days when I loved taking public transportation, and other days when I didn't. On a good day, I liked to sit back and watch the show, study the rest of the passengers, read into their little ticks and mannerisms and body language, and try to guess at their back stories, giving them names and identities in my head. It was fun in a voyeuristic kind of way. And luckily, today was a good day. I watched the old Vietnamese woman with the cluster of plastic shopping bags gripped tightly in her hand like a cloud of tiny white bubbles. My eyes traced the deep lines grooving her face, and I wondered about the life that led her to this place. I watched the lonely businessman staring longingly across the aisle at the beautiful Mexican girl in the tight jeans standing with her back to him. He fidgeted with the gold band on his finger, and I couldn't tell if he was using it to remind himself of his commitment or if he was debating whether he should slyly slip it off and talk to her. Question: The author's ride on public transportation probably lasted: Options:  A. two days  B. an hour or less  C. one day  D. not enough information\nAnswer:", "answer": "D. not enough information"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_510648", "question": "Article: Do your parents ever say \"do it like a lady\" or \"be a gentleman\" to you? But in the eyes of today's students, what should a lady or a gentleman be like? Let's take a look. What is a gentleman? _ ?  _ : A gentleman doesn't always get angry . He wants others to be well and happy. He's always ready to help others. There is a boy in my class I think he is a gentleman. If I don't do well in the English exam, he will say \"You will do better next time\". That makes me feel happy.  _ : A gentleman always says, \"Ladies first\". When students clean the classroom, he always does heavy work. He lets girls go into rooms first. There are no gentlemen in my class. When there is something to eat, the boys in my class always get them before girls! What is a lady? Boys tell us what they think a lady is:  _ : A lady is kind and quiet  ,but she's not shy   and she can talk about her ideas in front of others. To me, Dong Jie, a film star, is a lady. She is pretty and kind. She does a lot for others.  _ : A lady is not just beautiful but clever. She never says bad words. She is quiet and kind to others. I don't think there is a lady in my class. Most of the girls are _ , I think. Question: Who find a lady/gentleman at school? Yes or no, is the answer \"Huang Xiaoyu\"?", "answer": "Title: What Makes a Lady or a Gentleman in the Eyes of Today's Students?\n\nDo your parents ever say \"do it like a lady\" or \"be a gentleman\" to you? But in the eyes of today's students, what should a lady or a gentleman be like? Let's take a look.\n\nWhat is a gentleman? \n\nStudent 1: A gentleman doesn't always get angry. He wants others to be well and happy. He's always ready to help others. There is a boy in my class I think he is a gentleman. If I don't do well in the English exam, he will say \"You will do better next time\". That makes me feel happy.\n\nStudent 2: A gentleman always says, \"Ladies first\". When students clean the classroom, he always does heavy work. He lets girls go into rooms first. There are no gentlemen in my class. When there is something to eat, the boys in my class always get them before girls!\n\nWhat is a lady? Boys tell us what they think a lady is:\n\nStudent 3: A lady is kind and quiet, but she's not shy and she can talk about her ideas in front of others. To me, Dong Jie, a film star, is a lady. She is pretty and kind. She does a lot for others.\n\nStudent 4: A lady is not just beautiful but clever. She never says bad words. She is quiet and kind to others. I don't think there is a lady in my class. Most of the girls are different, I think.\n\nQuestion: Who finds a lady/gentleman at school?\n\nThe answer, based on the article, is yes, Student 1 does find a gentleman at school. However, the answer \"Huang Xiaoyu\" is not mentioned or relevant to the question."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_108153", "question": "What are the specific anatomical and behavioral characteristics that differentiate Homo erectus from earlier hominins, and how did these adaptations contribute to their success as a species?", "answer": "Homo erectus, an extinct species of hominins, exhibited several anatomical and behavioral characteristics that set them apart from their earlier predecessors. These adaptations played a crucial role in their success as a species, enabling them to survive and thrive in various environments.\n\nAnatomical Characteristics:\n\n1. Increased brain size: Homo erectus had a larger brain size compared to earlier hominins, with an average cranial capacity of about 900 cubic centimeters. This increase in brain size likely contributed to their advanced cognitive abilities, problem-solving skills, and social behaviors.\n\n2. Smaller teeth and jaws: Homo erectus had smaller teeth and jaws compared to earlier hominins, suggesting a shift in their diet. This change in dentition may have been due to the consumption of softer, cooked foods, which required less chewing and grinding.\n\n3. More human-like body proportions: Homo erectus had a more modern body structure, with longer legs and shorter arms compared to earlier hominins. These proportions allowed for more efficient bipedal locomotion, enabling them to cover greater distances and adapt to various environments.\n\n4. Reduced sexual dimorphism: Homo erectus exhibited less difference in body size between males and females compared to earlier hominins. This reduction in sexual dimorphism may have led to more cooperative social behaviors and a more equitable division of labor within the group.\n\nBehavioral Characteristics:\n\n1. Use of fire: Homo erectus is believed to be the first hominin species to use fire, which provided numerous benefits such as warmth, protection from predators, and the ability to cook food. Cooking food made it easier to digest and allowed for the consumption of a wider range of food sources.\n\n2. Advanced tool-making: Homo erectus developed and used more sophisticated stone tools, known as Acheulean tools, which were more efficient for cutting, chopping, and processing food. This technological advancement allowed them to exploit their environment more effectively and access a wider range of resources.\n\n3. Hunting and gathering: Homo erectus likely had a more diverse diet, incorporating both plant and animal resources. They were capable hunters, using their advanced tools and social cooperation to bring down large game.\n\n4. Social behaviors: Homo erectus exhibited more complex social behaviors, such as group living, cooperation, and division of labor. These behaviors likely contributed to their success as a species by allowing them to share resources, protect each other, and raise offspring more effectively.\n\n5. Dispersal and migration: Homo erectus was the first hominin species to disperse out of Africa and into Eurasia, which allowed them to adapt to various environments and exploit new resources. This migration and dispersal contributed to their success as a species and their ability to survive in diverse habitats.\n\nIn summary, the anatomical and behavioral characteristics that differentiated Homo erectus from earlier hominins contributed to their success as a species by enabling them to adapt to various environments, exploit a wider range of resources, and develop more complex social behaviors. These adaptations ultimately allowed Homo erectus to thrive and persist for a longer period than their predecessors."}
