mber of counters Kevin has, Reina has 3 * 40 = 120 counters. Reina also has four times the number of marbles that Kevin has, meaning he has 4 * 50 = 200 marbles. In total, Reina has 120 counters + 200 marbles = 320 items.\n[Q & A]", "answer": "The question is Kevin has 40 counters and 50 marbles. Reina has three times as many counters as Kevin and four times as many marbles. How many items does Reina have in total?\nThe answer is 320"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_370469", "question": "I'm using the golang's `testing` package and `go test` for writing unit tests. However, I can only see the coverage report in the CLI output, and I'm unable to find any option in `go test` that provides a summary report for the entire test suite. I've searched online and couldn't find any suitable native options or third-party tools/libraries for this purpose. The only library I found, which is not very convenient, is `go-junit-report` (https://github.com/jstemmer/go-junit-report), which requires further processing to get the summary. Can someone please suggest a tool or library that I can use with `go test` and the `testing` package to generate a summary report of my test suite when running via the CLI? Thanks.", "answer": "You can use `gotestsum` (https://github.com/gotestyourself/gotestsum) for generating test reports with `go test` and the `testing` package. It is a `go test` runner that provides output optimized for humans, JUnit XML for CI integration, and a summary of the test results.\n\nTo use `gotestsum`, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Install `gotestsum` by running the following command:\n```\ngo get gotest.tools/gotestsum\n```\n\n2. Once installed, you can run your tests using `gotestsum` instead of `go test`. For example, if you previously ran:\n```\ngo test ./...\n```\nYou can now run:\n```\ngotestsum ./...\n```\n\n3. After running the tests, `gotestsum` will provide a summary report with the following information:\n- Total number of tests in the test suite.\n- Number of tests that passed.\n- Number of tests that failed.\n\nAdditionally, `gotestsum` generates JUnit XML output, which can be used for CI integration if needed.\n\nOverall, `gotestsum` is a convenient tool for generating test reports when working with `go test` and the `testing` package."}
