{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_371367", "question": "Why is the following assembly code considered an anti-debugging tool?\n\n```assembly\nl1:\ncall l3\nl2:\n;some code\nl3:\nmov al, 0c3h\nmov edi, offset l3\nor ecx, -1\nrep stosb\n```\n\nI am familiar with the fact that `C3h` represents `RETN` and that `stobs` writes the value in `al` as the opcode according to the offset in `edi`, and it is repeated `ecx` times due to the `rep` instruction.\n\nI also understand that `stobs` and `stosw` will run if they were pre-fetched on Intel architecture in their original format.\n\nIf we run the program in debugged mode, the pre-fetch is irrelevant and the `l2` label will be executed (because it is single-step). However, if there is no debugger, will it keep alternating between `l1` and `l3`?", "answer": "When the program is debugged using single-step mode, the prefetch queue is flushed at each step when an interrupt occurs. However, when the program is executed normally, this flushing will not happen for `rep stosb`. In older processors, the prefetch queue was not flushed even when there was a memory write to the cached area, in order to support self-modifying code that was changed except for `rep movs` and `rep stosb`. This behavior was eventually fixed in i7 processors.\n\nThat's why, if there is a debugger (single-step), the code will execute correctly and when `rep stosb` is replaced by `ret`, `l2` will be executed. However, when there is no debugger, `rep stosb` will continue executing. Since `ecx` is set to the maximum value possible, it will eventually write to a location where it is not supposed to write, causing an exception to occur.\n\nThis anti-debugging technique is described in detail in [this paper](http://pferrie.tripod.com/papers/unpackers.pdf)."}
