{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_68818", "question": "Consider the following first-order chemical reaction:\nA → B with a rate constant k = 0.05 s^-1, where A is the initial concentration of reactant.\n\nIf the initial concentration of A is 0.5 M, what is the concentration of A after 20 seconds?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we can use the first-order integrated rate law equation:\n\n[A] = [A]₀ * e^(-kt)\n\nwhere [A] is the concentration of A at time t, [A]₀ is the initial concentration of A, k is the rate constant, and t is the time.\n\nGiven the initial concentration [A]₀ = 0.5 M, the rate constant k = 0.05 s^-1, and the time t = 20 seconds, we can plug these values into the equation:\n\n[A] = (0.5 M) * e^(-0.05 s^-1 * 20 s)\n\n[A] = (0.5 M) * e^(-1)\n\n[A] = (0.5 M) * 0.36787944117144233\n\n[A] ≈ 0.184 M\n\nSo, the concentration of A after 20 seconds is approximately 0.184 M."}
