{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_220849", "question": "Is there a pre-defined #define compiler macro in CUDA (nvcc) that I can utilize, similar to _WIN32 for Windows and so on? I want to use this for header code that will be shared between nvcc and VC++ compilers. I am aware I can create my own and pass it as an argument to the nvcc compiler (-D), but I am looking for an existing one.", "answer": "Yes, CUDA does provide pre-defined macros that you can use. One of these macros is `__CUDACC__`. It is defined when the NVCC CUDA compiler is running.\n\nHere's an example of how you can use it:\n\n```cpp\n#ifdef __CUDACC__\n  //This code will be compiled by NVCC\n#else\n  //This code will be compiled by VC++\n#endif\n```\n\nThis `__CUDACC__` macro allows you to differentiate between CUDA C++ and regular C++, which can be particularly useful for header code compatibility between NVCC and VC++ compilers."}
