{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_214856", "question": "I am trying to use the BatchNormalization function in Keras in my model. I am unsure about where to call this function. Should it be called only once at the beginning? Here's my current code:\n\n```python\nmodel = Sequential()\nkeras.layers.normalization.BatchNormalization(epsilon=1e-06, mode=0, momentum=0.9, weights=None)\nmodel.add(Dense(64, input_dim=14, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('tanh'))\nmodel.add(Dropout(0.5))\nmodel.add(Dense(64, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('tanh'))\nmodel.add(Dropout(0.5))\nmodel.add(Dense(2, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('softmax'))\n\nsgd = SGD(lr=0.1, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True)\nmodel.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd)\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train, nb_epoch=20, batch_size=16, show_accuracy=True, validation_split=0.2, verbose = 2)\n```\n\nWhen I run this code with the second line including the BatchNormalization, and if I run the code without the second line, I get similar outputs. Am I calling the function in the right place or does it not make much of a difference?", "answer": "The BatchNormalization function in Keras should be called and added as a layer in your neural network model. Each time you add it, it normalizes the activations of the previous layer at each batch, i.e., applies a transformation that maintains the mean activation close to 0 and the activation standard deviation close to 1.\n\nFrom your code, it seems that you are not adding the BatchNormalization layer to the model. You need to use the `add` method of the model to do this as follows:\n\n```python\nmodel = Sequential()\nmodel.add(keras.layers.normalization.BatchNormalization(epsilon=1e-06, mode=0, momentum=0.9, weights=None))\nmodel.add(Dense(64, input_dim=14, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('tanh'))\nmodel.add(Dropout(0.5))\nmodel.add(Dense(64, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('tanh'))\nmodel.add(Dropout(0.5))\nmodel.add(Dense(2, init='uniform'))\nmodel.add(Activation('softmax'))\n\nsgd = SGD(lr=0.1, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True)\nmodel.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd)\nmodel.fit(X_train, y_train, nb_epoch=20, batch_size=16, show_accuracy=True, validation_split=0.2, verbose = 2)\n```\n\nThe BatchNormalization layer can be used multiple times in a model if required. It's not always necessary to use it at the start of your model. Usually, it is added after fully connected layers (like Dense), and before non-linearity layers (like Activation)."}
