{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_228055", "question": "How can I show the progress of a Python multiprocessing pool imap_unordered call? I'm currently running a script with a multiprocessing Pool task using an imap_unordered() call. My num_tasks is about 250,000, which causes the join() to lock the main thread for around 10 seconds. I want to be able to output to the command line incrementally to show that the main process isn't locked. Is there a method for the result object or the pool that shows the number of tasks remaining? I tried using a multiprocessing.Value object as a counter, however, the counter only increases to about 85% of the total value before ceasing to increment. Here is my code:\n\n```python\np = multiprocessing.Pool()\nrs = p.imap_unordered(do_work, xrange(num_tasks))\np.close() \np.join() \n```\n\nI would like to modify it to something like this:\n\n```python\np = multiprocessing.Pool()\nrs = p.imap_unordered(do_work, xrange(num_tasks))\np.close() \nwhile (True):\n  remaining = rs.tasks_remaining() \n  if (remaining == 0): break \n  print(\"Waiting for\", remaining, \"tasks to complete...\")\n  time.sleep(2)\n```", "answer": "Unfortunately, there isn't a built-in way to know the number of remaining tasks in imap_unordered. However, you can make use of a shared counter which can be incremented in each worker process after they complete their task and then use it to calculate the number of remaining tasks.\n\nHere is a sample code showing how you can do this:\n\n```python\nfrom multiprocessing import Pool, Value, Lock\nimport time\n\ncounter = None\n\ndef init(args):\n    ''' store the counter for later use '''\n    global counter\n    counter = args\n\ndef do_work(args):\n    ''' increment the global counter, sleep to simulate work '''\n    global counter\n    time.sleep(0.5)  # simulate work\n    with counter.get_lock():\n        counter.value += 1\n    return args\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    total_tasks = 10\n    # create a shared counter\n    counter = Value('i', 0)\n    # create a lock for the counter\n    counter_lock = Lock()\n\n    pool = Pool(initializer = init, initargs = (counter, ))\n    result = pool.map_async(do_work, range(total_tasks))\n\n    while not result.ready():\n        remaining = total_tasks - counter.value\n        print(f\"Waiting for {remaining} tasks to complete...\")\n        time.sleep(0.5)\n\n    pool.close()\n    pool.join()\n```\n\nIn the above code, we use a shared value and a lock to create a shared counter. The initializer function is used to store the counter in a global variable so it can be accessed from within the worker process. The lock is used to ensure that only one process increments the counter at a time, preventing race conditions. The remaining tasks are calculated by subtracting the current value of the counter from the total number of tasks."}
