mative (end-of-unit) assessments to gauge student understanding and progress towards the lesson goal. Examples of assessments include quizzes, group discussions, exit tickets, or project presentations.\n6. Adapt the lesson plan to accommodate diverse learners:\n\t* The tool should provide options to modify or add activities, resources, or supports to meet the needs of diverse learners (e.g., English language learners, students with special needs, or advanced learners).\n7. Generate a detailed lesson plan:\n\t* Once the user has reviewed and finalized the chosen strategies, activities, and assessments, the tool should generate a comprehensive lesson plan, including an overview, learning objectives, materials list, step-by-step instructions, and any necessary resources or handouts.\n8. Monitor and adjust:\n\t* The tool should have a built-in feedback mechanism for teachers to reflect on the effectiveness of the lesson and make any necessary adjustments. This feature can help the tool learn from user feedback and continuously improve its recommendations.\n\nBy following these steps, your lesson planning tool should be able to create tailored lesson plans that meet the needs of teachers and their students, even with limited input from the user."}
