gest Christian denomination in the United States. It is the largest denomination in the Latter Day Saint movement founded by Joseph Smith during the period of religious revival known as the Second Great Awakening.  - Leonard James Arrington (July 2, 1917  February 11, 1999) was an American author, academic and the founder of the Mormon History Association. He is known as the \"Dean of Mormon History\" and \"the Father of Mormon History\" because of his many influential contributions to the field.  - Brigham Young (June 1, 1801August 29, 1877) was an American leader in the Latter Day Saint movement and a settler of the Western United States. He was the second President of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church) from 1847 until his death in 1877. He founded Salt Lake City and he served as the first governor of the Utah Territory. Young also led the foundings of the precursors to the University of Utah and Brigham Young University.  - The American Historical Association (AHA) is the oldest and largest society of historians and professors of history in the United States. Founded in 1884, the association promotes historical studies, the teaching of history, and the preservation of and access to historical materials. It publishes \"The American Historical Review\" five times a year, with scholarly articles and book reviews. The AHA is the major organization for historians working in the United States, while the Organization of American Historians is the major organization for historians who study and teach about the United States.  - Nunavut (from Inuktitut:  ) is the newest, largest, northernmost, and least populous territory of Canada. It was separated officially from the Northwest Territories on April 1, 1999, via the Nunavut Act and the Nunavut Land Claims Agreement Act, though the boundaries had been contemplatively drawn in 1993. The creation of Nunavut resulted in the first major change to Canada's political map since the incorporation of the province of Newfoundland and Labrador in 1949.  - The Northwest Territories (also known as NWT; French: \"les Territoires du Nord-Ouest\", \"TNO\"; Athabaskan languages: \"Denendeh\"; Inuinnaqtun: \"Nunatsiaq\"; Inuktitut: ) is a territory of Canada. At a land area of approximately and a 2011 population of 41,462, it is the second largest and most populous of the three territories in Northern Canada. Its estimated population as of 2016 is 44,291. Yellowknife became the territorial capital in 1967, following recommendations by the Carrothers Commission.  - The Mormon History Association (MHA) is an independent, non-profit organization dedicated to the study and understanding of all aspects of Mormon history to promote understanding, scholarly research, and publication in the field. MHA was founded in December 1965 at the American Historical Association (AHA) meeting in San Francisco under the leadership of Latter-day Saint and historian, Leonard J. Arrington. In 1972, MHA became an independent organization with its own annual conferences and publications. \"The Journal of Mormon History\", the official biennial publication of the association, began publication in 1974. MHA also publishes the quarterly \"Mormon History Newsletter\" and is an affiliate of both AHA and the Western History Association.  - Saskatchewan (or ) is a prairie and boreal province in west-central Canada, the only province without natural borders. It has an area of , nearly 10 percent of which is fresh water, composed mostly of rivers, reservoirs, and the province's 100,000 lakes.    What object entity has the relation of 'occupation' with the subject 'richard e. bennett'?   Choices: - academic  - accounting  - author  - book  - canada  - forestry  - founder  - historian  - leader  - major  - official  - president  - religious  - research  - saint  - settler  - teach\nAnswer:", "answer": "Richard Edmond Bennett has the relation of 'occupation' with the subject 'richard e. bennett' in the following capacities:\n\n1. Academic: Bennett is a professor of Church History and Doctrine at Brigham Young University (BYU). He has a PhD in United States intellectual history from Wayne State University and has contributed significantly to the field of Mormon history.\n\n2. Historian: Bennett's work as a historian includes his service as president of the Mormon History Association. In his academic role, he has focused on the history of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church). His publications include \"We'll Find the Place: The Mormon Exodus, 1846-1848\" and \"Mormons at the Missouri: 1846-1852.\" He has also held editorial positions in relevant historical journals.\n\n3. Author: Bennett has authored several books, as mentioned above, and contributed to publications such as BYU Studies and the Journal of Book of Mormon Studies.\n\n4. Research: As a historian and professor, Bennett's work involves conducting research in the field of Church History and Doctrine. His research has added significant insight into the history of the LDS Church and the Mormon exodus.\n\nIn summary, Richard E. Bennett's occupations include being an academic, historian, author, and researcher, all primarily focused on the history of the LDS Church and the wider field of Mormon history."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_219815", "question": "Why does Python have both a format function and a format method? The format function in builtins seems to act like a subset of the str.format method, used specifically for the case of formatting a single object. For example, using format(13, 'x') is apparently preferred over '{0:x}'.format(13). In my opinion, it does look nicer, but wouldn't it be simpler to just use str.format in every case? Both of these were introduced in Python 2.6, so there must be a good reason for having both at once, what is it?", "answer": "Python provides both a format function and str.format method to offer flexibility and convenience for different scenarios. \n\nThe format function is considered simpler and more straightforward for formatting single objects. It's a built-in function that can convert an object to a string based on a given format specification. \n\nHere's an example:\n\n```python\nnumber = 13\nformatted_number = format(number, 'x')\nprint(formatted_number)  # prints 'd'\n```\n\nOn the other hand, the str.format method is more powerful and versatile as it can handle multiple substitutions and value formatting. It's a method of the str (string) class and needs a string object to work on.\n\nHere's an example:\n\n```python\nnumber = 13\nformatted_number = '{:x}'.format(number)\nprint(formatted_number)  # prints 'd'\n```\n\nIn this example, ':x' is a format specification for hexadecimal conversion. The str.format method replaces '{}' with the formatted version of the specified value.\n\nWhile the format function might be more convenient for simple formatting tasks, the str.format method is the way to go for more complex string formatting requirements. The choice between the two depends on the specific use case. \n\nNote that starting from Python 3.6, you can also use f-strings, which is another, often more readable way to format strings:\n\n```python\nnumber = 13\nformatted_number = f'{number:x}'\nprint(formatted_number)  # prints 'd'\n```\n\nIn this example, 'number:x' inside the curly braces is an expression that gets evaluated and its result is then formatted as a hexadecimal number."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_457428", "question": "Harry needs to buy 5 spellbooks that each cost 5 gold, three potion kits that each cost 20 silver, and one owl that costs 28 gold. There are 9 silver to a gold. How much will Harry pay total, in silvers?", "answer": "The cost of 5 spellbooks is 5 gold x 5 = 25 gold.\nThe cost of 3 potion kits is 3 x 20 silver = 60 silver.\nThe cost of the owl is 28 gold x 9 silver/gold = 252 silver.\nIn total, Harry will pay 25 gold + 60 silver + 252 silver = 25 gold + 312 silver.\nTo convert gold to silver, we multiply by 9, so 25 gold is equal to 25 x 9 = 225 silver.\nTherefore, Harry will pay a total of 225 silver + 312 silver = 537 silver.\n#### 537\nThe answer is: 537"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_945121", "question": "Find the mean of all integers in a given array, rounded down to the nearest integer.\nArray: [1, 2, 3].", "answer": "To find the mean of all integers in the given array rounded down to the nearest integer, we first need to calculate the sum of all the integers in the array, then divide that by the total number of elements in the array.\n\nSumming up all the integers in the array [1, 2, 3] we get 1 + 2 + 3 = 6. \n\nSince the given array has 3 elements, we need to divide the summed value by 3: 6 / 3 = 2. \n\nSo, the mean of all integers in the array [1, 2, 3] rounded down to the nearest integer is 2."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_5348", "question": "In a village, there are 50 houses. Each house has either a red or blue door. If the first house has a red door and every third house after that also has a red door, how many houses have blue doors?", "answer": "There are 16 houses with red doors and 34 houses with blue doors.\n\nHere's the reasoning behind this:\n\n1. We know that the first house has a red door.\n2. Then we are told that every third house after the first one also has a red door.\n3. To find out how many houses have red doors, we can use the following formula: (Total number of houses - 1) / 3 + 1\n4. Plugging in the values: (50 - 1) / 3 + 1 = 49 / 3 + 1 ≈ 16.33 + 1\n5. Since the number of houses must be a whole number, we round down to 16 houses with red doors.\n6. Now, to find out how many houses have blue doors, we subtract the number of houses with red doors from the total number of houses: 50 - 16 = 34\n\nTherefore, there are 34 houses with blue doors in the village."}
