{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_95437", "question": "Here's a numerical problem for a math student to solve on the subtopic Finding the Fourier series of a function with a jump discontinuity:\n\nFind the Fourier series of the function f(x) given by:\n\nf(x) = \n  {\\begin{cases} \n      1, & 0 \\leq x < \\pi \\\\\n     -1, & \\pi \\leq x < 2\\pi\n  \\end{cases}}\n\nover the interval 0 ≤ x ≤ 2π.", "answer": "To find the Fourier series of the given function f(x), we need to compute the Fourier coefficients a_0, a_n, and b_n.\n\nThe general form of a Fourier series is:\n\nf(x) = a_0 + Σ [a_n * cos(nx) + b_n * sin(nx)]\n\nwhere the sum is from n=1 to infinity.\n\nFirst, let's find a_0:\n\na_0 = (1/(2π)) * ∫[f(x) * 1] dx from 0 to 2π\n\nSince f(x) is piecewise, we need to split the integral into two parts:\n\na_0 = (1/(2π)) * [∫[1 * 1] dx from 0 to π + ∫[-1 * 1] dx from π to 2π]\n\na_0 = (1/(2π)) * [x | from 0 to π - x | from π to 2π]\n\na_0 = (1/(2π)) * [π - 0 - (2π - π)]\n\na_0 = (1/(2π)) * [π - π] = 0\n\nNow, let's find a_n:\n\na_n = (1/π) * ∫[f(x) * cos(nx)] dx from 0 to 2π\n\nAgain, we need to split the integral into two parts:\n\na_n = (1/π) * [∫[1 * cos(nx)] dx from 0 to π + ∫[-1 * cos(nx)] dx from π to 2π]\n\na_n = (1/π) * [sin(nx)/n | from 0 to π - (-sin(nx)/n) | from π to 2π]\n\na_n = (1/π) * [(sin(nπ)/n - sin(0)) - (-sin(2nπ)/n + sin(nπ)/n)]\n\nSince sin(nπ) = 0 for all integer values of n, a_n = 0.\n\nFinally, let's find b_n:\n\nb_n = (1/π) * ∫[f(x) * sin(nx)] dx from 0 to 2π\n\nSplitting the integral into two parts:\n\nb_n = (1/π) * [∫[1 * sin(nx)] dx from 0 to π + ∫[-1 * sin(nx)] dx from π to 2π]\n\nb_n = (1/π) * [-cos(nx)/n | from 0 to π + cos(nx)/n | from π to 2π]\n\nb_n = (1/π) * [(-cos(nπ)/n + cos(0)) + (cos(2nπ)/n - cos(nπ)/n)]\n\nFor even values of n, cos(nπ) = 1 and cos(2nπ) = 1, so b_n = 0.\nFor odd values of n, cos(nπ) = -1 and cos(2nπ) = 1, so b_n = (2/πn) * 2 = 4/πn.\n\nSo, the Fourier series of the given function f(x) is:\n\nf(x) = Σ [(4/πn) * sin(nx)] for odd values of n\n\nwhere the sum is from n=1 to infinity."}
