{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_960417", "question": "sudo systemctl start nsql-master\n\nThis command will start the master node of the NSQL (NoSQL) database system, which uses the master-slave replication model to synchronize data between nodes. The master node serves as the primary node and receives all write operations, which are then replicated to the slave nodes in the cluster. This ensures that all nodes have a consistent copy of the data, and provides fault tolerance and high availability.\n\nHow does NSQL ensure fault tolerance and high availability in its master-slave replication model?", "answer": "NSQL ensures fault tolerance and high availability in its master-slave replication model by replicating data from the master node to the slave nodes in real-time. In the event of a failure of the master node, one of the slave nodes can be promoted to become the new master node, ensuring that data is still available and accessible to clients. This process is automated and transparent to clients, ensuring that downtime is minimized and data consistency is maintained. Additionally, NSQL supports sharding, which further enhances fault tolerance and scalability by distributing data across multiple nodes."}
