{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_218794", "question": "Is there a Python library available for caching? I am looking for something with a simple dict-like interface where I can set keys and their expiration and then retrieve them back cached. I need functionality similar to what is described by this code: \n\n```python\ncache.get(myfunction, duration=300)\n```\nThis should return the item from the cache if it exists or call the function and store it if it doesn't or has expired. Can anyone suggest a library that can provide this functionality?", "answer": "Yes, there is a Python library called `cachetools` which provides exactly the functionality you're looking for. It's a powerful caching library featuring caches with a dict-like interface, and it supports various caching algorithms.\n\nTo install it, you can use pip:\n```python\npip install cachetools\n```\n\nHere's how you can use it: \n\n```python\nimport cachetools\n\n# create a cache with a capacity limit\ncache = cachetools.LRUCache(maxsize=10)\n\ndef expensive_function(arg1, arg2):\n    # ... expensive computations ...\n    return result\n\n# create a cached version of your function\ncached_function = cachetools.cached(cache)(expensive_function)\n\n# now you can call your function, and it will be cached\nresult = cached_function(arg1, arg2)\n```\nThe `cachetools.cached` decorator will check if the function has been called before with the same arguments. If so, it will return the result from cache. If not, it will call the function and store the result in cache. The cache object can be any cache from cachetools (in this case, an LRU cache is used), or a custom one that has a dict-like interface.\n\nFor setting expiration times, you can use `cachetools.TTLCache`:\n\n```python\ncache = cachetools.TTLCache(maxsize=100, ttl=300)  \n```\nIn the above code, `ttl` is the time-to-live in seconds. After this duration, the cache entries expire."}
