{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_598444", "question": "Question: If your trouser fly is unfastened what should you do? - do up - tie up - zip up - pick up - button up  The best answer is\nAnswer:", "answer": "The best answer is \"zip up\" or \"button up,\" depending on the type of fastening mechanism your trouser fly has. \n\nIf the fly of your trousers features a zipper, then the most appropriate course of action is to \"zip up\". To do this, you should follow these steps:\n\n1. Locate the zipper tab, which is typically found at the base of the fly opening.\n2. Hold the waistband of your trousers with one hand to ensure that both sides of the fly opening are properly aligned.\n3. With your other hand, grasp the zipper tab firmly.\n4. Slowly and carefully, pull the zipper tab upwards along the track, making sure not to snag any fabric.\n5. Once the zipper is fully zipped, double-check to ensure it is secure and there are no gaps or snags in the fabric.\n\nOn the other hand, if your trouser fly features buttons, the correct action to take is to \"button up\". In this case, you should follow these steps:\n\n1. Ensure both sides of the fly are properly aligned. The buttonholes should be directly across from the buttons.\n2. Start from the bottom button, taking it between your fingers and carefully pushing it through the corresponding buttonhole. Make sure not to force the button too hard, as this can cause the button or fabric to tear.\n3. Repeat this process for each button along the fly, working your way up. Be patient, as buttoning the fly might require more dexterity due to the close proximity of buttons and fabric layers.\n4. Once all buttons are secure, double-check that the fly is closed, and there are no gaps or twisted fabric.\n\nIn either case, it is advisable to excuse yourself to a private location, such as a restroom or a discreet corner, to fix your fly. This action maintains your privacy and helps avoid potentially embarrassing situations."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_286190", "question": "How can I create a GraphQL schema to handle movie information, allowing for adding, editing, and deleting movies along with their title, description, release date, and number of likes?", "answer": "You can use the Apollo Server package and the GraphQL `gql` function to create a schema for movie information with the desired functionalities. Here is an example code snippet:\n\n```javascript\nimport { gql } from 'apollo-server';\n\n// Movie type\nconst typeDefs = gql`\n  type Movie {\n    id: ID!\n    title: String!\n    description: String\n    releaseDate: String!\n    likes: Int\n  }\n\n  // Mutations\n  type Mutation {\n    addMovie(title: String!, releaseDate: String!, description: String): Movie\n    editMovie(id: ID!, title: String, description: String, releaseDate: String): Movie\n    deleteMovie(id: ID!): Movie\n  }\n\n  // Query\n  type Query {\n    movie(id: ID!): Movie\n    movies: [Movie]\n  }\n`;\n\nexport default typeDefs;\n```\n\nThis schema defines a `Movie` type with properties like `id`, `title`, `description`, `releaseDate`, and `likes`. The `Mutation` type includes three methods: `addMovie`, `editMovie`, and `deleteMovie`. These methods allow for adding, editing, and deleting movie information respectively. The `Query` type provides methods to fetch a single movie (`movie`) or a list of movies (`movies`).\n\nYou can customize this schema further to suit your specific needs, but this should give you a good starting point for handling movie information with GraphQL."}
