{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_97496", "question": "Let $g$ be the metric defined on the unit sphere $S^2$ given by $g_p(v,w) = \\|p \\times v \\cdot p \\times w\\|$, where $p$ is a fixed point in $S^2$ and $\\times$ denotes the cross product. Find the volume form of the metric $g$ on $S^2$.", "answer": "To find the volume form of the metric $g$, we first need to find an orthonormal basis for the tangent space $T_pS^2$ at each point $p \\in S^2$. Let $e_1 = p \\times e_z$ and $e_2 = p \\times e_1$, where $e_z$ is the unit vector in the $z$-direction. Note that $e_1$ and $e_2$ are orthogonal to $p$ and to each other, and have unit length.\n\nNow, let $v = a_1 e_1 + a_2 e_2$ and $w = b_1 e_1 + b_2 e_2$ be arbitrary tangent vectors at $p$. Then, we have:\n\n$g_p(v,w) = \\|p \\times v \\cdot p \\times w\\| = \\|(p \\times (a_1 e_1 + a_2 e_2)) \\cdot (p \\times (b_1 e_1 + b_2 e_2))\\|$\n\nUsing the properties of the cross product, we can expand this expression:\n\n$g_p(v,w) = \\|a_1 b_1 (p \\times e_1) \\cdot (p \\times e_1) + a_1 b_2 (p \\times e_1) \\cdot (p \\times e_2) + a_2 b_1 (p \\times e_2) \\cdot (p \\times e_1) + a_2 b_2 (p \\times e_2) \\cdot (p \\times e_2)\\|$\n\nSince $p \\times e_1$ and $p \\times e_2$ are orthogonal, their dot product is zero:\n\n$g_p(v,w) = \\|a_1 b_1 (p \\times e_1) \\cdot (p \\times e_1) + a_2 b_2 (p \\times e_2) \\cdot (p \\times e_2)\\|$\n\nNow, we can use the fact that the cross product of two orthogonal vectors has magnitude equal to the product of their magnitudes:\n\n$g_p(v,w) = \\|a_1 b_1 \\|p \\times e_1\\|^2 + a_2 b_2 \\|p \\times e_2\\|^2\\|$\n\nSince $e_1$ and $e_2$ are unit vectors, we have $\\|p \\times e_1\\| = \\|p \\times e_2\\| = 1$. Thus,\n\n$g_p(v,w) = \\|a_1 b_1 + a_2 b_2\\|$\n\nThis shows that the metric $g$ is the standard Euclidean metric on the tangent space $T_pS^2$. Therefore, the volume form of the metric $g$ is the same as the standard volume form on $S^2$, which is given by:\n\n$\\omega = \\sqrt{\\det(g_{ij})} \\, dA = dA$\n\nwhere $dA$ is the standard area element on $S^2$."}
