{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_373066", "question": "Is it possible to change the default :id parameter to :username in Ruby on Rails 3's new routing system? I would like to have routes like /users/:username instead of /users/:id. This would be really helpful for the project I'm currently working on. Can this parameter be changed, and if not, is there a specific reason why it cannot be changed?", "answer": "If I understand correctly, you want to replace the default :id parameter with :username in your URL. To achieve this, you can override the to_param method in your model. The to_param method allows you to specify a custom string representation for your model, which will be used in URLs.\n\nHere's an example of how you can override the to_param method in your User model to use :username instead of :id:\n\n```ruby\nclass User < ApplicationRecord\n  def to_param\n    username\n  end\nend\n```\n\nBy overriding the to_param method and returning the username attribute, any URLs generated for User objects will use the username instead of the default id. For example, /users/1 will become /users/johndoe.\n\nYou can find more information about this approach and how to implement it in the Railscasts episode [Model Name in URL](http://railscasts.com/episodes/63-model-name-in-url)."}
