{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_227069", "question": "I am developing an application in Flask and I have a task that calls out to a third party API which can take several minutes to complete. I want to run this task asynchronously, so that Flask can continue processing other requests while this task is running. Here's how my view currently looks:\n\n```python\n@app.route('/render/<id>', methods=['POST'])\ndef render_script(id=None):\n    ...\n    data = json.loads(request.data)\n    text_list = data.get('text_list')\n    final_file = audio_class.render_audio(data=text_list)\n    # do stuff\n    return Response(\n        mimetype='application/json',\n        status=200\n    )\n```\n\nI want the `final_file = audio_class.render_audio()` line to run and provide a callback to be executed when the method returns. I'm considering using Twisted, Klein, Threading, or Celery for this, but I'm not sure which one would be the best choice. Can you provide some guidance on how to best implement this?", "answer": "For this specific use case, I would recommend using Celery because it's designed for this type of task. Also, Celery works well with Flask. Here's an example of how you can modify your code to use Celery:\n\nFirst, you need to install Celery and set it up:\n\n```shell\npip install celery\n```\n\nThen, create a new Celery instance in your Flask application:\n\n```python\nfrom celery import Celery\n\ndef make_celery(app):\n    celery = Celery(\n        app.import_name,\n        backend=app.config['CELERY_RESULT_BACKEND'],\n        broker=app.config['CELERY_BROKER_URL']\n    )\n    celery.conf.update(app.config)\n    return celery\n```\n\nNext, define your asynchronous task. This will be a Celery task that will run in the background:\n\n```python\nfrom your_flask_app import make_celery\n\ncelery = make_celery(your_flask_app)\n\n@celery.task\ndef render_audio_task(text_list):\n    return audio_class.render_audio(data=text_list)\n```\n\nFinally, modify your view to call the asynchronous task:\n\n```python\n@app.route('/render/<id>', methods=['POST'])\ndef render_script(id=None):\n    ...\n    data = json.loads(request.data)\n    text_list = data.get('text_list')\n    final_file = render_audio_task.delay(text_list)\n    # do stuff\n    return Response(\n        mimetype='application/json',\n        status=200\n    )\n```\n\nIn this example, calling `render_audio_task.delay(text_list)` will start the asynchronous task and immediately return a `AsyncResult` object, which you can use to check the status of the task, get the result when it's ready, or provide a callback to be executed when the task is done."}
