{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_506680", "question": "Answer the following question: Pakistan tried to control the foreign exchange market and India didn't. By creating the foreign exchange control department, Pakistan tried to stop the devaluation of their currency. India chose to not interfere and let the exchange market regulate itself.  Given the paragraph above, please answer correctly the following question:   Which country was more regulated in regards to foreign currency exchange?  Hint: Often, foreign exchange controls can result in the creation of black markets to exchange the weaker currency for stronger currencies. This leads to a situation where the exchange rate for the foreign currency is much higher than the rate set by the government, and therefore creates a shadow currency exchange market. As such, it is unclear whether governments have the ability to enact effective exchange controls.[1]\nAnswer:", "answer": "Based on the information provided in the paragraph, Pakistan was more regulated in regards to foreign currency exchange because they created the foreign exchange control department to attempt control over the market and prevent devaluation of their currency. On the other hand, India chose not to interfere and let the exchange market regulate itself."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_230432", "question": "I am experiencing inconsistency between the `%time` and `%timeit` IPython magic commands. I used both to measure the execution time of a function that generates a large list of tuples. The function is defined as follows:\n\n```python\ndef get_list_of_tuples():\n    return [(i,) for i in range(10**6)]\n```\n\nWhen I use `%time`, it reports the execution time is approximately one second:\n\n```python\n%time res = get_list_of_tuples()\n```\n\nOutput: \n\n```\nCPU times: user 0.93 s, sys: 0.08 s, total: 1.01 s\nWall time: 0.98 s\n```\n\nHowever, when I use `%timeit`, it reports the execution time is around 0.1 second:\n\n```python\n%timeit res = get_list_of_tuples()\n```\n\nOutput: \n\n```\n1 loops, best of 3: 92.1 ms per loop\n```\n\nWhy is there such a significant difference in the execution time reported by these two commands? I am using IPython version 0.11 with Python 2.6.5.", "answer": "The discrepancy you're observing is due to the different ways `%time` and `%timeit` operate.\n\n`%time` executes the statement once and provides a simple report on the time taken. It includes system and user CPU time, as well as the total wall clock time.\n\n`%timeit`, on the other hand, is designed to provide more accurate time measurements for small code snippets. It achieves this by running the code snippet multiple times and taking the best result to eliminate the effects of other tasks running on your computer that may interfere with the timing. \n\nIn your case, `%timeit` is running the function `get_list_of_tuples` multiple times and returning the best time. This is why the time reported by `%timeit` is less than the time reported by `%time`.\n\nHere is an example of how `%time` and `%timeit` work:\n\n```python\ndef get_list_of_tuples():\n    return [(i,) for i in range(10**6)]\n\n%time res = get_list_of_tuples()\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nCPU times: user 0.93 s, sys: 0.08 s, total: 1.01 s\nWall time: 0.98 s\n```\n\n```python\n%timeit res = get_list_of_tuples()\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n1 loops, best of 3: 92.1 ms per loop\n```\n\nIn conclusion, `%timeit` is more suited for micro-benchmarks, while `%time` is for longer running code snippets. If you want a quick, slightly less accurate execution time, use `%time`. For a more accurate measurement, especially for small code snippets, use `%timeit`."}
