{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_452767", "question": "If James and 4 of his friends were able to plant a total of 200 flowers in 2 days, and each of them planted the same number of flowers, how many flowers did James plant in a single day?", "answer": "If James and 4 of his friends planted a total of 200 flowers in 2 days, then they planted 200/2 = 100 flowers in a single day.\nSince each of them planted the same number of flowers, we divide 100 flowers by the number of people, which is 1 + 4 = 5.\nTherefore, James planted 100/5 = 20 flowers in a single day.\n#### 20\nThe answer is: 20"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_258443", "question": "How can I index all the documents in an Apache Solr search core?", "answer": "To index all the documents in an Apache Solr search core, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. First, navigate to the directory where Apache Solr is installed. Let's assume the Solr Home directory is \"<Solr_Home>\".\n   Use the command:\n   ```\n   $ cd <Solr_Home>/bin\n   ```\n\n2. Next, create a new Solr core using the following command:\n   ```\n   $ ./solr create -c <core_name>\n   ```\n   Replace \"<core_name>\" with the desired name for your core.\n\n3. Once the core is created, you can start indexing documents into it. Make sure you have the document files available.\n   You can use the following command to post the documents to the Solr core:\n   ```\n   $ ./post -c <core_name> <list_of_document_files>\n   ```\n   Replace \"<core_name>\" with the name of the core you created in the previous step.\n   \"<list_of_document_files>\" should be replaced with the path or paths to the document files you want to index.\n\nBy following these steps, you will be able to index all the documents in your Apache Solr search core."}
