{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_381087", "question": "I am working with an Access Database using C# and I am encountering an error when trying to concatenate a value in my SQL query. The error message I am receiving is \"Syntax error (missing operator) in query expression\". Below is my code:\n\n```csharp\ncmd.CommandText = \"Select * from TEMP1 WHERE EMAIL=\" + GlobalData.Email;\n```\n\nCan someone please help me identify the cause of this error and provide the correct syntax for concatenation?", "answer": "To address your original question and improve the security of your code, it is recommended to use SqlParameter. Here is an example using SqlParameter:\n\n```csharp\nSqlCommand cmd = new SqlCommand(\"SELECT * FROM Temp1 WHERE Email LIKE @email\");\ncmd.Parameters.Add(new SqlParameter(\"email\", GlobalData.Email));\n```\n\nBy using SqlParameter, you can prevent SQL injection attacks and ensure the correct handling of special characters.\n\nRegarding your original code, the issue occurs because you are not using string delimiters in your SQL query. Without the delimiters, your query would look like this:\n\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM Temp1 WHERE Email LIKE email@email.com\n```\n\nInstead, it should be:\n\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM Temp1 WHERE Email LIKE 'email@email.com'\n```\n\nBy including the single quotes around the email value, you correctly indicate that it is a string literal in the query."}
