{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_350309", "question": "I am a bit new to assembly language and I'm having difficulty understanding the term \"byte equivalent\". It is used in the following context:\n\nThe MOV instruction causes ambiguity at times. For example, look at the statements:\n\n```\nMOV  EBX, [MY_TABLE]  ; Effective Address of MY_TABLE in EBX\nMOV  [EBX], 110       ; MY_TABLE[0] = 110\n```\n\nIt is not clear whether you want to move a byte equivalent or word equivalent of the number 110. In such cases, it is wise to use a type specifier.\n\nIt would be a great help if anybody could explain the term byte equivalent and provide a clear situation in which \"type specifiers\" may come in handy.", "answer": "The term \"byte equivalent\" refers to the ambiguity of the size of a value in assembly language. In the given instruction `MOV  [EBX], 110`, it is not clear whether you intend to move an 8-bit (byte equivalent), 16-bit (word equivalent), or 32-bit (dword equivalent) value of the number 110. \n\nTo resolve this ambiguity and specify the size of the value, you can use a type specifier. The exact syntax for type specifiers depends on the assembler you are using. \n\nIn NASM syntax, you would use `mov byte [ebx], 110` to specify that you want to store a byte. \n\nIn MASM/TASM syntax, you would use `mov byte ptr [ebx], 110`.\n\nBy using type specifiers, you can provide clarity to the assembler regarding the size of the value you intend to move, avoiding any ambiguity and ensuring correct execution of the assembly code."}
