rate additional types of microbial feed to expand the range of choices available to users. This can be done by providing information on different types of microbial feed, their benefits, and their applications.\n\n8. User Feedback: Continuously gather user feedback to understand how the website can be improved further.\n\nBy following this multi-step approach, users will have a better experience and will be more engaged with the website. Incorporating an interactive interface and customizable content options will provide users with the flexibility to access the information that is most relevant to them. Furthermore, expanding the range of microbial feed choices will help users understand the full range of benefits and applications of microbial feed."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_473746", "question": "Daisy’s milk cow provides 16 cups of milk per day.  75% of the milk is consumed by Daisy’s kids.  Daisy uses x% of the remaining milk to cook with.  How much milk is left over?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 2, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Daisy's milk cow provides 16 cups of milk per day.\n75% of the milk is consumed by Daisy's kids, which means they consume 0.75 * 16 = 12 cups of milk.\nThe remaining milk is 16 - 12 = 4 cups.\nDaisy uses x% of the remaining milk to cook with, which means she uses (x/100) * 4 = (4x/100) = (2x/50) cups of milk for cooking.\nThe amount of milk left over is: 4 - (2x/50) = (200/50) - (2x/50) = (200 - 2x)/50 cups.\nWe are given that the amount of milk left over is 2 cups, so we can write: (200 - 2x)/50 = 2.\nMultiplying both sides by 50, we get: 200 - 2x = 100.\nSubtracting 200 from both sides, we get: -2x = -100.\nDividing both sides by -2, we get: x = 50.\nThe value of x is 50.\n#### 50\nThe answer is: 50"}
