{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_278045", "question": "How do I find the first repeating element in an array using Python?", "answer": "You can use the following code to find the first repeating element in an array:\n\n```python\ndef first_repeating(arr): \n    dict = {}\n    for item in arr:\n        if item in dict:\n            return item\n        else:\n            dict[item] = 1 \n    return None\n```\n\nThis function takes an array as input and uses a dictionary to keep track of the frequency of elements. It iterates through each element in the array, checking if it already exists in the dictionary. If it does, it means that the element is repeating, so the function returns it. If the element is not found in the dictionary, it is added to the dictionary with a frequency of 1.\n\nIf no repeating element is found in the array, the function returns `None`.\n\nTo use this function, simply call it with your array as an argument. For example:\n\n```python\narray = [2, 5, 8, 2, 9, 1, 3, 5, 4]\nprint(first_repeating(array))\n```\n\nThis will output `2`, as it is the first repeating element in the given array."}
