{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_379544", "question": "I have two tables, `tbl1` and `tbl2`. The first table contains master data and has the following columns: ID, Name, and Total. \n\n```\nTable tbl1:\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| ID          | Name       | Total      | \n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| 1           | a          | 10         |\n| 2           | b          | 5          |\n| 3           | c          | 4          |\n| 4           | a          | 4          |\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n```\n\nThe second table, `tbl2`, contains child data and has the columns: id and qty. The key between the two tables is the ID. \n\n```\nTable tbl2:\n+-------------+------------+\n|id           | qty        | \n+-------------+------------+\n| 1           | 4          |              \n| 1           | 3          |                \n| 1           | 1          |                \n| 3           | 1          |                \n| 3           | 3          |                \n+-------------+------------+\n```\n\nI need to obtain an output that displays the sum of the Total column from `tbl1` and the sum of the qty column from `tbl2` for each unique name in `tbl1`. The desired output should look like this:\n\n```\nOutput:\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| name        | sum_tot    | sum_qty    | \n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| a           | 14         | 8          |\n| b           | 5          | 0          |\n| c           | 4          | 4          |\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n```\n\nI have tried the following query, but the output is not correct:\n\n```\nselect tbl1.name, SUM(tbl1.total), SUM(tbl2.qty)\nfrom tbl1\nleft join tbl2 ON tbl1.id = tbl2.id\nGROUP by tbl1.name\n```\n\nThe output that I get is:\n\n```\nOutput:\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| name        | sum_tot    | sum_qty    | \n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| a           | 34         | 8          |\n| b           | 5          |null        |\n| c           | 8          | 4          |\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n```\n\nWhich is not correct. It seems that the query is somehow running three times. How can I fix this issue?\n\nHere is the [sql fiddle](http://sqlfiddle.com/#!9/646b08/3):\n\n![enter image description here](https://i.stack.imgur.com/zrZsf.png)\n\nThe summary from the first table is not in relation with the second table.", "answer": "You can modify your query to use a correlated sub-query to calculate the sum of `tbl2.qty` for each `tbl1.id`. This will ensure that the sums are correctly calculated and associated with the corresponding names from `tbl1`. \n\nHere is the updated query:\n\n```sql\nselect tbl1.name, \n       SUM(tbl1.total), \n       SUM(COALESCE((select SUM(tbl2.qty) \n                     from tbl2\n                     where tbl1.id = tbl2.id), 0)) as qty_tot\nfrom tbl1\nGROUP by tbl1.name\n```\n\nExplanation:\n\n- In the sub-query `(select SUM(tbl2.qty) from tbl2 where tbl1.id = tbl2.id)`, we calculate the sum of `tbl2.qty` for each `tbl1.id` by using a correlated condition in the WHERE clause (`tbl1.id = tbl2.id`).\n- The COALESCE function is used to handle cases where there are no matching rows in `tbl2` for a given `tbl1.id`. If there are no matching rows, the sub-query will return NULL. The COALESCE function replaces NULL values with 0, ensuring that the final sum is not affected.\n- The outer query then sums the `tbl1.total` column as before and also includes the calculated sum of `tbl2.qty` as `qty_tot`.\n- Finally, the results are grouped by `tbl1.name`.\n\nThis modified query should give you the desired output:\n\n```\nOutput:\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| name        | sum_tot    | sum_qty    | \n+-------------+------------+------------+\n| a           | 14         | 8          |\n| b           | 5          | 0          |\n| c           | 4          | 4          |\n+-------------+------------+------------+\n```"}
