{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_278304", "question": "How can I design an algorithm to detect the presence of a 404 page from a given URL in Python?", "answer": "You can use the following code to detect the presence of a 404 page from a given URL in Python:\n\n```python\nimport requests\n\ndef detect_404(url):\n    # Make a GET request to the URL.\n    try:\n        resp = requests.get(url)\n        \n        # Check the response status code.\n        if resp.status_code == 404:\n            return True\n        else:\n            return False\n    except:\n        # If the request fails, assume 404.\n        return True\n\nurl = 'https://www.example.com/products/'\nresult = detect_404(url)\nprint(result)  # Output: False\n```\n\nIn this code, we first import the `requests` library, which allows us to send HTTP requests. \n\nNext, we define a function `detect_404` which takes a `url` as input. Inside the function, we make a GET request to the given URL using `requests.get(url)`. \n\nThen, we check the response status code using `resp.status_code`. If the status code is 404, it means that the requested page was not found, and we return `True`. Otherwise, we return `False`.\n\nIn case the GET request fails (e.g., due to network issues), the code inside the `except` block will be executed, and it will also return `True` assuming a 404 error.\n\nFinally, we call the `detect_404` function with the given URL and print the result.\n\nSo, in this specific example, the output will be `False` as the URL 'https://www.example.com/products/' does not result in a 404 page."}
