{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_259573", "question": "How can I create a PHP script to display a paginated list of posts?", "answer": "You can achieve this by using the following PHP code. This script will display a paginated list of posts on a web page.\n\n```php\n<html>\n   <head>\n      <title>Paginated Posts</title>\n   </head>\n   <body>\n   <?php\n      $per_page = 10;\n      $page = intval(isset($_GET['page']) ? $_GET['page'] : 1);\n      $start = ($page - 1) * $per_page;\n\n      $query = \"SELECT title, content FROM posts LIMIT $start, $per_page\";\n      $result = mysqli_query($conn, $query);\n\n      while($row = mysqli_fetch_array($result)) {\n         echo '<div>';\n         echo '<h1>'.$row['title'].'</h1>';\n         echo '<p>'.$row['content'].'</p>';\n         echo '</div>';\n      }\n\n      $total_pages = ceil(mysqli_num_rows($result) / $per_page);\n\n      for($i = 1; $i <= $total_pages; $i++) {\n         echo '<a href=\"?page='.$i.'\">'.$i.'</a> ';\n      }\n   ?>\n   </body>\n</html>\n```\n\nExplanation:\n- The `$per_page` variable determines the number of posts to display per page. You can modify this value to fit your requirements.\n- The `$page` variable retrieves the current page number from the URL query parameter using `$_GET['page']`.\n- The `$start` variable calculates the starting index for the SQL query based on the current page and number of posts per page.\n- The SQL query selects the `title` and `content` columns from the `posts` table, using the `LIMIT` clause to retrieve only the desired number of posts for the current page.\n- The query result is stored in the `$result` variable.\n- The `while` loop fetches each row from the query result and displays the post title and content within a `<div>` element.\n- The `$total_pages` variable calculates the total number of pages by dividing the total number of rows by the number of posts per page and rounding up using the `ceil()` function.\n- The `for` loop generates the pagination links, each linking to a specific page by appending the page number as a query parameter in the URL.\n\nYou can use this code as a starting point and adapt it to your specific application, database structure, and styling requirements."}
