{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_333885", "question": "How can I convert a binary tree into a TreeMap using Python?", "answer": "To convert a binary tree into a TreeMap, you can use the following code:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\ndef convert_to_tree_map(node):\n    # Creating a Treemap\n    map = defaultdict(list)\n    # Creating a queue and enqueue the root\n    q = deque([node])\n    # Looping until the queue is empty\n    while len(q):\n        # Dequeuing the front node from the queue\n        n = q.popleft()\n        # Inserting the node data into the TreeMap\n        map[n['data']].append([n['left'], n['right']])\n        # Checking if the left node is not None\n        if n['left'] is not None:\n            # Enqueue the left node\n            q.append(n['left'])\n        # Checking if the right node is not None\n        if n['right'] is not None:\n            # Enqueue the right node\n            q.append(n['right'])\n    # Return the TreeMap\n    return map\n```\n\nThis code uses a breadth-first search algorithm to traverse the binary tree and create a TreeMap. It uses a queue to keep track of the nodes to be processed. The algorithm starts by enqueuing the root node and then iterates until the queue is empty. In each iteration, it dequeues a node, inserts its data into the TreeMap, and checks if its left and right nodes are not None. If they are not None, they are enqueued for further processing. Finally, the created TreeMap is returned.\n\nYou can use this `convert_to_tree_map` function by passing the root node of your binary tree as an argument. It will return a TreeMap where each key represents the node data, and its corresponding value is a list containing the left and right child nodes (if present) of that node."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_457806", "question": "If one fourth of the engines in each of the 5 batches, each containing 80 engines, are defective, what is the total number of engines that are not defective?", "answer": "One fourth of 80 engines is 80/4 = 20 engines.\nIn each of the 5 batches, there are 20 defective engines.\nSo, the total number of defective engines is 20 x 5 = 100 engines.\nSince there are 80 engines in each batch, the total number of engines is 80 x 5 = 400 engines.\nTherefore, the total number of engines that are not defective is 400 - 100 = 300 engines.\n#### 300\nThe answer is: 300"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_67206", "question": "Solve the following system of linear equations using Cramer's rule:\n \n3x + 4y - 5z = 7\n2x - 3y + 4z = -2\n5x + 2y - z = 10\n\nFind the values of x, y, and z.", "answer": "To solve the given system of linear equations using Cramer's rule, we first need to find the determinant of the coefficient matrix (D), and then the determinants of the matrices obtained by replacing the columns with the constant terms (Dx, Dy, Dz).\n\nThe coefficient matrix is:\n| 3  4 -5 |\n| 2 -3  4 |\n| 5  2 -1 |\n\nLet's find the determinant D:\nD = 3((-3)(-1) - (4)(2)) - 4((2)(-1) - (4)(5)) - 5((2)(2) - (-3)(5))\nD = 3(3 - 8) - 4(-2 - 20) - 5(4 + 15)\nD = 3(-5) + 4(22) - 5(19)\nD = -15 + 88 - 95\nD = -22\n\nNow, let's find the determinant Dx by replacing the first column with the constant terms:\n| 7  4 -5 |\n| -2 -3  4 |\n| 10  2 -1 |\n\nDx = 7((-3)(-1) - (4)(2)) - 4((-2)(-1) - (4)(10)) - 5((-2)(2) - (-3)(10))\nDx = 7(3 - 8) + 4(-2 - 40) + 5(-4 + 30)\nDx = 7(-5) - 4(42) + 5(26)\nDx = -35 - 168 + 130\nDx = -73\n\nNow, let's find the determinant Dy by replacing the second column with the constant terms:\n| 3  7 -5 |\n| 2 -2  4 |\n| 5  10 -1 |\n\nDy = 3((-2)(-1) - (4)(10)) - 7((2)(-1) - (4)(5)) + 5((2)(10) - (-2)(5))\nDy = 3(-2 - 40) - 7(-2 - 20) + 5(20 + 10)\nDy = 3(-42) + 7(18) + 5(30)\nDy = -126 + 126 + 150\nDy = 150\n\nFinally, let's find the determinant Dz by replacing the third column with the constant terms:\n| 3  4  7 |\n| 2 -3 -2 |\n| 5  2  10 |\n\nDz = 3((-3)(10) - (-2)(2)) - 4((2)(10) - (-2)(5)) - 7((2)(2) - (-3)(5))\nDz = 3(-30 + 4) - 4(20 + 10) - 7(4 + 15)\nDz = 3(-26) - 4(30) - 7(19)\nDz = -78 - 120 - 133\nDz = -331\n\nNow we can find the values of x, y, and z using the determinants:\n\nx = Dx / D = -73 / -22 = 73/22\ny = Dy / D = 150 / -22 = -75/11\nz = Dz / D = -331 / -22 = 331/22\n\nSo the solution is:\nx = 73/22\ny = -75/11\nz = 331/22"}
