{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_14197", "question": "As Dory from Finding Nemo, describe your latest underwater adventure.", "answer": "Oh, hello there! I'm Dory. You know, the blue tang fish with short-term memory loss? Anyway, let me tell you about my latest underwater adventure.\n\nIt all started when I saw this shiny thingamabob floating in the water. It was so sparkly and beautiful, I just had to see what it was. So off I swam towards it, leaving Marlin behind. He's always telling me not to swim off on my own but...wait, who's Marlin again?\n\nAnyway, as I got closer to the shiny thing, I realized it wasn't a thing at all. It was a giant squid! Oh boy, did he look grumpy. But I remembered someone once told me that squids are more scared of us than we are of them. Or was that spiders? Never mind!\n\nI decided to say hi, because, well, why not? \"Hello, Mr. Squid!\" I said. \"My name is Dory.\" And then I forgot what I was doing there. Was I supposed to be looking for something? Or someone? \n\nSuddenly, I heard a loud noise. It was Marlin and Nemo! They were shouting my name and swimming towards me as fast as they could. The squid looked scared and tried to swim away, but I told him not to worry. My friends are really nice once you get to know them.\n\nWe ended up having a great time together. We played hide-and-seek among the coral reefs (which I won, by the way), and even found some delicious krill for lunch. By the end of the day, the squid didn't seem so scary anymore. In fact, he was actually pretty cool!\n\nAnd that's the story of my latest underwater adventure. At least, I think it is. Wait, what was I talking about again?"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_201018", "question": "What is the formula for calculating the energy expenditure during running in humans? Please explain the variables involved and their significance.\n[Formula]: \nEE = 1.036 x BW(kg) x D(m)\nWhere:\nEE = energy expenditure (kcal/kg/m)\nBW = body weight (kg)\nD = distance traveled (m)", "answer": "The formula for calculating the energy expenditure during running in humans is EE = 1.036 x BW(kg) x D(m). \nEE represents the energy expenditure in kcal/kg/m. \nBW stands for body weight in kilograms. This variable is significant because the more a person weighs, the more energy they need to expend to move their body weight. \nD represents the distance traveled in meters. This variable is significant because the longer the distance traveled, the more energy the body needs to expend to maintain the movement. \nThe constant 1.036 is the oxygen cost of running, which is the amount of oxygen required to produce a unit of energy. This constant is used to convert the amount of oxygen consumed during running into energy expenditure. \nTherefore, the formula calculates the energy expenditure during running by taking into account the body weight of the person and the distance they traveled, while also considering the oxygen cost of running."}
