{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_609852", "question": "What is the solution?\n\nSolve -70*l - 1814 = -344 for l.", "answer": "To solve the equation -70*l - 1814 = -344 for l, follow these steps:\n\nStep 1: Isolate the term with the variable (l) on one side of the equation.\nThe given equation is -70*l - 1814 = -344. We want to isolate the term containing the variable l, which is -70*l.\n\nStep 2: Add 1814 to both sides of the equation.\nTo do this, we'll add 1814 to both sides of the equation to eliminate the 1814 term from the left-hand side, resulting in the following equation:\n\n-70*l - 1814 + 1814 = -344 + 1814\n\nSimplify the equation:\n\n-70*l = 1470\n\nNow we have isolated -70*l on the left side of the equation.\n\nStep 3: Divide both sides by the coefficient of the variable (l), which is -70.\nNow we want to isolate the variable l itself, so we divide both sides of the equation by -70:\n\n(-70*l) / -70 = 1470 / -70\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation and solve for l.\nAfter dividing, the left side of the equation simplifies to just l:\n\nl = -21\n\nThe solution to the equation is l = -21."}
