{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_394032", "question": "I'm trying to understand buffer overflows and how the value of eip works. Can someone explain what is happening in this code snippet?\n\nHere is the C code:\n\n```c\nvoid copy(char *arg) {\n  char msg[256];\n  strcpy(msg,arg);\n}\n```\n\nAnd here is the corresponding assembly:\n\n```assembly\n0x804847d <copy+25>:    call   0x8048368 <strcpy@plt>\n0x8048482 <copy+30>:    leave  \n0x8048483 <copy+31>:    ret    \n```\n\nI'm passing a string as an argument, for example, \"_\\xAA\\xBB\\xCC\\xDD\", with a size calculated in a way that the last 4 bytes overwrite the real return address, located 4 bytes after $ebp. Surprisingly, it seems to work.\n\nWhen I debug the program in gdb, I observe the following:\n\n```\n(break before strcpy)\nx/2wx $ebp\n0xbffffb38: 0xbffffb58  0x080484d2\nn\n(just after strcpy execution)\nx/2wx $ebp\n0xbffffb38: 0x80cdd189  0x080484b6\n...\nn\n...\nx/2wx $ebp\n0xbffffb38: 0x80cdd189  0x080484b6\n```\n\nSo, the original return address was `0x080484d2`, and after the overflow, it becomes `0x080484b6`, which is what I want. However, the program exits with the error message \"Cannot access memory at address 0x80cdd18d\".\n\nI'm confused as to why $eip was not set to my address. I'm pretty confident that $ebp+4 holds the return address. \n\nI tried again with a string that is 4 bytes smaller, and this time it overwrote $ebp instead of $ebp+4, and after the return, $eip was set to the value contained in $ebp+4.\n\nCan someone explain this behavior?", "answer": "Sure! The behavior you are observing is due to the instructions in the assembly code and the impact of a buffer overflow on the stack.\n\nLet's break it down step by step:\n\n1. The `call` instruction at `0x804847d` is calling the `strcpy` function, which is responsible for copying the contents of `arg` into `msg`.\n\n2. The `leave` instruction at `0x8048482` is used to clean up the stack frame before returning from the function. It performs two operations:\n   - It sets `esp` to the value of `ebp`, effectively deallocating the stack space used by the function.\n   - It restores the previous value of `ebp` by popping it from the stack.\n\n3. The `ret` instruction at `0x8048483` is responsible for changing the value of `eip` (the instruction pointer) and returning control to the calling function.\n\nNow, let's analyze the impact of the buffer overflow:\n\nWhen you overwrite the 4 bytes after `ebp` with your desired value, you are changing the return address that will be loaded into `eip` when the `ret` instruction is executed. This is why you observe the change in the value of `eip` from `0x080484d2` to `0x080484b6` after the overflow.\n\nHowever, the reason you are encountering the error \"Cannot access memory at address 0x80cdd18d\" is because you are also modifying the value of `ebp` with your overflow. The `leave` instruction takes the value from `ebp` and restores it, but since you have overwritten it, the restored value is incorrect. This leads to the error when the program tries to access memory using the corrupted `ebp` value.\n\nTo make it work successfully, you should avoid overwriting the value at `ebp`. By doing so, the `leave` instruction will correctly restore the original value of `ebp`, and the program will execute without errors.\n\nI hope this explanation helps you understand the behavior you observed. Let me know if you have any further questions!"}
