{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_3608", "question": "A train travels from Town A to Town B at a constant speed. The distance between the two towns is 120 miles. If the train leaves Town A at 2 PM and arrives in Town B at 5 PM, what time will it be when the train has traveled half the distance?", "answer": "Let's reason through this problem:\n1. The train travels a total distance of 120 miles.\n2. It takes 3 hours (from 2 PM to 5 PM) for the train to travel this distance.\n3. To find the speed of the train, we can divide the total distance by the time taken: 120 miles / 3 hours = 40 miles per hour.\n4. Half the distance between the two towns is 120 miles / 2 = 60 miles.\n5. To find the time it takes for the train to travel half the distance, we can divide the half-distance by the train's speed: 60 miles / 40 miles per hour = 1.5 hours.\n6. Since the train leaves Town A at 2 PM, it will have traveled half the distance after 1.5 hours, which means it will be 3:30 PM.\n\nTherefore, it will be 3:30 PM when the train has traveled half the distance."}
