{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_710286", "question": "Q: What do atoms form by sharing valence electrons?    Choices:  - phenotype bonds  - neutron bonds  - ionic bonds  - covalent bonds  A:\nA:", "answer": "Atoms form covalent bonds by sharing valence electrons. \n\nStep 1: Identify the correct answer choice\nIn the given options, \"covalent bonds\" is the only choice related to sharing electrons. Ionic bonds involve the transfer of electrons, while phenotype bonds and neutron bonds are not genuine types of chemical bonds. \n\nStep 2: Justify why covalent bonds form by sharing valence electrons\nCovalent bonds form when atoms share their valence electrons to achieve a full outer electron shell, resulting in a stable configuration. The shared electrons then belong to both atoms equally, allowing them to complete their outer shells without actually losing or gaining electrons. This sharing of electrons results in the formation of molecules, and the bond between the atoms is known as a covalent bond."}
