{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_244900", "question": "I'm trying to create a web application using JavaScript and Express that functions as an add and subtract calculator. Could someone provide me with a code snippet that accomplishes this?", "answer": "Certainly! You can achieve this by utilizing the Express framework. Here's an example solution:\n\n```javascript\nconst express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\n\napp.use(express.json());\n\napp.get('/calculator', (req, res) => {\n  // Get the value of the operands from the request body\n  const { firstOperand, secondOperand } = req.body;\n\n  // Add the two numbers\n  const addResult = firstOperand + secondOperand;\n\n  // Subtract the two numbers\n  const subtractResult = firstOperand - secondOperand;\n\n  // Create a response object with each result\n  const response = {\n    addResult,\n    subtractResult,\n  };\n\n  res.json(response);\n});\n\napp.listen(9000);\n```\n\nIn this code, we start by requiring the Express module and creating an instance of the `app` object. We then enable parsing of JSON data using `app.use(express.json())`.\n\nThe `/calculator` route is configured to handle GET requests. Inside the route handler function, we extract the `firstOperand` and `secondOperand` values from the request body.\n\nWe perform the addition and subtraction operations, storing the results in `addResult` and `subtractResult`, respectively.\n\nNext, we create a response object called `response` that contains both results. Finally, we send the response back to the client using `res.json(response)`.\n\nTo test this calculator, you can make a request to `http://localhost:9000/calculator` with the operands provided in the request body. The server will respond with a JSON object containing the addition and subtraction results."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_565166", "question": "News article: Sam's Club taps e-commerce in search of edge over Costco\n\nSam’s Club, the warehouse club operated by Walmart Stores WMT , has overhauled its in-store pick-up service for online orders as it looks to gain an edge in e-commerce over archival Costco Wholesale COST .\n\nThe company, the eight largest U.S. retailer with sales of $58 billion last year, already gives customers the option to order products online and pick them up in stores.\n\nBut Sam’s Club said Thursday that it has improved the service, renamed “Club Pickup” from “Click ‘n Pull,” to let customers build and save shopping lists online so they can reorder the same items later or do so automatically. They can also get suggestions for substitutions if an item is out of stock. The service, which has an expanded assortment of items available, will be open for business seven days a week rather than just five.\n\nSam’s Club said that could be particularly handy for its convenience store customers. That part of its business that has struggled as that area of retail has consolidated and tobacco sales softened.\n\nThe initiative is just the latest by Sam’s Club to shore up its revenue from business customers, which account for as much as one-third of Sam’s Club’s membership, according to Kantar Retail estimates. But lately, they have been a softer part of its business compared to non-business members, impeding its performance compared to Costco.\n\nWe “believe the busiest members will benefit the most, like parents and small business owners who have limited time and the most recurring needs,” said Sam’s Club CEO Rosalind Brewer.\n\nThis follows other initiatives Brewer described last year in an interview with Fortune, including a big expansion of what it sells online for small businesses.\n\nThis service could give Sam’s Club a welcome edge over Costco, which quarter in and quarter out reports better sales numbers. Costco does not yet let customers place orders online that they can retrieve at a warehouse.\n\nSam’s Club can use the new service to place orders online or through an app, select the location and time they want to pick up the order, and get an email or text alert when the order is ready.\n\nFor more about Walmart, watch this Fortune video:\nWhat are the most important parts of this news article?", "answer": "This news article is about Sam's Club, a big store owned by Walmart, trying to do better than its competitor, Costco, by improving its online shopping and pick-up service. They changed the service's name to \"Club Pickup\" and made it better by letting customers save lists of items they like to buy and giving suggestions if something is not available. The pick-up service will now be open every day of the week. This could be very helpful for busy people like parents and small business owners. Costco doesn't have a similar service, so this might give Sam's Club an advantage."}
