overeignty over a geographic area. International law defines sovereign states as having a permanent population, defined territory, one government, and the capacity to enter into relations with other sovereign states. It is also normally understood that a sovereign state is neither dependent on nor subjected to any other power or state.  - Continental climates are defined in the Köppen climate classification has having a coldest month mean temperature below -3 C (26.6 F) or 0 °C depending on which isotherm used for the coldest month and four months above 10 °C. In the Köppen climate system, Continental climates were bordered to the south by Temperate climates or C climates (coldest month above 0 C, but below 18 C) and to the north by Boreal climate or E climates (only 1 to 3 months with a mean temperature of 50 F). Köppen also defined continental climates as having more than 30 days with continuous snowcover on the ground.   - Bucharest is the capital and largest city of Romania, as well as its cultural, industrial, and financial centre. It is located in the southeast of the country, at , on the banks of the Dâmbovia River, less than north of the Danube River and the Bulgarian border.  - Hungary is a unitary parliamentary republic in Central Europe. It covers an area of , situated in the Carpathian Basin and bordered by Slovakia to the north, Romania to the east, Serbia to the south, Croatia to the southwest, Slovenia to the west, Austria to the northwest, and Ukraine to the northeast. With about 10 million inhabitants, Hungary is a medium-sized member state of the European Union. The official language is Hungarian, which is the most widely spoken Uralic language in the world. Hungary's capital and largest metropolis is Budapest, a significant economic hub, classified as an Alpha- global city. Major urban areas include Debrecen, Szeged, Miskolc, Pécs and Gyr.    Given the information above, choose from the list below the object entity that exhibits the relation 'instance of' with the subject 'iezerul mic river'.  Choices: - 1  - area  - balkans  - body of water  - border  - capital  - city  - classification  - climate  - country  - economic union  - financial centre  - government  - home  - hungary  - international law  - landlocked country  - law  - market  - member  - metropolis  - month  - official  - part  - peninsula  - republic  - river  - sea  - sovereign state  - state  - temperature  - territorial dispute  - territory  - union  - volume\nThe answer is:", "answer": "river"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_639823", "question": "Please answer this question: Which island, a former Dutch colony with its capital at Orangestad, continues to move slowly towards complete independence?", "answer": "The island you're referring to is Aruba, which is a small island located in the southern Caribbean Sea, just north of the coast of Venezuela. It covers an area of about 179 square kilometers (69 square miles) and has a population of around 106,000 people. The capital of Aruba is Oranjestad, a vibrant city that serves as the island's hub for commerce, tourism, and culture.\n\nAruba has a rich history that includes colonization by the Dutch in the early 17th century. The Dutch established their presence on the island in 1636 when they claimed possession of it from the indigenous Caquetio Indians. They ruled Aruba for over two centuries under the jurisdiction of the Dutch West India Company until it became a colony of the Netherlands in 1815.\n\nDuring the 20th century, Aruba began to seek greater autonomy from the Netherlands. In 1954, it achieved a certain degree of self-government as a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, which also included the Netherlands Antilles and the Netherlands.\n\nIn 1986, Aruba decided to separate from the Netherlands Antilles, becoming a separate and autonomous constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands. There were initial plans for Aruba to gain complete independence by 1996, but the process was halted in 1990 due to concerns about the island's economic stability and sustainability.\n\nSince then, Aruba has maintained its status as a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands but continues to steadily move towards greater autonomy and potentially full independence. In recent years, there has been an increased push for self-determination, with various political parties and movements advocating for more control over the island's natural resources, environment, and economic policies.\n\nThe issue of independence remains a topic of debate among the Aruban population, balancing the potential benefits of complete self-governance against the costs and uncertainties of disconnecting from the Dutch support system. While Aruba has not yet achieved complete independence, it continues to cultivate its unique identity, culture, and political system, which could shape the island's future relationship with the Netherlands.\n\nIn conclusion, the island of Aruba is a former Dutch colony with its capital at Oranjestad that continues to move slowly towards independence. As a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, Aruba has been gradually asserting more of its autonomy and self-governance over the past decades. With an evolving political landscape and an ongoing debate on the benefits and challenges of full independence, Aruba's future remains a subject of discussion and interest."}
