{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_347802", "question": "I'm trying to unmarshal a JSON response into a struct array in Go, but I'm having trouble with the nested structures. The fields within the \"abilityDescription1\" (and other similar fields) are not getting populated correctly. Can someone suggest a solution?\n\n```go\ntype God struct {\n    Ability1                      string\n    Ability2                      string\n    Ability3                      string\n    Ability4                      string\n    Ability5                      string\n    AbilityId1                    int\n    AbilityId2                    int\n    AbilityId3                    int\n    AbilityId4                    int\n    AbilityId5                    int\n    Attack_speed                  float64\n    Attack_speed_per_level        float64\n    Cons                          string\n    Hp5_per_level                 float64\n    Health                        int\n    Health_per_five               int\n    Health_per_level              int\n    // ...\n    Abilitydescription1           struct {\n        Item_description struct {\n            Cooldown    string\n            Cost        string\n            Description string\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n    // ...\n}\n\nvar gods []God\njson.Unmarshal(jsonResponse, &gods)\nreturn gods\n```", "answer": "To resolve the issue with nested structures not being populated correctly when unmarshaling JSON in Go, you can use struct tags to map JSON field names to struct field names. This will allow the encoding/json package to access and populate the appropriate fields.\n\nAdditionally, it is recommended to split your structs into separate items and then embed them for better readability and the ability to add tags. This will also avoid repeating fields like \"Rank_items\". For example:\n\n```go\ntype God struct {\n    Ability1                      string\n    Ability2                      string\n    Ability3                      string\n    Ability4                      string\n    Ability5                      string\n    AbilityId1                    int\n    AbilityId2                    int\n    AbilityId3                    int\n    AbilityId4                    int\n    AbilityId5                    int\n    Attack_speed                  float64\n    Attack_speed_per_level        float64\n    Cons                          string\n    Hp5_per_level                 float64\n    Health                        int\n    Health_per_five               int\n    Health_per_level              int\n    // ...\n    Abilitydescription1           ItemDesc `json:\"abilityDescription1\"`\n    // ...\n}\n\ntype ItemDesc struct {\n    Item_description struct {\n        Cooldown    string `json:\"cooldown\"`\n        Cost        string `json:\"cost\"`\n        Description string `json:\"description\"`\n        // ...\n    } `json:\"itemDescription\"`\n}\n\nvar gods []God\njson.Unmarshal(jsonResponse, &gods)\nreturn gods\n```\n\nBy using struct tags like `json:\"abilityDescription1\"` and `json:\"itemDescription\"`, the encoding/json package will correctly match the JSON field names with the struct field names, allowing the nested structures to be populated correctly during unmarshaling."}
