{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_875732", "question": "q: Assisants are needed to prepare for preparation. Each helper can make either 2 large cakes or 35 small cakes/hour. The kitchen is available for 3hours and 20 large cakes and 700small cakes are needed. How many helpers are required?\nOptions:\n(A) 9\n(B) 10\n(C) 13\n(D) 16\n(E) 18\na: 20 large cakes will require the equivalent of 10 helpers working for one hour. 700 small cakes will require the equivalent of 20 helpers working for one hour. This means if only one hour were available we would need 30 helpers. But since three hours are available we can use 10 helpers. The answer is (B).\n--\nq: What is the sum of all the composite numbers up to 20?\nOptions:\n(A) 130\n(B) 132\n(C) 124\n(D) 145\n(E) 166\na: 4 + 6 + 8 + 9 + 10 + 12 + 14 + 15 + 16 + 18 = 132 The answer is (B).\n--\nq: A 160 meter long train crosses a man standing on the platform in 8 sec. What is the speed of the train?\nOptions:\n(A) 96 kmph\n(B) 94 kmph\n(C) 92 kmph\n(D) 86 kmph\n(E) 72 kmph\na: S = 160/8 * 18/5 = 72 kmph The answer is (E).\n--\nq: The H.C.F. of two numbers is 11 and their L.C.M. is 7700. If one of the numbers is 275, then the other is:\nOptions:\n(A) 279\n(B) 283\n(C) 308\n(D) 318\n(E) 328\na:", "answer": "We know that the product of two numbers is equal to the product of their H.C.F. and L.C.M. So, let the other number be x.\n\n275 * x = 11 * 7700\n\nNow, we need to find the value of x:\n\nx = (11 * 7700) / 275\nx = 308\n\nThe other number is 308. The answer is (C)."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_309685", "question": "How can I design an algorithm to join two sorted linked lists?", "answer": "You can use the following code snippet as a solution. \n```python\ndef join_sorted_lists(list1, list2):\n    # init a new linked list\n    result = LinkedList()\n    temp1 = list1.head\n    temp2 = list2.head\n\n    # iterate through both linked lists\n    while (temp1 is not None) and (temp2 is not None):\n        # if the element of list1 is smaller add it to the new list\n        if temp1.data < temp2.data:\n            result.append(temp1.data)\n            temp1 = temp1.next\n        # else add the element of list2\n        else:\n            result.append(temp2.data)\n            temp2 = temp2.next\n\n    # add the remaining elements\n    while temp1 is not None:\n        result.append(temp1.data)\n        temp1 = temp1.next\n    while temp2 is not None:\n        result.append(temp2.data)\n        temp2 = temp2.next\n\n    return result\n```\n\nIn this solution, we initiate a new linked list called `result`. We also create two temporary variables, `temp1` and `temp2`, to keep track of the current position in the input linked lists `list1` and `list2`, respectively.\n\nWe then iterate through both linked lists using a while loop, comparing the current elements of `temp1` and `temp2`. If the element from `list1` is smaller, we append it to the `result` linked list and move `temp1` to the next node. If the element from `list2` is smaller or equal, we append it to the `result` linked list and move `temp2` to the next node.\n\nAfter iterating through both lists, we use two additional while loops to add any remaining elements from `list1` and `list2` to the `result` linked list.\n\nFinally, we return the `result` linked list, which contains the merged and sorted elements from both input linked lists."}
