{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_148494", "question": "Compute the value of 7/8 + (1/4 x 9)", "answer": "Sure, to compute the value of 7/8 + (1/4 x 9), let's start by solving the operation inside the parentheses first:\n\n(1/4 x 9) = 9/4\n\nNow, we can add 7/8 to 9/4:\n\n7/8 + (9/4) = (7/8) + (9 x 2/4 x 2) = (7/8) + (18/8) = 25/8\n\nTherefore,  the value of 7/8 + (1/4 x 9) is equal to 25/8, which can also be expressed as a mixed number: 3 1/8."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_991235", "question": "How can you automatically insert the average of values in column B of every sheet in a Google Spreadsheet and append it to the last row of column C, using a single script command?", "answer": "You can use the following script command to automatically insert the average of values in column B of every sheet in a Google Spreadsheet and append it to the last row of column C:\n\n```\nfunction insertAverage() {\n  var sheets = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheets();\n  for (var i = 0; i < sheets.length; i++) {\n    var sheet = sheets[i];\n    var lastRow = sheet.getLastRow();\n    var values = sheet.getRange(1, 2, lastRow, 1).getValues();\n    var sum = 0;\n    for (var j = 0; j < values.length; j++) {\n      sum += values[j][0];\n    }\n    var average = sum / values.length;\n    sheet.getRange(lastRow + 1, 3).setValue(average);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis script retrieves all the sheets in the current active spreadsheet, loops through each sheet, gets the last row in column B, calculates the average of the values in column B, and appends the result to the last row of column C. You can trigger this script manually or use a time-driven trigger to run it automatically."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_237822", "question": "I am trying to find a concise way to compare the values of multiple variables in Python, such that no two variables should have the same value. For instance, I have:\n\n```python\na=1\nb=2\nc=3\nif a != b and b != c and a != c:\n    #do something \n```\nIn a scenario where there are more variables, the 'if' statement becomes quite long and filled with 'and' operators. Is there a simpler method to ensure no two variable values are identical in Python?", "answer": "Yes, there is a simpler way in Python to check if no two variables share the same value. You can achieve this by using sets. \n\nPython sets are an unordered collection of unique elements. When you convert your variables to a set, it automatically removes any duplicates. Therefore, you can simply compare the length of the set with the length of your original list of variables. If the lengths are equal, this means all your variables have unique values.\n\nHere is a step-by-step solution:\n\n1. First, put your variables into a list:\n\n```python\nvariables = [a, b, c]\n```\n\n2. Convert the list to a set:\n\n```python\nunique_variables = set(variables)\n```\n\n3. Compare the lengths of the original list and the set:\n\n```python\nif len(variables) == len(unique_variables):\n    #do something \n```\n\nSo the complete code would be:\n\n```python\na=1\nb=2\nc=3\nvariables = [a, b, c]\nunique_variables = set(variables)\nif len(variables) == len(unique_variables):\n    #do something \n```\n\nThis concise way eliminates the need for long 'if' statements filled with 'and' operators and effectively checks for uniqueness of variable values."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_239705", "question": "Can someone provide a list of recommended Python-based REST frameworks that can be used on the server-side to write my own RESTful APIs? I would appreciate if the recommendations could include pros and cons for each framework.", "answer": "There are several Python-based REST frameworks that you can use to write your own RESTful APIs. Here are a few:\n\n1. Django REST Framework:\n   - Pros: Django REST Framework is powerful, flexible and easy to use. It has great documentation and a huge community. It provides a full suite of features including authentication, viewsets, serializers, and routers.\n   - Cons: It can be quite large and heavy for small projects. It requires a good understanding of Django.\n\n2. Flask-RESTful:\n   - Pros: Flask-RESTful is lightweight and easy to use. It is great for small projects and for people just starting with REST APIs. It integrates well with Flask-SQLAlchemy and Flask-Marshmallow.\n   - Cons: It might lack some advanced features provided by larger frameworks.\n\n3. FastAPI:\n   - Pros: FastAPI is modern and fast (high performance), with a simple API. It has automatic interactive API documentation and it's built on Starlette for the web parts and Pydantic for the data parts.\n   - Cons: Being relatively new, it might lack some features and its community is not as large as Django or Flask.\n\n4. Tornado:\n   - Pros: Tornado is a Python web framework and asynchronous networking library, originally developed at FriendFeed. It uses non-blocking network I/O and can scale to tens of thousands of open connections, making it ideal for long polling, WebSockets, and other applications that require a long-lived connection to each user.\n   - Cons: It is less popular and not as widely used as Django or Flask. \n\n5. Pyramid:\n   - Pros: Pyramid is a general, open source, Python web framework. Its main goal is to make it easier for a Python developer to create web applications.\n   - Cons: Pyramid's documentation is not as good as some of the other frameworks like Django or Flask. It's community is also smaller.\n\nThese frameworks offer a variety of features, so the best one to use depends on your specific needs and preferences."}
