itness to the world gone by,\nBut in my heart, a hope that swells,\nFor nature's power, it surely tells.\n\nFor though we're lost, and tossed, and torn,\nAnd though we bear the brunt of scorn,\nWe'll find a way, to break the chain,\nAnd live in harmony again."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_484555", "question": "Bert fills out the daily crossword puzzle in the newspaper every day. He uses up a pencil to fill out the puzzles every two weeks. On average, it takes him 1050 words to use up a pencil. How many words are in each crossword puzzle on average?", "answer": "Bert uses up a pencil every two weeks, and it takes him 1050 words to use up a pencil.\nSo in two weeks, Bert completes 1050 words of crossword puzzles.\nTherefore, on average, Bert completes 1050/2 = 525 words of crossword puzzles per week.\nSince there are 7 days in a week, Bert completes 525/7 = 75 words of crossword puzzles per day.\nTherefore, on average, each crossword puzzle contains 75 words.\n#### 75\nThe answer is: 75"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_164105", "question": "What are some creative job titles that can be used for a fictional story about a job seeker's interview experience, showcasing their skills and qualifications while also incorporating wordplay or riddles related to the industry? The story should delve into the protagonist's thoughts and emotions throughout the interview process, from their anxious preparations in the morning to the intense exchange with the interviewers. The SQL database table \"candidates\" contains the following columns: id, name, skills, qualifications, and industry experience. How can we query this table to generate unique and relevant job titles for our story?", "answer": "To generate unique and relevant job titles for the story, we can query the \"candidates\" table using the following SQL statement:\n```\nSELECT CONCAT('Chief ', LEFT(skills, 3), ' Officer') AS job_title\nFROM candidates\nWHERE qualifications LIKE '%Bachelor%' AND industry_experience >= 5\n```\nThis query selects candidates who have a Bachelor's degree and at least 5 years of industry experience. It then generates a job title using wordplay and riddles related to their skills. For example, if a candidate's skills include SQL, the generated job title could be \"Chief SQL Officer\". The protagonist could be interviewing for this position and the story could delve into their thoughts and emotions throughout the interview process."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_919776", "question": "Let $a,$ $b,$ $c$ be the roots of $x^3 + px + q = 0.$  Express\n\\[\\begin{vmatrix} 1 + a & 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 + b & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 & 1 + c \\end{vmatrix}\\]in terms of $p$ and $q.$", "answer": "We can expand the determinant as follows:\n\\begin{align*}\n\\begin{vmatrix} 1 + a & 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 + b & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 & 1 + c \\end{vmatrix} &= (1 + a) \\begin{vmatrix} 1 + b & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 + c \\end{vmatrix} - \\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 + c \\end{vmatrix} + \\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 + b \\\\ 1 & 1 \\end{vmatrix} \\\\\n&= (1 + a)((1 + b)(1 + c) - 1) - ((1)(1 + c) - 1) + (1 - (1 + b)) \\\\\n&= abc + ab + ac + bc.\n\\end{align*}By Vieta's formulas, $ab + ac + bc = p$ and $abc = -q,$ so\n\\[abc + ab + ac + bc = p - q.\\]"}
