{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_299265", "question": "Can you provide a C++ program that converts a given ASCII string to its binary representation?", "answer": "Certainly! Here's a C++ program that achieves that:\n\n```cpp\n#include<iostream>\n#include<string>\n \nusing namespace std;\n \nstring StrToBin(string str)\n{\n    string binStr;\n    for(int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {\n        bool negative = false;\n        int dec = str[i];\n        string bin = \"\";\n \n        while (dec > 0) {\n            int rem = dec % 2;\n            if (rem < 0) {\n                negative = true;\n            } else {\n                bin = to_string(rem) + bin;\n            }\n            dec /= 2;\n        }\n \n        while (bin.length() < 8) bin = \"0\" + bin;\n        if (negative) bin = \"1\" + bin;\n        binStr += bin;\n    }\n    return binStr;\n}\n \nint main()\n{\n    string str = \"Hello World\";\n \n    cout << \"Input string is:  \" << str << endl;\n    cout << \"Equivalent binary string is:  \" << StrToBin(str) << endl;\n \n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nIn this program, we have a function `StrToBin` that takes a string as input and returns its binary representation as a string. The function iterates over each character in the input string and converts its ASCII value to binary.\n\nInside the loop, we initialize a boolean variable `negative` to false and an integer `dec` to the ASCII value of the current character. Then, we define an empty string `bin` to store the binary representation.\n\nWe use a while loop to perform the conversion from decimal to binary. We calculate the remainder (`rem`) of `dec` divided by 2 and add it to the beginning of the `bin` string. If the remainder is negative, we set `negative` to true.\n\nAfter the conversion, we ensure that the `bin` string has a length of 8 by adding leading zeros if necessary. If `negative` is true, we prepend a '1' to the `bin` string.\n\nFinally, we concatenate the `bin` string to the `binStr` string, which stores the binary representation of the entire input string.\n\nIn the `main` function, we define a string variable `str` with the value \"Hello World\". We then print the input string and its equivalent binary representation using the `StrToBin` function.\n\nOutput:\n```\nInput string is:  Hello World\nEquivalent binary string is:  0100100001100101011011000110110001101111001000000101011101101111011100100110110001100100\n```\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions."}
