{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_563154", "question": "Given the question: Park farm and Fiddle farm provided Red city with tonnes of produce annually. Fiddle farm used and abundance of fertilizers and pesticides, while Park farm didn't use any of those substances.  Which farm caused more fertilizer to dissolve in the soil because of rain?  Hint: Rain dissolves fertilizer in the soil. Runoff carries it away. The fertilizer ends up in bodies of water, from ponds to oceans. Nitrogen is a fertilizer in the water. Since there is a lot of nitrogen, it causes algae to grow out of control. Pictured below is a pond covered with algae ( Figure below ). Algae use up carbon dioxide in the water. After the algae die, decomposers break down the dead tissue. The decomposers use up all the oxygen in the water. This creates a dead zone. A dead zone is an area in a body of water where nothing grows because there is too little oxygen. There is a large dead zone in the Gulf of Mexico ( Figure below ). The U.S. states outlined on the map have rivers that drain into the Gulf of Mexico. The rivers drain vast agricultural lands. The water carries fertilizer from these areas into the Gulf.\nThe answer is:", "answer": "Given the information provided, Fiddle farm caused more fertilizer to dissolve in the soil because of rain. This is because Fiddle farm used an abundance of fertilizers and pesticides, while Park farm did not use any of those substances. \n\nWhen it rains, the water dissolves and carries away the applied fertilizers and pesticides in the soil through runoff. The runoff then transports these chemicals to various bodies of water, including ponds, rivers, and oceans. The presence of excessive nitrogen in these waters (due to the fertilizers) triggers the overgrowth of algae. This phenomenon, known as an algal bloom, can cause significant ecological imbalance.\n\nThe algae consume carbon dioxide in the water and subsequently die. The decomposers then break down the dead algal matter, using up oxygen in the process and creating a dead zone. A dead zone is an area in a body of water where nothing grows due to the depletion of oxygen. This can have detrimental effects on aquatic life and ecosystems.\n\nIn the given scenario, Fiddle farm contributed to greater fertilizer dissolution in the soil, and thus a higher likelihood of contributing to the formation of dead zones in nearby bodies of water."}
