{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_346256", "question": "I am trying to implement a function in my Graph class called `PutPixel` which takes in three parameters: `x`, `y`, and `c`. Inside the function, I have an assembly code block that performs some calculations and then stores a value in the memory location specified by `_buffer`. However, when I run the code, I always get a value of 0 for both `_buffer` and `_width`, even though I know they have different values assigned to them. I found a solution online where they suggest copying the class variables to local variables and using those instead. Here is the fixed code:\n\n```cpp\nvoid Graph::PutPixel(DWORD x, DWORD y, DWORD c)\n{\n    DWORD bufAddr = (DWORD)_buffer;\n    DWORD w = _width;\n    __asm \n    {\n        Mov Eax, y\n        Mov Ebx, w\n        Mul Ebx\n        Add Eax, x\n        Shl Eax, 2 // Multiply by four\n        Add Eax, bufAddr\n        Mov Edi, Eax\n        Mov Eax, c\n        StosD\n    }\n}\n```\n\nMy question is, what is the problem with directly using the class variables `_buffer` and `_width`? Is it possible to fix the code without using local variables?", "answer": "The issue you are facing with directly using the class variables `_buffer` and `_width` in your assembly code is related to the way assembly code accesses memory locations. Assembly code typically works with registers and memory addresses, and it may not directly recognize the names of class variables.\n\nTo fix the problem without using local variables, you can modify your assembly code to explicitly reference the class and its members using the `this` pointer. Here is an example of how you can modify your code:\n\n```cpp\nvoid Graph::PutPixel(DWORD x, DWORD y, DWORD c)\n{\n    __asm \n    {\n        mov ecx,this\n        mov Eax, y\n        mov Ebx, [ecx]Graph._width //alias ecx to type 'Graph' and access member\n        mul Ebx\n        add Eax, x\n        shl Eax, 2\n        add Eax, [ecx]._buffer //access member with bound alias\n        mov Edi, Eax\n        mov Eax, c\n        stosd\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this modified code, we use the `this` pointer to refer to the current instance of the `Graph` class. By using the `this` pointer, we can access the class members `_width` and `_buffer` within the assembly code.\n\nBy making this change, you should be able to directly use the class variables without the need for copying them to local variables."}
