{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_326950", "question": "I need help writing a program in C that takes a user inputted number and prints a multiplication table from 1 to 10 for that number. Can you provide a solution?", "answer": "Certainly! Here is a C program that accomplishes that task:\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main()\n{\n    int n, i;\n    printf(\"Enter an integer: \");\n    scanf(\"%d\", &n);\n\n    for (i = 1; i <= 10; ++i) {\n        printf(\"%d * %d = %d \\n\", n, i, n * i);\n    }\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nExplanation:\n- The program starts by declaring two variables, `n` and `i`, both of type `int`. \n- The user is prompted to enter an integer using `printf()` and `scanf()` functions.\n- A `for` loop is used to iterate from 1 to 10, incrementing `i` by 1 in each iteration.\n- Inside the loop, `printf()` is used to display the multiplication table for the inputted number. The format specifier `%d` is used to represent integers, and `n * i` calculates the multiplication.\n- Finally, the program returns 0 to indicate successful execution.\n\nBy running this program and providing an input integer, it will display the multiplication table from 1 to 10 for that number."}
