{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_188648", "question": "In a SQL database table called \"Players\", there is a column \"Hobbies\" that contains the following data:\n| Name | Hobbies |\n|------|---------|\n| John | Reading |\n| Mary | Video Games |\n| Tom  | Hiking   |\nIf I want to retrieve all players who do not like playing video games, what SQL query should I use?\nNote: The sentence \"She likes playing video games\" is equivalent to \"Mary likes playing video games\" based on the given data in the table.", "answer": "You can use the following SQL query to retrieve all players who do not like playing video games:\n```\nSELECT Name, Hobbies\nFROM Players\nWHERE Hobbies <> 'Video Games';\n```\nThis query will select all players from the \"Players\" table whose \"Hobbies\" column does not contain the value \"Video Games\". The result will be:\n| Name | Hobbies |\n|------|---------|\n| John | Reading |\n| Tom  | Hiking   |"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_266548", "question": "How can I design a class in Java that represents a customer in an online shop?", "answer": "You can design a customer class in Java by creating a class called \"Customer\" and defining its properties and methods. Here's an example code:\n\n```java\npublic class Customer {\n    private final String name;\n    private final String address;\n    private final int age;\n    private final int purchaseCount;\n\n    public Customer(String name, String address, int age, int purchaseCount) {\n        this.name = name;\n        this.address = address;\n        this.age = age;\n        this.purchaseCount = purchaseCount;\n    }\n\n    public String getName() {\n        return name;\n    }\n\n    public String getAddress() {\n        return address;\n    }\n\n    public int getAge() {\n        return age;\n    }\n\n    public int getPurchaseCount() {\n        return purchaseCount;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `Customer` class has four instance variables: `name`, `address`, `age`, and `purchaseCount`. These variables are marked as `final`, which means their values cannot be changed once assigned. The class also has a constructor that takes these variables as parameters and assigns them to the respective instance variables.\n\nAdditionally, the class provides getter methods (`getName()`, `getAddress()`, `getAge()`, and `getPurchaseCount()`) to retrieve the values of these instance variables.\n\nBy using this class, you can create customer objects in your online shop and access their information easily."}
