{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_480222", "question": "Jordan picked 54 mangoes from his tree. One-third of the mangoes were ripe while the other two-thirds were not yet ripe. Jordan kept x unripe mangoes and gave the remainder to his sister who pickled them in glass jars. If it takes 4 mangoes to fill a jar, how many jars of pickled mangoes can Jordan's sister make?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 5, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Jordan picked 54 mangoes from his tree.\nOne-third of the mangoes were ripe, which means (1/3) * 54 = 18 mangoes were ripe.\nThe other two-thirds of the mangoes were not yet ripe, which means (2/3) * 54 = 36 mangoes were not yet ripe.\nJordan kept x unripe mangoes, which means he gave 36 - x mangoes to his sister.\nHis sister can make jars of pickled mangoes, and it takes 4 mangoes to fill a jar. So the number of jars she can make is (36 - x) / 4.\nWe are given that the number of jars his sister can make is 5, so we can write: (36 - x) / 4 = 5.\nMultiplying both sides by 4, we get: 36 - x = 20.\nSolving for x, we get: x = 16.\nThe value of x is 16.\n#### 16\nThe answer is: 16"}
