{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_247012", "question": "I have a list of strings and I want to find the index of a specific word in the list. How can I achieve this using Python?", "answer": "You can use the following code snippet to find the index of a search word in a list of strings.\n\n```python\ndef search(word_list, search_word):\n    for index, word in enumerate(word_list):\n        if word == search_word:\n            return index\n    return -1\n```\n\nIn the code above, the `search` function takes two parameters: `word_list`, which is the list of strings, and `search_word`, which is the word you want to find the index of. \n\nThe `enumerate` function is used to iterate over the `word_list` along with its corresponding indices. For each word in the list, the code checks if it matches the `search_word`. If a match is found, the function returns the index. If no match is found after iterating through the entire list, the function returns -1.\n\nYou can call this function by passing your list of strings and the search word as arguments. The function will return the index of the search word if it exists in the list, otherwise -1."}
