{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_55575", "question": "A cylinder has a radius of 5 cm and a height of 10 cm. What is the surface area of the cylinder in square centimeters?", "answer": "To find the surface area of a cylinder, we need to calculate the area of the two circular bases and the lateral surface area (the area around the cylinder). The formula for the surface area of a cylinder is:\n\nSurface Area = 2πr² + 2πrh\n\nwhere r is the radius and h is the height of the cylinder.\n\nGiven that the radius (r) is 5 cm and the height (h) is 10 cm, we can plug these values into the formula:\n\nSurface Area = 2π(5)² + 2π(5)(10)\n\nSurface Area = 2π(25) + 2π(50)\n\nSurface Area = 50π + 100π\n\nSurface Area = 150π\n\nNow, we can multiply by the value of π (approximately 3.14159):\n\nSurface Area ≈ 150 * 3.14159\n\nSurface Area ≈ 471.2385 cm²\n\nSo, the surface area of the cylinder is approximately 471.24 square centimeters."}
