 results in mild bilateral foraminal narrowing. No significant spinal canal stenosis is seen at any level.\n\nMild facet arthropathy is noted at C4-5 through C6-7 levels. However, no significant spinal canal stenosis is seen at any level.\n\nNo suspicious bone marrow abnormality is detected. The visualized posterior fossa is normal.\n\nOverall, the MRI findings suggest a relatively normal cervical spine. However, mild uncovertebral joint hypertrophy with foraminal narrowing is noted at C5-6 and C6-7 levels. This may explain the cervical radiculopathy symptoms experienced by the individual. \n\nIf available, comparison with previous MRI tests can provide valuable information regarding the progression or stability of the observed abnormalities. In case of the progression of symptoms or worsening of findings on imaging, a surgical intervention may be considered. However, in most cases, conservative measures such as physical therapy, medication, or steroid injections can be effective in managing the symptoms. A personalized treatment plan can be developed based on the individual's symptoms and the imaging findings."}
