{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_248977", "question": "How can I write a C program that checks whether a given number is a prime?", "answer": "You can achieve this by using the following C program:\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n \nint main() \n{\n    int n, i, flag=0;\n    scanf(\"%d\", &n);\n    for(i=2; i<=n/2; ++i)\n    {\n        if(n%i == 0)\n        {\n            flag = 1;\n            break;\n        }\n    }\n\n    if (flag==0)\n        printf(\"%d is a prime number.\", n);\n    else\n        printf(\"%d is not a prime number.\", n);\n    \n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nThis program starts by prompting the user to enter a number, `n`, which we want to check for primality. Then, we initiate the variables `i` (our divisor) and `flag` (used to track whether `n` is divisible by any number other than 1 and itself) with the value of 0.\n\nNext, we iterate through a for loop starting from 2, up to `n/2`. We check if `n` is divisible by `i` using the modulo operator (`%`). If the result is 0, it means `n` is divisible by `i` and we set `flag` to 1 and break out of the loop.\n\nAfter the loop, we check the value of `flag`. If it is still 0, it means that `n` is not divisible by any number other than 1 and itself, thus making it a prime number. We print the message `\"n is a prime number.\"`. Otherwise, if `flag` is 1, it means that `n` is divisible by at least one number other than 1 and itself, making it not a prime number. We print the message `\"n is not a prime number.\"`.\n\nFinally, we return 0 to indicate successful execution of the program."}
