{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_951333", "question": "Can you modify the \"technology_stocks\" table in the SQL database by adding two new columns for dividend yield and debt-to-equity ratio? In addition, can you update the stock prices and market capitalizations for each company to reflect current values? Furthermore, can you add data for two new technology companies, including their stock prices, market capitalizations, and industry? This will provide a more comprehensive understanding of the current technology stock market in Australia and enable investors to make more informed decisions.", "answer": "Yes, I can modify the \"technology_stocks\" table in the SQL database by adding two new columns for dividend yield and debt-to-equity ratio. To add the columns, I can use the ALTER TABLE statement as follows:\n\n```\nALTER TABLE technology_stocks ADD COLUMN dividend_yield DECIMAL(5,2);\nALTER TABLE technology_stocks ADD COLUMN debt_to_equity_ratio DECIMAL(5,2);\n```\n\nTo update the stock prices and market capitalizations for each company to reflect current values, I would need to obtain the most recent data for each company and then update the table accordingly. Assuming that I have the updated data in a CSV file, I can use the following SQL command to update the table:\n\n```\nUPDATE technology_stocks\nSET stock_price = new_stock_price, market_capitalization = new_market_capitalization\nWHERE ticker = company_ticker;\n```\n\nHere, \"new_stock_price\" and \"new_market_capitalization\" represent the updated values for each company, and \"company_ticker\" is the unique identifier for each company in the table.\n\nTo add data for two new technology companies, I can use the following SQL command:\n\n```\nINSERT INTO technology_stocks (ticker, company_name, industry, stock_price, market_capitalization, dividend_yield, debt_to_equity_ratio)\nVALUES ('NEW1', 'New Tech Company 1', 'Software', 10.50, 500000000, 2.50, 0.75),\n       ('NEW2', 'New Tech Company 2', 'Hardware', 8.25, 250000000, 1.75, 1.25);\n```\n\nThis will add two new rows to the \"technology_stocks\" table, each representing one of the new technology companies. The values in the parentheses correspond to the values for each column in the table."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_234594", "question": "I have a problem with using `setup.py` to setup a python package. My directory setup is as follows: \n\n```\nmaindir\n   |- setup.py\n   |-mymodule\n         |- __init__.py\n         |- mainmodule.py\n         |-subdir\n             |- __init__.py\n             |- submodule.py\n```\n\nThe file `submodule.py` contains `teststring = \"hello world\"`. `mainmodule.py` contains:\n\n```\nfrom .subdir import submodule\nmainstring = \"42\"\n```\n\nMy `setup.py` contains:\n\n```\nimport os\nfrom setuptools import setup\nsetup(\n    name = \"mytestmodule\",\n    version = \"0.0.1\",\n    description = (\"A simple module.\"),\n    packages=['mymodule'],\n)\n```\n\nWhen I do `from mymodule import mainmodule` with `ipython` from within `sourceTest`, the behavior works as expected and I can reference `mainmodule.submodule.teststring` which gives me the string `hello world`. \n\nBut, when I install this 'package' using `python setup.py install` and try to do the same (from within some other directory), I get an import error:\n\n```\nIn [1]: from mymodule import mainmodule\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nImportError                               Traceback (most recent call last)\n/home/alexander/<ipython-input-1-cf4c9bafa487> in <module>()\n----> 1 from mymodule import mainmodule\n\n/home/alexander/build/bdist.linux-i686/egg/mymodule/mainmodule.py in <module>()\n\nImportError: No module named subdir\n```\n\nI have followed a \"Getting started tutorial\" and \"rules for importing intra-packages\" but I still face this issue. Can someone help me solve this?", "answer": "The problem is that your `subdir` is not being recognized as a package by python because you have not included it in the `packages` list in your `setup.py` file.\n\nThe `packages` argument to the `setup()` function is a list of all Python import packages that are included in the distribution. Since, you have a package within a package, you need to include both in this list.\n\nYou should update your `setup.py` file as follows:\n\n```python\nimport os\nfrom setuptools import setup\nsetup(\n    name = \"mytestmodule\",\n    version = \"0.0.1\",\n    description = (\"A simple module.\"),\n    packages=['mymodule', 'mymodule.subdir'],\n)\n```\n\nThis will make sure that both `mymodule` and `mymodule.subdir` are installed when you run `python setup.py install`.\n\nAfter making these changes, you can reinstall your package and the import error should be resolved."}
