{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_375528", "question": "I have an MVC3 project in VS2010 (Project A) and I want to reference an assembly in one of my other projects (Project B). Project B outputs to \\bin\\Debug and \\bin\\Release. I want to add a reference to the proper Project B assembly, based on the configuration of Project A. Is there a way to do this without having to include Project B in Project A's solution? I've always included the project in my solution if I've needed to do this in the past, is this the only and best option?", "answer": "In my opinion, including Project B in Project A's solution is the better option if you have access to the project. However, if you want to reference the assembly without including Project B in the solution, you can modify the csproj file of Project A. \n\nTo achieve this, open the csproj file of Project A in a text editor and locate the reference to Project B. Modify the Reference hint by introducing a macro to dynamically set the reference path based on the current configuration. \n\nFor example, you can add the following code to A.csproj:\n\n```xml\n<Reference Include=\"B,...\">\n  <SpecificVersion>False</SpecificVersion>\n  <HintPath>..\\ProjectB\\bin\\$(Configuration)\\B.dll</HintPath>\n</Reference>\n```\n\nAfter saving the changes and reloading the project, the reference properties will show that the path changes based on the selected configuration. This allows you to reference the proper Project B assembly without including it in Project A's solution."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_126485", "question": "Compare and contrast coffee and tea.", "answer": "Coffee and tea are two of the most popular beverages consumed around the world, and both have been enjoyed for thousands of years. Despite their popularity, there are a number of differences between the two.\n\nOne of the most obvious differences between coffee and tea is that coffee is made from roasted coffee beans, while tea is made from the leaves, buds, and stems of the tea plant. Because of this, the production and processing of the two a bit different: coffee involves roasting, grinding, and brewing, while tea involves withering, rolling or crushing, oxidation, and firing or steaming.\n\nIn terms of taste, coffee and tea can both vary widely depending on the specific type, roast, and preparation method. Coffee is generally characterized as having a rich, bold flavor and aroma, while tea can range from delicate, floral notes to strong, earthy tastes.\n\nCaffeine content is another area where coffee and tea differ. A cup of coffee generally contains more caffeine than a cup of tea, although this can vary depending on several factors such as the type of tea or coffee, the preparation method, and the serving size.\n\nOne key similarity between coffee and tea is that both are known to have potential health benefits. Both contain antioxidants and other beneficial compounds, and research suggests that regular consumption of either drink may reduce the risk of several chronic diseases.\n\nIn summary, coffee and tea are two very different drinks that share some commonalities. Each has its own unique taste, production methods, and potential health benefits, making them both beloved choices for people around the world."}
