{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_233686", "question": "Is there a method to convert a gettext .mo file into a .po file, especially in a situation where the original .po file is no longer accessible? I need to alter the content of a .mo file but without the availability of the corresponding .po file. Is this conversion feasible?", "answer": "Yes, it is possible to convert gettext .mo files to .po files. This can be done using the `msgunfmt` command, which decompiles .mo files back into .po files. Here's how you can do it:\n\nStep 1: Firstly, you need to install the gettext utilities. \nIf you are using Ubuntu, you can install it using the following command in terminal:\n```\nsudo apt-get install gettext\n```\nFor macOS users, use brew to install gettext:\n```\nbrew install gettext\n```\nAnd for Windows, you can download it from [here](https://mlocati.github.io/articles/gettext-iconv-windows.html).\n\nStep 2: After installing gettext, use the `msgunfmt` command for conversion. The basic syntax of this command is as follows:\n```\nmsgunfmt [inputfile] -o [outputfile]\n```\nReplace `[inputfile]` with the path of your .mo file and `[outputfile]` with the desired output path of your .po file. \n\nFor example:\n```\nmsgunfmt messages.mo -o messages.po\n```\nThis command will convert the 'messages.mo' file into a 'messages.po' file.\n\nStep 3: Now, you can edit the .po file as per your requirements.\n\nRemember, the `msgunfmt` command doesn't recover comments and file positions from the .mo file. This information is discarded when the .po file is compiled into a .mo file."}
