{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_906132", "question": "Kevin's fish tank was leaking slowly at a rate of 1.5 ounces per hour. He planned to go to the fish tank store later that day to get a new tank, but it may be as long as 12 hours before he can return home with the new tank. Therefore, to collect the leaking fluid over that time, he placed a bucket underneath the tank that could hold twice the amount of fluid that would leak over 12 hours. What size bucket, in ounces, did he use? Give me reasons, before answering the question", "answer": "To calculate the size of the bucket Kevin used, we first need to determine the amount of fluid that will leak over the 12-hour period and then find a bucket that can hold twice that amount.\n\nStep 1: Calculate the amount of fluid leaked over 12 hours.\nWe know that the tank leaks at a rate of 1.5 ounces per hour. To find the total amount of fluid leaked over 12 hours, we multiply the leakage rate by the number of hours:\n\nLeakage rate: 1.5 ounces/hour\nHours: 12 hours\n\nTotal leakage: 1.5 ounces/hour * 12 hours = 18 ounces\n\nStep 2: Determine the size of the bucket needed.\nKevin wants a bucket that can hold twice the amount of fluid that will leak over 12 hours. So, we need to multiply the total leakage (18 ounces) by 2:\n\nBucket size: 18 ounces * 2 = 36 ounces\n\nTherefore, Kevin used a bucket that can hold 36 ounces to collect the leaking fluid over the 12-hour period."}
