{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_391105", "question": "I have a value stored in register AX and I need to check multiple bits at a time. Specifically, I want to check the first and last bits while the others are don't care values. However, my current approach is inefficient as I need to check for each value separately. Is there a more efficient way to do this using MASM?\n\n```assembly\nAND AX, 8001H\nCMP AX, 8001H\nJE\n```\n\nI have considered using the parity flag to check all the bits at once, but it seems that in MASM, the parity flag only checks the first 8 bits. Is there an alternative solution that can improve the efficiency of my code?", "answer": "To test if both the first and last bits are set, you will need two instructions (excluding the conditional jump). Your current approach takes up 6 bytes:\n\n```assembly\n25 01 80          AND   AX, 8001H\n3D 01 80          CMP   AX, 8001H\n```\n\nYou can save a byte by using the `NOT` instruction, which inverts all the bits, eliminating the need for the `CMP` instruction. The `NOT` instruction is only 2 bytes in size.\n\n```assembly\nF7 D0             NOT   AX\n25 01 80          AND   AX, 8001H\n```\n\nIf these instructions are executed in a loop multiple times, and you have an extra register available, you can save another byte. Although the total amount of code increases, you can keep part of it outside the loop, resulting in slightly faster execution.\n\n```assembly\nBB 01 80          MOV   BX, 8001H   ; keep this outside the loop\n...               ...\nF7 D0             NOT   AX\n21 D8             AND   AX, BX\n```\n\n**EDIT:**\nThere is one more possibility for improvement. If you are always testing whether one or more bits are set, you can consider flipping the meaning of zeroes and ones throughout your function or even the entire program. This means defining zero as true and one as false. In digital circuits, this is a common practice. By doing this, you can eliminate the `NOT AX` instruction, saving two more bytes. Additionally, you can replace `AND` with the non-destructive `TEST` instruction, allowing you to perform multiple tests without needing to save and restore the value in AX. However, to determine if this is applicable in your specific case, I would need to see more of your code."}
