{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_228571", "question": "I am trying to understand the use of Python's 3.5 async/await feature. I have read several articles and tutorials on this, but I am still confused with the use of get_event_loop() and run_until_complete(), ensure_future(), asyncio.wait(), and call_soon(). I also noticed that all examples use asyncio.sleep() as a simulation of slow operation which returns an awaitable object. However, when I try to replace this with real code, it doesn't work. Specifically, I am using the Quandl library to fetch some stock data, but I am unsure how to make it async/await ready. Here is my code:\n\n```\nimport asyncio\nimport quandl\n\nasync def slow_operation(n):\n    # await asyncio.sleep(1) # Works because it's await ready.\n    await quandl.Dataset(n) # Doesn't work because it's not await ready.\n\n\nasync def main():\n    await asyncio.wait([\n        slow_operation(\"SIX/US9884981013EUR4\"),\n        slow_operation(\"SIX/US88160R1014EUR4\"),\n    ])\n\n# You don't have to use any code for 50 requests/day.\nquandl.ApiConfig.api_key = \"MY_SECRET_CODE\"\n\nloop = asyncio.get_event_loop()\nloop.run_until_complete(main())\n```\nWhat is the difference between the approaches mentioned above and how do I run a third-party library which is not ready for async/await?", "answer": "The issue you're facing arises because the Quandl library is not designed to be used with async/await, and hence it does not produce awaitable objects. This means you can't use `await` with `quandl.Dataset(n)`. \n\nTo resolve this issue, you can use the `run_in_executor` method provided by asyncio. This allows you to run blocking IO-bound functions in separate threads. Here is an example of how to use it:\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\nimport quandl\n\ndef slow_operation(n):\n    # This is a blocking call.\n    return quandl.Dataset(n)\n\nasync def main():\n    loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()\n\n    # Create tasks for slow_operation.\n    tasks = [\n        loop.run_in_executor(None, slow_operation, \"SIX/US9884981013EUR4\"),\n        loop.run_in_executor(None, slow_operation, \"SIX/US88160R1014EUR4\"),\n    ]\n\n    # Wait for all tasks to complete.\n    await asyncio.wait(tasks)\n\n# You don't have to use any code for 50 requests/day.\nquandl.ApiConfig.api_key = \"MY_SECRET_CODE\"\n\nloop = asyncio.get_event_loop()\nloop.run_until_complete(main())\n```\nIn the code above, the `None` argument to `run_in_executor` means that the default executor is used. This is a `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` with `max_workers` equal to `5 * (number of CPUs)`. If you need a different max_workers value, you can create your own `ThreadPoolExecutor` and pass it as the first argument to `run_in_executor`.\n\nRemember to be careful when using threads in Python due to the Global Interpreter Lock (GIL). In this case, you're primarily dealing with IO-bound operations (network requests), so the GIL won't be a significant issue."}
