{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_257161", "question": "How can I create a React application for a simple calculator that accepts integer inputs, performs calculations, and displays the result?", "answer": "You can create a React application for a calculator by using the following code:\n\n```jsx\nimport React, { useState } from 'react'\n\nconst Calculator = () => {\n  const [num1, setNum1] = useState('')\n  const [num2, setNum2] = useState('')\n  const [result, setResult] = useState(0)\n\n  const calculateResult = () => {\n    let res = 0\n    let n1 = parseInt(num1)\n    let n2 = parseInt(num2)\n\n    if (n1 && n2) {\n      res = n1 + n2\n      setResult(res)\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <input\n        type=\"number\"\n        value={num1}\n        onChange={e => setNum1(e.target.value)}\n      />\n      <input\n        type=\"number\"\n        value={num2}\n        onChange={e => setNum2(e.target.value)}\n      />\n      <button onClick={calculateResult}>Result</button>\n      <p>Result: {result}</p>\n    </div>\n  )\n}\n\nexport default Calculator\n```\nThis code uses the `useState` hook from React to define three state variables: `num1`, `num2`, and `result`. The `num1` and `num2` variables store the input values from the two input fields, while the `result` variable holds the calculated result. \n\nThe `calculateResult` function is triggered when the \"Result\" button is clicked. It converts the input values to integers using `parseInt` and performs the addition operation. If both input values are valid integers, the result is updated using the `setResult` function.\n\nThe JSX code renders two input fields for number input, a button for triggering the calculation, and a paragraph tag to display the result.\n\nOverall, this React component creates a simple calculator that takes integer inputs, performs addition, and displays the result."}
