{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_346309", "question": "<p>How does the .NET framework resolve assemblies with fully qualified names? I am confused about the concepts of public/private key tokens and strong naming. Can someone explain it to me in detail? Also, I have heard about delayed signing. Is it commonly used? Who generates the key to sign an assembly? Apologies if I am asking too many questions, but I really need clarification on this topic.</p>", "answer": "<p>When it comes to resolving assemblies in .NET, the process involves strong naming and the use of a public key token. Let me explain it in detail:</p>\n\n<p>Strong naming is a technique used to sign assemblies and provide a unique identity to them. It ensures that the assembly has not been tampered with since it was distributed. The strong name includes information like the assembly's name, version, culture, and a public/private key pair. This information is used to generate a unique assembly full display name, such as \"mscorlib, version=2.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b4778,.....\".</p>\n\n<p>The public key token, which is derived from the strong name, plays a crucial role in resolving assemblies. It allows the .NET loader to detect any modifications made to the assembly after distribution. When an assembly is signed with a private key, the compiler generates a hash value based on the public portion of the private key. This hash value is embedded in the assembly metadata. The loader can then compare this hash value to ensure the assembly has not been tampered with.</p>\n\n<p>Regarding your question about delayed signing, it is a practice where an assembly is signed at a later stage, typically during deployment. It allows developers to work on the code without having access to the private key used for signing. Delayed signing can be useful in scenarios where multiple developers are working on different parts of an assembly, and the final signing is done by a release engineer or a dedicated signing process. However, it is not commonly used in all development scenarios.</p>\n\n<p>As for generating the key to sign an assembly, it is typically done by the developer or the team responsible for the assembly. The key generation process involves creating a key pair consisting of a public key and a private key. The private key is kept secure and used for signing the assembly, while the public key is embedded in the assembly for verification purposes.</p>\n\n<p>Now, let's discuss how assemblies are resolved in .NET:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Probing:</strong> The .NET loader attempts to locate assemblies by using a probing technique. It searches for the assembly in the application's startup directory and its subdirectories. If the assembly is not found, the <code>AppDomain</code>'s <code>AssemblyResolve</code> event is triggered. This event allows custom resolution of assemblies.</li>\n<li><strong>Machine/User/System configuration:</strong> The .NET resolver can be configured at the machine, user, or system level using configuration files like <code>machine.config</code>, <code>user.config</code>, and <code>system.config</code>. These files enable changing the resolver's behavior globally.</li>\n<li><strong>Publisher Policy:</strong> The application's configuration file, such as <code>MyApp.exe.config</code>, can specify a certain version of an assembly or a different location to load the assembly from using the \"<code>&lt;assemblyIdentity&gt;</code>\" XML token.</li>\n<li><strong>Custom resolution:</strong> The <code>AssemblyResolve</code> event of the <code>AppDomain</code> allows developers to handle assembly resolution in a custom manner. This event is raised when an assembly cannot be resolved using the traditional methods mentioned above.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In summary, the .NET assembly resolver follows a process of probing, configuration, publisher policy, and custom resolution to locate and load assemblies. Handling the <code>AssemblyResolve</code> event is a common approach for custom resolution.</p>"}
