{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_865880", "question": "Are all students guaranteed lunch at school in the US?\nChain of thought:", "answer": "1. The question asks if all students in the US are guaranteed lunch at school.\n2. This implies that there should be a nationwide policy or law that ensures students have access to lunch during school hours.\n3. The National School Lunch Program (NSLP) is a federal program that provides low-cost or free lunches to eligible students in public and nonprofit private schools in the United States.\n4. The NSLP sets guidelines and provides funding for schools to offer nutritious meals to students.\n5. However, not all students are automatically eligible for free or reduced-price lunches under the NSLP; eligibility is based on income level and other factors.\n6. While the NSLP aims to provide access to lunch for as many students as possible, it does not guarantee that every student in the US will receive lunch at school.\n7. Schools may have additional programs or resources in place to help provide lunch for students who don't qualify for the NSLP or who cannot afford to pay for lunch.\n\nBased on this chain of thought, the answer is no, not all students are guaranteed lunch at school in the US. However, there are programs like the National School Lunch Program that aim to provide affordable lunches for eligible students, and schools may have additional resources to help students who need assistance."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_920662", "question": "Of the 60 students in the drama club, 36 take mathematics, 27 take physics and 20 students take both mathematics and physics. How many drama club students take neither mathematics nor physics?", "answer": "I need to find out how many students take neither mathematics nor physics, so I will start by finding out how many students take either mathematics or physics, or both. To do that, I will use the formula for the union of two sets: |A ∪ B| = |A| + |B| - |A ∩ B|, where A is the set of students who take mathematics and B is the set of students who take physics. In this case, |A ∪ B| is the number of students who take either mathematics or physics, or both, |A| is 36, |B| is 27, and |A ∩ B| is 20. Plugging in these values, I get |A ∪ B| = 36 + 27 - 20 = 43. This means that 43 students take either mathematics or physics, or both. To find out how many students take neither mathematics nor physics, I will subtract this number from the total number of students in the drama club, which is 60. So, 60 - 43 = 17. Therefore, 17 drama club students take neither mathematics nor physics."}
