{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_914863", "question": "Question: Carlos is doing his laundry. He needs to wash two loads, which takes 45 minutes per load. Then he can combine both loads and dry them, which takes 75 minutes. How long does his laundry take in total? Think carefully first, then make a decision:", "answer": "Step 1: Calculate the time it takes to wash both loads.\nCarlos needs to wash two loads of laundry, and each load takes 45 minutes. To find the total washing time, we can multiply the time per load by the number of loads:\n\n45 minutes/load × 2 loads = 90 minutes for washing\n\nStep 2: Add the drying time.\nCarlos can combine both loads and dry them, which takes 75 minutes. To find the total laundry time, we can add the washing time and drying time:\n\n90 minutes (washing) + 75 minutes (drying) = 165 minutes\n\nDecision: Carlos's laundry takes a total of 165 minutes to complete."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_412672", "question": "Implement a Python function to merge two sorted lists into a new, sorted list.\n[1, 3, 5], [2, 4, 6]", "answer": "def merge_sorted_lists(list1, list2):\n    result = []\n    i, j = 0, 0\n\n    while i < len(list1) and j < len(list2):\n        if list1[i] < list2[j]:\n            result.append(list1[i])\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            result.append(list2[j])\n            j += 1\n\n    result.extend(list1[i:])\n    result.extend(list2[j:])\n\n    return result\n\nmerged_list = merge_sorted_lists([1, 3, 5], [2, 4, 6])\nprint(merged_list)"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_887282", "question": "[TEACHER] Which of these sentences doesn't make sense?\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"People bitten by dogs need to break the cold vaccine.\"\n- Sentence B: \"People bitten by dogs need rabies vaccine.\"\n\n[Student] Tetanus vaccine has no effect on rabies virus.\nThe answer is Sentence A.\n\n\nTeacher: Of the following two sentences, which one is against common sense?\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"Caesar has secretly raised opponents in the enemy country and they will put Caesar's rival down the throne\"\n- Sentence B: \"Caesar has secretly raised opponents in the enemy country and they will pull Caesar's rival down the throne\"\n\nStudent: Putting his rival down the thrown would not be beneficial to Caesar.\nThe answer is Sentence A.\n\n\nquestion in book:\nOne of the following sentences is nonsensical. Which one is it?\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"The grass is growing.\"\n- Sentence B: \"The grass is singing.\"\n\nstandard solution:\nGrass does not have voice or mouth to make noise.\nThe answer is Sentence B.\n\n\n[TEACHER] Pick which sentence is not logical.\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"dad drives his own car\"\n- Sentence B: \"dad can drive two cars at the same time\"\n\n[Student] Dad only has one pair of arms and legs and can only drive one car at a time.\nThe answer is Sentence B.\n\n\nTeacher: Which of the following two sentences does not make sense?\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"Football is square\"\n- Sentence B: \"Football is round\"\n\nStudent: The football couldn't fly through the air if it was square.\nThe answer is Sentence A.\n\n\nquestion in book:\nPick which sentence is not logical.\nOptions:\n- Sentence A: \"He stares at the CPU to watch the movie\"\n- Sentence B: \"He stares at the screen to watch the movie\"\n\nstandard solution:", "answer": "The CPU is the central processing unit of a computer and is not used for displaying visuals.\nThe answer is Sentence A."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_764850", "question": "Here is a question about this article: John Evans, for whom Evanston is named, bought 379 acres (153 ha) of land along Lake Michigan in 1853, and Philo Judson developed plans for what would become the city of Evanston, Illinois. The first building, Old College, opened on November 5, 1855. To raise funds for its construction, Northwestern sold $100 \"perpetual scholarships\" entitling the purchaser and his heirs to free tuition. Another building, University Hall, was built in 1869 of the same Joliet limestone as the Chicago Water Tower, also built in 1869, one of the few buildings in the heart of Chicago to survive the Great Chicago Fire of 1871. In 1873 the Evanston College for Ladies merged with Northwestern, and Frances Willard, who later gained fame as a suffragette and as one of the founders of the Woman's Christian Temperance Union (WCTU), became the school's first dean of women. Willard Residential College (1938) is named in her honor. Northwestern admitted its first women students in 1869, and the first woman was graduated in 1874.\nWhat is the answer to this question: Who was Northwestern's first dean of women?", "answer": "The answer to the question is: Frances Willard was Northwestern's first dean of women."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_789665", "question": "Answer the following question: Read the following article and select the best answer. Article: When I was six, dad brought home a dog one day, who was called \"Brownie\". My brothers and I all loved Brownie and did different things with her. One of us would walk her, another would feed her, then there were baths, playing catch and many other games. Brownie, in return, loved each other and every one of us. One thing that most touched my heart was that she would go to whoever was sick and just be with them. We always felt better when she was around. One day , as I was getting her food, she chewed up one of dad's shoes, which had to be thrown away in the end. I knew dad would be mad and I had to let her know what she did was wrong. When I looked at her and said, \"Bad girl,\" she looked down at the ground and then went and hid. I saw a tear in her eyes. Brownie turned out to be more than just our family pet. She went everywhere with us. People would stop and ask if they could pet her. Of course she'd let anyone pet her. She was just the most lovable dog. There were many times when we'd be out walking and a small child would come over and pull on her hair. She never barked or tried to get away. Funny thing is she would smile. This frightened people because they thought she was showing her teeth. Far from the truth, she loved everyone. Question: Which of the following best describes Brownie? - Shy - Polite - Brave - Caring\nAnswer:", "answer": "Caring best describes Brownie. The article highlights several instances that showcase her caring nature, such as going to the person who was sick in the family, allowing strangers to pet her, and patiently tolerating small children pulling on her hair without protest. Brownie's loving interactions with both her family and strangers demonstrate her caring personality."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_72548", "question": "How many different 5-card hands can be dealt from a standard deck of 52 cards?", "answer": "To find the number of different 5-card hands that can be dealt from a standard deck of 52 cards, we can use the combination formula. The combination formula is:\n\nC(n, k) = n! / (k!(n-k)!)\n\nwhere n is the total number of items, k is the number of items to choose, and ! denotes the factorial (the product of all positive integers up to that number).\n\nIn this case, n = 52 (total number of cards in the deck) and k = 5 (number of cards in a hand).\n\nC(52, 5) = 52! / (5!(52-5)!)\n\nC(52, 5) = 52! / (5!47!)\n\nC(52, 5) = (52 × 51 × 50 × 49 × 48) / (5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1)\n\nC(52, 5) = 2,598,960\n\nSo, there are 2,598,960 different 5-card hands that can be dealt from a standard deck of 52 cards."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_342711", "question": "I have a .Net Standard library, and I'm encountering an error when trying to use one of the dependent libraries. I suspect that the error is caused by a version conflict. In a traditional .Net Class library, I would typically resolve this issue by adding a binding redirect in the configuration file. However, since I am working with a .Net Standard library, I am unable to do that. Can someone please guide me on how to address such version conflicts in the .Net Standard world?", "answer": "In the .Net Standard and .Net Core world, binding redirects, which are a concept in the .NET Framework, are not available. However, there is an alternative strategy to resolve version conflicts.\n\nIn the .NET Core environment, the resolution of dependencies is done through a generated `deps.json` file, which is based on the build input. On the other hand, the .NET Framework applications still use binding redirects.\n\nIf a binding redirect is necessary, it needs to be added to the .NET Framework application or library that is utilizing the .NET Standard library.\n\nTo simplify the process of using the correct binding redirects, you can configure the .NET Framework app or library by setting the following properties in the csproj/vbproj file (the second property is not required for projects generating .exe executables, but it is needed for unit test projects):\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n    <AutoGenerateBindingRedirects>true</AutoGenerateBindingRedirects>\n    <GenerateBindingRedirectsOutputType>true</GenerateBindingRedirectsOutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nBy setting these properties, the correct binding redirects will be automatically generated during the build process, based on the assemblies used during compilation. This automatic generation of binding redirects is handled seamlessly when using NuGet's `PackageReference` style for referencing NuGet packages.\n\nFor more detailed descriptions on how to configure binding redirects correctly based on different project types, you can refer to the announcement titled \"Issues with .NET Standard 2.0 with .NET Framework & NuGet\" on GitHub.\n\nRemember to keep the code in the original question intact and avoid using HTML in your answers."}
