{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_175051", "question": "How can I organize a school supply room containing books, pens, and pencils according to the following rules:\n1. Each item must be placed in its designated area.\n2. Books should be placed on shelves, with a maximum of 10 books per shelf.\n3. Pens should be placed in drawers, with a maximum of 50 pens per drawer.\n4. Pencils should be placed in boxes, with a maximum of 20 pencils per box.\n5. Each item must be labeled with a unique code, consisting of a letter followed by a number. \"B\" for books, \"P\" for pens, and \"C\" for pencils. The number represents the item's location (shelf, drawer, or box).\nHere is the data in JSON format:\n{\n  \"books\": {\n    \"shelves\": 0,\n    \"last_code\": \"\"\n  },\n  \"pens\": {\n    \"drawers\": 0,\n    \"last_code\": \"\"\n  },\n  \"pencils\": {\n    \"boxes\": 0,\n    \"last_code\": \"\"\n  }\n}\nHow many shelves, drawers, and boxes do I need to organize all items? And what will be the unique code for the last item in each designated area?", "answer": "To organize all items, you will need:\n- Shelves: ceil(total number of books / 10)\n- Drawers: ceil(total number of pens / 50)\n- Boxes: ceil(total number of pencils / 20)\nLet's assume you have 150 books, 500 pens, and 200 pencils. Then you will need:\n- Shelves: ceil(150 / 10) = 15 shelves\n- Drawers: ceil(500 / 50) = 10 drawers\n- Boxes: ceil(200 / 20) = 10 boxes\nThe unique code for the last item in each designated area will be:\n- Books: B15\n- Pens: P10\n- Pencils: C10\nNote that the \"last_code\" attribute in the JSON data can be used to keep track of the last code used in each designated area. After adding an item, you can update the \"last_code\" attribute to generate the next unique code."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_395599", "question": "I'm performing the following request in golang:\n\n```go\nrequest := &http.Request{\n        URL:           url,\n        Body:          requestBody, //io.ReadCloser containing the body\n        Method:        http.MethodPost,\n        ContentLength: int64(len(postBody)),\n        Header:        make(http.Header),\n        Proto:         \"HTTP/1.1\",\n        ProtoMajor:    1,\n        ProtoMinor:    1,\n    }\n\nres, err := http.DefaultClient.Do(request)\n\n//Printing the request:\ndump, dumpErr := httputil.DumpRequest(request, true)\nif dumpErr != nil {\n   log.Fatal(\"Cannot dump the request\")\n}\nlog.Println(string(dump))\n```\n\nI want to specify the host in the path of the post request. Is it possible?\n\nExpected result:\n\n```\nPOST \"http://127.0.0.1:10019/system?action=add_servers\" HTTP/1.1\nHost: 127.0.0.1:10019\nAccept: \"*/*\"\nConnection: keep-alive\n```\n\nActual result:\n\n```\nPOST \"/system?action=add_servers\" HTTP/1.1\nHost: 127.0.0.1:10019\nAccept: \"*/*\"\nConnection: keep-alive\n```", "answer": "To specify the host in the path of the post request, you can set the `Request.URL` to an opaque URL. The opaque URL will be written to the request line as is. Here's an example:\n\n```go\nrequest := &http.Request{\n        URL:           &url.URL{Opaque: \"http://127.0.0.1:10019/system?action=add_servers\"},\n        Body:          requestBody, //io.ReadCloser containing the body\n        Method:        http.MethodPost,\n        ContentLength: int64(len(postBody)),\n        Header:        make(http.Header),\n        Proto:         \"HTTP/1.1\",\n        ProtoMajor:    1,\n        ProtoMinor:    1,\n    }\n```\n\nAlternatively, you can use the `http.NewRequest` function to create the request and then set the `Request.URL` to the opaque URL. Here's an example:\n\n```go\nu := \"http://127.0.0.1:10019/system?action=add_servers\"\nrequest, err := http.NewRequest(\"POST\", u, requestBody)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\nrequest.URL = &url.URL{Opaque: u}\n\nres, err := http.DefaultClient.Do(request)\n```\n\nBoth approaches will allow you to specify the host in the path of the post request."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_84787", "question": "Find all the possible subgroups of a group of order 36 and determine which of these subgroups are normal. Then, use this information to prove that every group of order 36 is isomorphic to either the cyclic group C36, the alternating group A4 × C3, or one of the nine non-abelian groups of order 36.", "answer": "Let G be a group of order 36. Since 36 = 2^2 * 3^2, by the Sylow theorems, we know that there are Sylow 2-subgroups and Sylow 3-subgroups in G. Let's find the possible number of these subgroups and their structures.\n\nFor Sylow 2-subgroups:\nBy the Sylow theorems, the number of Sylow 2-subgroups, n_2, must divide 3^2 = 9 and n_2 ≡ 1 (mod 2). So, n_2 can be 1 or 9. If n_2 = 1, then there is a unique Sylow 2-subgroup, which is normal. If n_2 = 9, then there are 9 Sylow 2-subgroups, and they are not normal. The possible structures for a group of order 4 are C4 (cyclic) and V4 (Klein-4 group).\n\nFor Sylow 3-subgroups:\nBy the Sylow theorems, the number of Sylow 3-subgroups, n_3, must divide 2^2 = 4 and n_3 ≡ 1 (mod 3). So, n_3 can be 1 or 4. If n_3 = 1, then there is a unique Sylow 3-subgroup, which is normal. If n_3 = 4, then there are 4 Sylow 3-subgroups, and they are not normal. The possible structures for a group of order 9 are C9 (cyclic) and C3 × C3.\n\nNow, let's analyze the possible structures for G:\n\n1. If G has a unique normal Sylow 2-subgroup and a unique normal Sylow 3-subgroup, then G is isomorphic to C4 × C9 or C4 × (C3 × C3) or V4 × C9 or V4 × (C3 × C3). The first two cases are abelian, and the last two cases are non-abelian.\n\n2. If G has a unique normal Sylow 2-subgroup and 4 non-normal Sylow 3-subgroups, then G is a semi-direct product of C4 or V4 with C3 × C3. This gives four non-abelian groups.\n\n3. If G has 9 non-normal Sylow 2-subgroups and a unique normal Sylow 3-subgroup, then G is a semi-direct product of C9 or (C3 × C3) with C4. This gives two non-abelian groups.\n\n4. If G has 9 non-normal Sylow 2-subgroups and 4 non-normal Sylow 3-subgroups, then G is isomorphic to the alternating group A4 × C3, which is non-abelian.\n\nIn total, we have 2 abelian groups (C36 and C4 × C9) and 9 non-abelian groups. Therefore, every group of order 36 is isomorphic to either the cyclic group C36, the alternating group A4 × C3, or one of the nine non-abelian groups of order 36."}
