{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_253489", "question": "Can you provide a code snippet to create a full binary tree from a given array of keys?", "answer": "Certainly! Here's a code example that demonstrates how to create a full binary tree from an array of keys. The code is written in Python.\n\n```python\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, data):\n        self.data = data\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\ndef array_to_tree(arr):\n    if not arr:\n        return None\n\n    mid = len(arr) // 2\n    root = Node(arr[mid])\n    root.left = array_to_tree(arr[:mid])\n    root.right = array_to_tree(arr[mid + 1:])\n\n    return root\n\narr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]\nroot = array_to_tree(arr)\n```\n\nIn this code, we define a `Node` class that represents a node in the binary tree. Each node has a `data` attribute to store the value and `left` and `right` attributes to reference its left and right child nodes, respectively.\n\nThe `array_to_tree` function takes the input array `arr` as a parameter. It first checks if the array is empty. If it is, it returns `None` to indicate an empty tree.\n\nNext, it calculates the `mid` index of the array by dividing the length of the array by 2. It then creates a new node with the value at the `mid` index and assigns it to the `root` variable.\n\nThe function recursively calls itself to create the left and right subtrees. For the left subtree, it passes the slice of the array from the beginning to the `mid` index (excluding `mid`). For the right subtree, it passes the slice of the array from `mid+1` to the end. These slices represent the left and right halves of the original array.\n\nFinally, the function returns the `root` node, which represents the fully constructed binary tree.\n\nTo use this code, you can provide your own array of keys by modifying the `arr` variable in the code. The resulting binary tree will be stored in the `root` variable."}
