{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_349157", "question": "How can I write a function in Javascript to check if every given 2D list is a palindrome sequence? For example, let's say our 2D list looks like [[1, 2, 3, 2, 1], [2, 3, 4, 3, 2], [3, 4, 5, 4, 3]]. To make the program more challenging, I should use recursion and limit the use of built-in functions like reverse or join, etc. Also, the time and space complexity should be relatively low. Can you provide a solution using ES6 syntax?", "answer": "Here is a possible solution:\n\n```javascript\nfunction is2DListPalindrome(arr) {\n    if (arr.length === 0) return true;  // Base case for empty list\n\n    // Check if the first element in the current list is a palindrome\n    const first = arr[0];\n    for (let i = 0, j = first.length - 1; i < Math.floor(first.length / 2); i++, j--) {\n        if (first[i] !== first[j]) return false;\n    }\n\n    // Recursively check the remaining lists\n    return is2DListPalindrome(arr.slice(1));\n}\n\n// Test\nconst arr = [[1, 2, 3, 2, 1], [2, 3, 4, 3, 2], [3, 4, 5, 4, 3]];\nconsole.log(is2DListPalindrome(arr));  // true\n```\n\nIn this program, we first check if the first element in the list is a palindrome. If it's not, we immediately return `false`. If it is, we recursively continue checking the next element until all elements have been checked.\n\nThe time complexity of this solution is O(n²), where n is the total number of elements (the average number of elements in each list multiplied by the number of lists)."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_335642", "question": "How can I create an API for a library application in Python that includes endpoints for creating a book, listing all books, updating a book, and deleting a book?", "answer": "You can create the API using Python and Flask. Here is an example code that demonstrates how to achieve this:\n\n```python\nimport flask\nfrom flask import request, jsonify\n\napp = flask.Flask(__name__)\n\n# Database functionality\n# classes used to represent the objects\nclass Book():\n    def __init__(self, title, author, isbn):\n        self.title = title\n        self.author = author\n        self.isbn = isbn\n\n# lists of books\nbooks = []\n\n# endpoints\n@app.route('/books', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef all_books():\n    response_object = {'status': 'success'}\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        post_data = request.get_json()\n        books.append(Book(post_data.get('title'), post_data.get('author'), post_data.get('isbn')))\n        response_object['message'] = 'Book added!'\n    else:\n        response_object['books'] = [book.__dict__ for book in books] \n\n    return jsonify(response_object)\n\n@app.route('/books/<int:isbn>', methods=['PUT', 'DELETE'])\ndef single_book(isbn):\n    response_object = {'status': 'success'}\n    if request.method == 'PUT':\n        post_data = request.get_json()\n        book = next(filter(lambda x: x.isbn == isbn, books), None)\n        if book:\n            book.title = post_data.get('title')\n            book.author = post_data.get('author')\n            response_object['message'] = 'Book updated'\n        else:\n            response_object['message'] = 'Book does not exist'\n    if request.method == 'DELETE':\n        global books\n        books = list(filter(lambda x: x.isbn != isbn, books))\n        response_object['message'] = 'Book deleted'\n    return jsonify(response_object)\n\n# Run the application\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()\n```\n\nThis code defines a Flask application that creates an API for a library application. It includes two endpoints: `/books` and `/books/<int:isbn>`. \n\nThe `/books` endpoint accepts both GET and POST requests. GET request returns a list of all books in the library, while POST request allows you to create a new book by providing the title, author, and ISBN as JSON data in the request body.\n\nThe `/books/<int:isbn>` endpoint accepts both PUT and DELETE requests. PUT request allows you to update an existing book by providing the ISBN of the book you want to update and the updated title and author as JSON data in the request body. DELETE request allows you to delete a book by providing the ISBN of the book you want to delete.\n\nThe API maintains a list of books as an in-memory database. When a book is created, it is added to the `books` list. When a book is updated, the corresponding book object is found based on the ISBN and its title and author are updated. When a book is deleted, the book object is removed from the `books` list.\n\nThe API returns JSON response objects with a status and a message indicating the success or failure of the request. When listing all books, the API returns a list of books as well.\n\nYou can run this application and then make requests to the defined endpoints to interact with the library application via the API."}
