{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_231684", "question": "I am trying to train a LSTM layer in PyTorch using 4 GPUs. Upon initializing, I used the .cuda() function to move the hidden layer to the GPU. However, when I run the code with multiple GPUs, I encounter a RuntimeError: \"Input and hidden tensors are not at the same device\". I attempted to use the .cuda() function in the forward function, as shown below:\n\n```python\nself.hidden = (self.hidden[0].type(torch.FloatTensor).cuda(), self.hidden[1].type(torch.FloatTensor).cuda())\n```\n\nThis seems to resolve the issue, but I am concerned about whether the updated hidden layer is seen across different GPUs. Should I move the vector back to the CPU at the end of the forward function for a batch, or is there another solution to this problem?", "answer": "This issue may arise if the input and hidden states of your LSTM are not on the same device (i.e., one is on the CPU and the other is on the GPU) or if they are not on the same GPU when using multiple GPUs.\n\nPyTorch's nn.DataParallel function might be causing this issue. This function splits your input into several chunks, which are then separately sent to your GPUs. Each GPU is then used to forward its chunk independently. If your model uses some form of state (like the hidden state in an LSTM), this can cause issues because the state is not being shared across GPUs.\n\nTo resolve this, you might need to modify your code to ensure that the hidden state is on the same device as the input data. Here's a simple way of doing this:\n\n```python\nclass MyModule(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self):\n        super(MyModule, self).__init__()\n        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(10, 10)\n        self.gpu = 0\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        self.gpu = x.get_device() if x.is_cuda else -1\n        h0 = torch.zeros(1, 1, 10)\n        c0 = torch.zeros(1, 1, 10)\n        if self.gpu > -1:\n            h0 = h0.cuda(self.gpu)\n            c0 = c0.cuda(self.gpu)\n        self.hidden = (h0, c0)\n        out, self.hidden = self.lstm(x, self.hidden)\n        return out\n```\n\nIn the above code, we first check if the input data is on a GPU, and if so, which one (this is stored in self.gpu). We then ensure that the initial hidden state is created on the correct device."}
