{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_332840", "question": "I want to create a JavaScript function that takes an array of strings and returns an ordered list of all the unique words in that array. Can you help me with the code?", "answer": "Sure! Here is a JavaScript function that solves your problem:\n\n```javascript\nfunction orderUniqueWords(arrOfStrings) {\n    // Create an output array\n    let orderedList = [];\n\n    // Parse through each string\n    for (let string of arrOfStrings) {\n        let words = string.split(\" \");\n        // Parse through each word\n        for (let word of words) {\n            // If the word is not in the orderedList, add it\n            if (!orderedList.includes(word)) {\n                orderedList.push(word);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Sort the array\n    orderedList.sort();\n    return orderedList;\n}\n```\n\nThis function takes the input array `arrOfStrings` and initializes an empty array called `orderedList` to store the unique words. Then, it loops through each string in `arrOfStrings` and splits it into an array of words using the `split(\" \")` method.\n\nNext, it iterates through each word and checks if it already exists in the `orderedList`. If the word is not found, it is added to the `orderedList` using the `push()` method.\n\nFinally, the `orderedList` is sorted in alphabetical order using the `sort()` method and returned as the output.\n\nYou can use this function by passing an array of strings as an argument. It will return an ordered list of all the unique words present in the input array."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_253555", "question": "What is the algorithm in JavaScript to convert between different temperature units?", "answer": "You can use the following function in JavaScript to convert between different temperature units:\n\n```javascript\nfunction convertTemp(temp, inputUnit, outputUnit) {\n    if (inputUnit === 'C') {\n        if (outputUnit === 'F') {\n            return temp * (9/5) + 32;\n        } else if (outputUnit === 'K') {\n            return temp + 273.15;\n        } else {\n            return temp;\n        }\n    } else if (inputUnit === 'F') {\n        if (outputUnit === 'C') {\n            return (temp - 32) * (5/9);\n        } else if (outputUnit === 'K') {\n            return (temp + 459.67) * (5/9);\n        } else {\n            return temp;\n        }\n    } else if (inputUnit === 'K') {\n        if (outputUnit === 'C') {\n            return temp - 273.15;\n        } else if (outputUnit === 'F') {\n            return temp * (9/5) - 459.67;\n        } else {\n            return temp;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis function takes three parameters: `temp` (the temperature value), `inputUnit` (the unit of the input temperature), and `outputUnit` (the desired unit of the output temperature). It uses conditional statements to check the input unit and output unit, and performs the appropriate calculations to convert the temperature. The function returns the converted temperature value.\n\nFor example, if you want to convert 45 degree Celsius to Fahrenheit, you can use the function as follows:\n\n```javascript\nlet convertedTemp = convertTemp(45, 'C', 'F');\nconsole.log(convertedTemp); // Output: 113\n```\n\nIn this case, the function will convert 45 degree Celsius to Fahrenheit and return the converted value, which is 113."}
