{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_292283", "question": "How can I create a Node.js server script that listens on a specific port and sends a 'Hello World!' message whenever it receives a request?", "answer": "You can achieve this by using the 'http' module in Node.js. Here is an example code that demonstrates the solution:\n\n```javascript\nconst http = require('http');\n\nconst hostname = '127.0.0.1';\nconst port = 8080;\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) => {\n res.statusCode = 200;\n res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');\n res.end('Hello World!');\n});\n\nserver.listen(port, hostname, () => {\n console.log(`Server running at http://${hostname}:${port}/`);\n});\n```\n\nExplanation:\n1. First, we import the 'http' module to access the functionality it provides.\n2. Then, we define the hostname and port variables. In this example, the server will run on '127.0.0.1' (localhost) and listen on port 8080.\n3. We create a server using the `createServer` method, which takes a callback function as a parameter. This callback function is executed whenever a request is received by the server.\n4. Inside the callback function, we set the response status code to 200, indicating a successful response.\n5. We set the 'Content-Type' header of the response to 'text/plain', specifying that the response body will be plain text.\n6. Finally, we send the 'Hello World!' message as the response body using the `end` method.\n7. The server is then set to listen on the specified port and hostname using the `listen` method. Once the server starts listening, the provided callback function is executed and a message is logged to the console.\n\nThis code will create a Node.js server that listens on port 8080 and sends a 'Hello World!' message whenever it receives a request."}
