{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_368395", "question": "I have a problem where when a user submits a form and leaves certain fields blank, they get saved as blank in the DB. I want to iterate through the `params[:user]` collection and if a field is blank, I want to set it to `nil` before updating the attributes. I tried using `each` to iterate, but it seems to create new objects instead. Can someone help me figure out how to do this?\n\n```ruby\ncoll = params[:user].each do |c|\n    if c == \"\"\n       c = nil\n    end\nend\n```\n\nThanks.", "answer": "To achieve your desired outcome, you can utilize a `before_save` callback in the model or an observer. By doing so, you can apply the same behavior regardless of where the change originates from (e.g., controller, console, batch processes). Here's an example:\n\n```ruby\nclass User < ActiveRecord::Base\n  NULL_ATTRS = %w(first_name last_name)\n  before_save :nil_if_blank\n\n  protected\n\n  def nil_if_blank\n    NULL_ATTRS.each { |attr| self[attr] = nil if self[attr].blank? }\n  end\nend\n```\n\nIn this example, the `before_save` callback is triggered before the model is saved. The `nil_if_blank` method iterates through the `NULL_ATTRS` array, which contains the attributes (fields) that you want to check for blank values. If an attribute is blank, it is set to `nil`. \n\nHere's how it behaves in practice:\n\n```ruby\nuser = User.new\nuser.first_name = \"John\"\nuser.last_name = \"\" # blank string here\nuser.save\n\nuser.first_name # Output: \"John\"\nuser.last_name.nil? # Output: true\n```\n\nBy using this approach, you can ensure that blank fields are saved as `nil` in the database, providing consistent behavior across different scenarios."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_773208", "question": "Background: Sir Pelham Grenville Wodehouse  (; 15 October 1881 - 14 February 1975) was an English author and one of the most widely read humorists of the 20th century. Born in Guildford, the son of a British magistrate based in Hong Kong, Wodehouse spent happy teenage years at Dulwich College, to which he remained devoted all his life. After leaving school, he was employed by a bank but disliked the work and turned to writing in his spare time.\nContext: There had been films of Wodehouse stories since 1915, when A Gentleman of Leisure was based on his 1910 novel of the same name. Further screen adaptations of his books were made between then and 1927, but it was not until 1929 that Wodehouse went to Hollywood where Bolton was working as a highly paid writer for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (MGM). Ethel was taken with both the financial and social aspects of Hollywood life, and she negotiated a contract with MGM on her husband's behalf under which he would be paid $2,000 a week. This large salary was particularly welcome because the couple had lost considerable sums in the Wall Street Crash of 1929.  The contract started in May 1930, but the studio found little for Wodehouse to do, and he had spare time to write a novel and nine short stories. He commented, \"It's odd how soon one comes to look on every minute as wasted that is given to earning one's salary.\" Even when the studio found a project for him to work on, the interventions of committees and constant rewriting by numerous contract authors meant that his ideas were rarely used. In a 2005 study of Wodehouse in Hollywood, Brian Taves writes that Those Three French Girls (1930) was \"as close to a success as Wodehouse was to have at MGM. His only other credits were minimal, and the other projects he worked on were not produced.\"  Wodehouse's contract ended after a year and was not renewed. At MGM's request, he gave an interview to The Los Angeles Times. Wodehouse was described by Herbert Warren Wind as \"politically naive [and] fundamentally unworldly,\" and he caused a sensation by saying publicly what he had already told his friends privately about Hollywood's inefficiency, arbitrary decision-making, and waste of expensive talent. The interview was reprinted in The New York Times, and there was much editorial comment about the state of the film industry. Many writers have considered that the interview precipitated a radical overhaul of the studio system, but Taves believes it to have been \"a storm in a teacup\", and Donaldson comments that, in the straitened post-crash era, the reforms would have been inevitable.  Wind's view of Wodehouse's naivete is not universally held. Some biographers suggest that his unworldliness was only part of a complex character, and that in some respects he was highly astute. He was unsparing of the studio owners in his early-1930s short stories set in Hollywood, which contain what Taves considers Wodehouse's sharpest and most biting satire.\nQuestion: Did Hollywood get upset about what he said\n\nAnswer:", "answer": "Yes, Hollywood was indeed upset about the remarks made by Sir Pelham Grenville Wodehouse (P.G. Wodehouse). His public declaration of Hollywood's inefficiencies, arbitrary decision-making process, and what he perceived as wasteful use of expensive talent was not taken lightly by the movie industry.\n\nWodehouse's comments were shared widely after he gave an interview to The Los Angeles Times, in which he openly criticized the Hollywood system and the way things operated there. His remarks were so impactful that they were later reprinted in The New York Times, drawing significant attention and causing quite a stir in the film industry. There was ample editorial commentary that followed, discussing and debating the state of the film industry based on Wodehouse's observations. This response indicates the kind of disruption and unrest his comments stirred among Hollywood's top brass and within the industry in general.\n\nHowever, some writers and researchers consider the entire episode as just \"a storm in a teacup\", suggesting that the effect and influence of Wodehouse's critiques may have been exaggerated. Brian Taves and Francis Donaldson, for instance, think that the change in the studio system had been inevitable due to the economic challenges faced post the Wall Street Crash of 1929, and Wodehouse's comments just served as a catalyst or an excuse to revamp the system.\n\nNevertheless, Wodehouse's remarks didn't play well with the studio owners and those in high places in Hollywood. Wodehouse was known for his biting satire and was unyielding in his criticism, as seen in his early-1930s short stories which contained scathing remarks about Hollywood. Therefore, it can be assumed that his public critique probably didn't endear him to the film industry, reinforcing the idea that what he said caused significant offense and displeasure among Hollywood's elite. His contract with the studio ended after a year and was not renewed, which could be seen as the studios' indirect reaction to his critiques."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_648759", "question": "Read this and answer the question\n\nThe infinitive form ends in t (archaically, ti). It is the form found in dictionaries and the form that follows auxiliary verbs (for example, můžu tě slyšet—\"I can hear you\"). Czech verbs have three grammatical moods: indicative, imperative and conditional. The imperative mood adds specific endings for each of three person (or number) categories: -Ø/-i/-ej for second-person singular, -te/-ete/-ejte for second-person plural and -me/-eme/-ejme for first-person plural. The conditional mood is formed with a particle after the past-tense verb. This mood indicates possible events, expressed in English as \"I would\" or \"I wish\".\n\nWhich Czech verb mood indicates possible events?", "answer": "The Czech verb mood that indicates possible events is the conditional mood. It is formed with a particle after the past-tense verb and used to express possibilities, similar to the English expressions \"I would\" or \"I wish.\""}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_198467", "question": "Develop a computational procedure to discern prime numbers by examining their divisibility only by 1 and themselves, taking into account the complexities of prime factorization and the potential effects of other mathematical operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division.", "answer": "Sure, I can help with that! Here's a simple computational procedure to determine whether a given number is prime:\n1. Take the number you want to test for primality and divide it by 2. If the remainder is 0, then the number is not prime, since it is divisible by 2.\n2. If the remainder is not 0, divide the number by the next odd integer, which is 3. If the remainder is 0, then the number is not prime, since it is divisible by 3.\n3. Continue this process, dividing the number by each subsequent odd integer up to the square root of the number. If the number is not divisible by any of these integers, then it is prime.\nFor example, let's say we want to determine whether the number 29 is prime:\n1. 29 divided by 2 gives a remainder of 1, so we continue to step 2.\n2. 29 divided by 3 gives a remainder of 2, so we continue to step 3.\n3. We need to check whether 29 is divisible by any odd integer up to the square root of 29, which is approximately 5.39. So we check whether 29 is divisible by 5. Since 29 divided by 5 gives a remainder of 4, we know that 29 is not divisible by 5.\nTherefore, we can conclude that 29 is prime.\nThis procedure works because any composite number can be expressed as the product of two smaller integers. If neither of these smaller integers is a factor of the original number, then the original number must be prime. The procedure also takes advantage of the fact that we only need to check divisors up to the square root of the original number, since any larger divisors would already have corresponding smaller divisors that we have already checked."}
