{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_674854", "question": "In this task, you are given the abstract of a research paper. Your task is to generate a summary of this abstract. Your summary should not be very short, but it's better if it's not more than 30 words.\n\nVariational inference based on chi-square divergence minimization (CHIVI) provides a way to approximate a model's posterior while obtaining an upper bound on the marginal likelihood. However, in practice CHIVI relies on Monte Carlo (MC) estimates of an upper bound objective that at modest sample sizes are not guaranteed to be true bounds on the marginal likelihood. This paper provides an empirical study of CHIVI performance on a series of synthetic inference tasks. We show that CHIVI is far more sensitive to initialization than classic VI based on KL minimization, often needs a very large number of samples (over a million), and may not be a reliable upper bound. We also suggest possible ways to detect and alleviate some of these pathologies, including diagnostic bounds and initialization strategies.", "answer": "Part 1: Task definition: Generate a summary of provided abstract.\nUsage: \"Variational inference approach CHIVI's performance is studied, revealing sensitivity to initialization, large sample size requirements, and unreliability as an upper bound.\" This sentence summarizes the abstract's main points, meeting the criteria for the task.\n\nPart 2: Summary length: No more than 30 words.\nUsage: The previous sample response is 19 words long, meeting the maximum length requirement.\n\nPart 3: Content: Focus on key points from the research paper's abstract.\nUsage: The sample response addresses CHIVI's performance, sensitivity, sample size, and reliability, which are the main points discussed in the abstract and therefore meets this criterion."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_224183", "question": "I am working with Plotly and I want to change the default fillcolor to a transparent one. But, every time I try to change the fillcolor, it is not transparent anymore. Here is the code I am using:\n\n```python\ntrace = (go.Scatter(x=[30,45],y=[3000,3000],\n            fill='tozeroy', \n#                 fillcolor='green',\n#                 fillcolor='rgb(26,150,65,0.5)',\n#                 fillcolor=dict(color='rgb(26,150,65,0.5)'),\n#          fillcolor=dict(marker=dict(color='rgb(26,150,65,0.5)')),\n            opacity=0.1,\n            showlegend=False,\n            hoverinfo='none',\n            mode='none'))\npy.offline.iplot(go.Figure(data=[trace]))\n```\n\nIn the default case, it results in the following plot:\n\n![default fillcolor](https://i.stack.imgur.com/Q65q6.png)\n\nAnd when I use `fillcolor='green'`, it results in this nontransparent color:\n\n![fillcolor = green](https://i.stack.imgur.com/UWyd4.png)\n\nBut, the commented code results in the default case again. How can I change the fillcolor to another and still maintain transparency?", "answer": "You should be able to achieve this by using rgba color codes. The 'a' stands for 'alpha', which controls the opacity of the color. You can set it to any value between 0 (completely transparent) and 1 (completely opaque). \n\nHere's an example of how you can modify your code:\n\n```python\ntrace = (go.Scatter(x=[30,45],y=[3000,3000],\n            fill='tozeroy', \n            fillcolor='rgba(26,150,65,0.5)',\n            opacity=0.1,\n            showlegend=False,\n            hoverinfo='none',\n            mode='none'))\npy.offline.iplot(go.Figure(data=[trace]))\n```\n\nIn the above code, the fillcolor is set to 'rgba(26,150,65,0.5)'. The '0.5' at the end is the alpha channel, setting it to 0.5 makes the color semi-transparent. \n\nYou can adjust the alpha channel to get the desired level of transparency."}
