{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_259101", "question": "Is there a way to design a program that can calculate the sum of two matrices? I want to create a function that takes in two matrices as input and returns a new matrix that contains the sum of the corresponding elements from the two input matrices. Can you provide me with a code example?", "answer": "Certainly! You can use the following code to compute the sum of two matrices:\n\n```python\ndef matrix_sum(matrix1, matrix2):\n    # Create a new matrix with the same dimensions\n    result = []\n    for i in range(len(matrix1)):\n        row = []\n        for j in range(len(matrix1[i])):\n            row.append(matrix1[i][j] + matrix2[i][j])\n        result.append(row)\n    return result\n\n# Example usage:\nmatrix1 = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]\nmatrix2 = [[5, 6], [7, 8]]\nresult = matrix_sum(matrix1, matrix2)\nprint(result)  # prints [[6, 8], [10, 12]]\n```\n\nIn this code, the function `matrix_sum` takes two matrices (`matrix1` and `matrix2`) as input. It creates a new matrix (`result`) with the same dimensions as the input matrices. Then, it iterates over each element of the input matrices using nested loops. It adds the corresponding elements from `matrix1` and `matrix2` and appends the sum to the `result` matrix. Finally, it returns the `result` matrix.\n\nIn the example usage, we have two matrices (`matrix1` and `matrix2`) defined as `[[1, 2], [3, 4]]` and `[[5, 6], [7, 8]]` respectively. We call the `matrix_sum` function with these matrices as arguments and store the returned result in the `result` variable. Finally, we print the `result` matrix, which gives us `[[6, 8], [10, 12]]` as the sum of the corresponding elements from `matrix1` and `matrix2`."}
