{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_617538", "question": "Given the task definition and input, reply with output. In this task you are given a sentence with one coordinating conjunction (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, and so). You must judge whether the order of two coordinated clausal conjoints have been inverted or not. Inversion would result in the sentence sounding unnatural. Label the instances as \"Original\" or \"Inversion\" based on your judgment.\n\nHer lungs were burning for air and she hadn 't even realized it .", "answer": "This task is asking you to determine if the given sentence has an unnatural order of clausal conjoints connected by a coordinating conjunction. The sentence you are given contains a coordinating conjunction (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, or so). Follow these simple steps to complete the task:\n\n1. Identify the coordinating conjunction in the sentence. In this case, the conjunction is \"and.\"\n\n2. Break the sentence into two clausal conjoints, separated by the coordinating conjunction.\n\n   - Her lungs were burning for air\n   - She hadn't even realized it\n\n3. Determine if the order of these clausal conjoints sounds natural or unnatural in the sentence. In this case, the sentence sounds natural.\n\n4. Based on your judgment, label the sentence as \"Original\" if it has a natural order, or \"Inversion\" if the order seems inverted and unnatural.\n\nHere, since the sentence has a natural order, label it as \"Original.\""}
