{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_210723", "question": "Can you use your logic skills to identify the prime number among these integers: 7, 14, 29, 58, and 117? Here is a table that may help you:\n| Number | Is it a Prime? |\n|--------|---------------|\n| 7      | Yes           |\n| 14     | No            |\n| 29     | Yes           |\n| 58     | No            |\n| 117    | No            |\nTo determine whether a number is prime, a formula was applied in Excel as follows:\n=IF(COUNTIF($A$2:$A$6,A2)=1,IF(MOD(A2,ROW(INDIRECT(\"2:\"&INT(SQRT(A2)))))<>0,\"Yes\",\"No\"),\"No\")\nThis method confirms whether the number appears only once in the series, then checks whether it is divisible by any number from 2 to the square root of the number. If it is not divisible by any of those numbers, it is classified as a prime number and shown as \"Yes\" in the table. Can you find the prime number from the given series using this table?", "answer": "Yes, the prime number among the given integers is 7. According to the table, 7 appears only once in the series and is classified as a prime number."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_611748", "question": "Throughout their history, the Liberals have been in electoral terms largely the party of the middle class (whom Menzies, in the era of the party's formation called \"The forgotten people\"), though such class-based voting patterns are no longer as clear as they once were. In the 1970s a left-wing middle class emerged that no longer voted Liberal.[citation needed] One effect of this was the success of a breakaway party, the Australian Democrats, founded in 1977 by former Liberal minister Don Chipp and members of minor liberal parties; other members of the left-leaning section of the middle-class became Labor supporters.[citation needed] On the other hand, the Liberals have done increasingly well in recent years among socially conservative working-class voters.[citation needed]However the Liberal Party's key support base remains the upper-middle classes; 16 of the 20 richest federal electorates are held by the Liberals, most of which are safe seats. In country areas they either compete with or have a truce with the Nationals, depending on various factors.\nIs there an answer to this question (If it cannot be answered, say \"unanswerable\"): In what year were the Australian Democrats founded?", "answer": "The Australian Democrats were founded in the year 1977."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_462137", "question": "If it takes 30 minutes to prepare pizza dough and another 30 minutes for the pizza to cook in the oven, and one batch of dough can make 3 pizzas but the oven can only fit 2 pizzas at a time, how many hours will it take for Camilla to complete the process of making 12 pizzas?", "answer": "One batch of dough can make 3 pizzas, so to make 12 pizzas, Camilla will need 12/3 = 4 batches of dough.\nPreparing one batch of dough takes 30 minutes, so preparing 4 batches will take 4 * 30 = 120 minutes.\nThe oven can only fit 2 pizzas at a time, so Camilla will need to cook 12/2 = 6 times.\nCooking one batch of pizzas takes 30 minutes, so cooking 6 batches will take 6 * 30 = 180 minutes.\nIn total, the whole process of making 12 pizzas will take 120 + 180 = 300 minutes.\nSince there are 60 minutes in an hour, it will take 300/60 = 5 hours.\n#### 5\nThe answer is: 5"}
