{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_230553", "question": "How can I parse an option that contains a list of values using the Python optparse module? For instance, if I'm using the command \"--groups one,two,three\", is there a way to convert these comma-separated values into a list so they can be accessed as \"options.groups[]\"? Is there a built-in optparse option to do this or should I do it manually?", "answer": "The Python `optparse` module does not directly support list options but you can achieve your goal by using callback function option of `optparse`. \n\nHere is an example of how to do this:\n\n```python\nfrom optparse import OptionParser\n\ndef callback(option, opt_str, value, parser):\n    setattr(parser.values, option.dest, value.split(','))\n\nparser = OptionParser()\nparser.add_option(\"--groups\", type=\"string\", action=\"callback\", callback=callback)\noptions, args = parser.parse_args()\n\nprint(options.groups)\n```\n\nIn this example, we define a callback function that splits the input by comma and set the value to the option. Then we add this callback to the `--groups` option. When you pass `--groups one,two,three` to this program, `options.groups` will be the list `['one', 'two', 'three']`.\n\nSo, you can use the `callback` function to parse the input values and convert them into a list. When you run this function with `--groups one,two,three`, you will get `options.groups` as a list `['one', 'two', 'three']` which you can then use in your program."}
