{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_683893", "question": "Solve 17*y + 2*y + 76 = 0 for y.", "answer": "Sure, let's solve the linear equation 17y + 2y + 76 = 0 for y. To begin, we can combine the terms with y to simplify the equation as follows:\n\n(17y + 2y) + 76 = 0\n19y + 76 = 0\n\nNow, our goal is to isolate the term with y (in this case, 19y) and find the value of y that satisfies the equation. We can achieve this by performing the following steps:\n\n1. Subtract 76 from both sides of the equation to move the constant term to the right side:\n\n19y = -76\n\n2. To find the value of y, we need to isolate y by dividing both sides of the equation by 19 (since 19 is the coefficient of y):\n\n19y / 19 = -76 / 19\ny = -4\n\nNow that we have found the value of y that satisfies the equation, we can conclude that:\n\ny = -4\n\nTo confirm that our solution is correct, we can substitute the value of y back into the original equation:\n\n17(-4) + 2(-4) + 76\n\n-68 - 8 + 76\n\n8 - 8\n\n0\n\nSince the equation equals zero, our solution of y = -4 is correct."}
