{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_67408", "question": "Solve the system of linear equations using LU decomposition: \n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n2x+4y+6z &= 8 \\\\\n4x+9y+7z &= 12 \\\\\n6x+10y+15z &= 18\n\\end{aligned}\n$$", "answer": "To solve the system of linear equations using LU decomposition, we first need to decompose the matrix A into a lower triangular matrix L and an upper triangular matrix U. The given system can be represented as:\n\n$$\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n2 & 4 & 6 \\\\\n4 & 9 & 7 \\\\\n6 & 10 & 15\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\begin{bmatrix}\nx \\\\\ny \\\\\nz\n\\end{bmatrix}\n=\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n8 \\\\\n12 \\\\\n18\n\\end{bmatrix}\n$$\n\nNow, let's find the L and U matrices using Doolittle's method:\n\n1. U matrix:\n\n$$\nu_{ij} = a_{ij} - \\sum_{k=1}^{i-1} l_{ik}u_{kj}, \\quad i \\le j\n$$\n\n2. L matrix:\n\n$$\nl_{ij} = \\frac{1}{u_{jj}}(a_{ij} - \\sum_{k=1}^{j-1} l_{ik}u_{kj}), \\quad i > j\n$$\n\nApplying these formulas, we get:\n\n$$\nL =\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\n2 & 1 & 0 \\\\\n3 & -1 & 1\n\\end{bmatrix},\n\\quad\nU =\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n2 & 4 & 6 \\\\\n0 & 1 & -5 \\\\\n0 & 0 & 3\n\\end{bmatrix}\n$$\n\nNow, we can solve the system by first solving $Ly = b$ for y and then solving $Ux = y$ for x.\n\n1. Solve $Ly = b$:\n\n$$\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 0 & 0 \\\\\n2 & 1 & 0 \\\\\n3 & -1 & 1\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\begin{bmatrix}\ny_1 \\\\\ny_2 \\\\\ny_3\n\\end{bmatrix}\n=\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n8 \\\\\n12 \\\\\n18\n\\end{bmatrix}\n$$\n\nSolving this system, we get:\n\n$$\ny_1 = 8 \\\\\ny_2 = 12 - 2y_1 = -4 \\\\\ny_3 = 18 - 3y_1 + y_2 = 2\n$$\n\n2. Solve $Ux = y$:\n\n$$\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n2 & 4 & 6 \\\\\n0 & 1 & -5 \\\\\n0 & 0 & 3\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\begin{bmatrix}\nx \\\\\ny \\\\\nz\n\\end{bmatrix}\n=\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n8 \\\\\n-4 \\\\\n2\n\\end{bmatrix}\n$$\n\nSolving this system, we get:\n\n$$\nz = \\frac{2}{3} \\\\\ny = -4 + 5z = 2 \\\\\nx = \\frac{1}{2}(8 - 4y - 6z) = -1\n$$\n\nSo, the solution to the system of linear equations is:\n\n$$\nx = -1, \\quad y = 2, \\quad z = \\frac{2}{3}\n$$"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_60303", "question": "A ball is thrown vertically upward from a height of 10 meters above the ground with an initial velocity of 20 meters per second. Find its maximum height, the time it takes to reach the maximum height, and the velocity and acceleration at the maximum height. (Assume the acceleration due to gravity is -9.8 meters per second squared.)", "answer": "To find the maximum height, time to reach maximum height, and the velocity and acceleration at the maximum height, we can use the following kinematic equations:\n\n1. v = u + at\n2. s = ut + (1/2)at^2\n3. v^2 = u^2 + 2as\n\nwhere:\n- v is the final velocity\n- u is the initial velocity (20 m/s)\n- a is the acceleration (-9.8 m/s^2)\n- t is the time\n- s is the displacement\n\nFirst, let's find the time it takes to reach the maximum height. At the maximum height, the final velocity (v) will be 0 m/s. Using equation 1:\n\n0 = 20 + (-9.8)t\n9.8t = 20\nt = 20 / 9.8\nt ≈ 2.04 seconds\n\nNow, let's find the maximum height (displacement). Using equation 2:\n\ns = ut + (1/2)at^2\ns = (20)(2.04) + (1/2)(-9.8)(2.04)^2\ns ≈ 20.4\n\nThe maximum height above the initial height of 10 meters is 20.4 meters. So, the total maximum height above the ground is:\n\nTotal maximum height = Initial height + Maximum height\nTotal maximum height = 10 + 20.4\nTotal maximum height ≈ 30.4 meters\n\nAt the maximum height, the final velocity (v) is 0 m/s, as we mentioned earlier. The acceleration at the maximum height is the same as the acceleration due to gravity, which is -9.8 m/s^2.\n\nIn summary:\n- Maximum height: ≈ 30.4 meters\n- Time to reach maximum height: ≈ 2.04 seconds\n- Velocity at maximum height: 0 m/s\n- Acceleration at maximum height: -9.8 m/s^2"}
