{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_974986", "question": "The purpose of this document is to detail the second phase of our Flywire integration, which encompasses a series of complex features that were removed from scope for the minimum viable product. These features include new plan flow, bulk estimates, enhanced servicing and DQ Mgmt solutions, servicing transfer use cases, and cancellations. Additionally, we aim to support Flywire's fee model, which entails a $3.95 service charge per month on top of the monthly plan amount for select providers. This fee should be configured to support fees by specific \"Companies\" in Flywire's terminology, and it must go directly to Flywire, not the provider. We will also support Flywire fee as a \"DynamicFee\" in Peach and enable the creation of external payments for each service fee. The get/payment plan endpoint will show the service fee expected and paid. Furthermore, we will allow posting to a Flywire API to process fees directly to Flywire, which would be listed as a transaction on the user's bank or billing statement. This extensive integration is necessary for a launch with our key partners, Flywire, and we aim to go live by April 15, 2023.", "answer": "The second phase of the Flywire integration includes the following features:\n\n1. New plan flow: We will create a new plan flow that will allow users to select their preferred payment plan, including the option to pay in full, pay monthly, or pay by semester. This feature will require significant development effort, but it will enhance the user experience and make it easier for users to manage their payments.\n\n2. Bulk estimates: We will enable users to generate bulk estimates for multiple payments. This feature will be useful for schools or institutions that need to generate estimates for multiple students at once.\n\n3. Enhanced servicing and DQ Mgmt solutions: We will create enhanced servicing and DQ Mgmt solutions that will allow users to manage their payments more efficiently. These solutions will include automated reminders, alerts, and notifications, as well as the ability to manage their payments directly from their account.\n\n4. Servicing transfer use cases: We will support servicing transfer use cases to enable users to transfer their servicing to another institution if they choose to do so.\n\n5. Cancellations: We will enable users to cancel their payment plans if they need to do so. This feature will require careful consideration to ensure that it does not create any financial or legal issues for either the user or the institution.\n\nIn addition to these features, we will also support Flywire's fee model, which involves a $3.95 service charge per month on top of the monthly plan amount for select providers. This fee will be configurable to support fees by specific \"Companies\" in Flywire's terminology, and it will go directly to Flywire, not the provider. We will also support Flywire fee as a \"DynamicFee\" in Peach and enable the creation of external payments for each service fee. The get/payment plan endpoint will show the service fee expected and paid. Furthermore, we will allow posting to a Flywire API to process fees directly to Flywire, which would be listed as a transaction on the user's bank or billing statement.\n\nWe aim to complete this extensive integration by April 15, 2023, and launch with our key partners, Flywire. This integration will significantly enhance the user experience and enable institutions to manage their payments more efficiently."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_235297", "question": "I am using requests in Python to access a RESTful API and everything seems to work fine. I can authenticate and retrieve a session token and even unit test the methods in my class for the API. However, when I run my code, after updating over 100 records with the metadata I supply, I encounter an SSL Certificate verification error. The error is \"ssl.SSLCertVerificationError: [SSL: CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED] certificate verify failed: self signed certificate in certificate chain (_ssl.c:1045)\". I have tried setting the verify kwarg to false in my request, but the error still persists. What could be causing this and how can I resolve it?", "answer": "The error message you are seeing is due to the SSL Certificate Verification failing. This happens when the SSL Certificate of the server is not trusted by your Python environment. The most common reason for this is that the server is using a self-signed certificate and your Python environment does not trust it.\n\nAlthough you've set `verify=False`, this doesn't seem to work as expected, which could be due to some libraries in your Python environment that are not respecting this setting.\n\nOne possible solution is to add the self-signed certificate of the server to your trusted store. Here is a step-by-step guide on how to do it:\n\n1. Download the self-signed certificate from the server. You can do this using the openssl command:\n\n    ```bash\n    echo | openssl s_client -servername hostname -connect host:port 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 > certificate.crt\n    ```\n\n    Replace `hostname` with the hostname of the server and `host:port` with the host and port of the server.\n\n2. Now, you need to add this certificate to your trusted store. For this, you need to find the location of the trusted store in your Python environment. You can do this by running the following Python code:\n\n    ```python\n    import certifi\n\n    print(certifi.where())\n    ```\n\n    This will print the location of the trusted store.\n\n3. Next, you need to append the content of the certificate file you downloaded to the trusted store. You can do this with the following command:\n\n    ```bash\n    cat certificate.crt >> /path/to/trusted/store\n    ```\n\n    Replace `/path/to/trusted/store` with the location of the trusted store you obtained in the previous step.\n\nAfter doing this, your Python environment should trust the self-signed certificate of the server and you should not see the SSL Certificate Verification error anymore."}
