ick Douglass. The paper commenced publication on December 3, 1847 and ceased as The North Star in June 1851 when it merged with Gerrit Smith's Liberty Party Paper (based in Syracuse, New York) to form Frederick Douglass' Paper. The North Star's slogan was \"Right is of no Sex -- Truth is of no Color -- God is the Father of us all, and we are all Brethren.\"\n\nBased on this passage, when did frederick douglass published the north star?\nStudent B:OK... To answer the question, consider the following: The North Star was a nineteenth-century anti-slavery newspaper published from the Talman Building in Rochester, New York by abolitionist Frederick Douglass.\nnineteenth - century.\n\nProblem:Surrealism is a cultural movement that began in the early 1920s, and is best known for its visual artworks and writings. Artists painted unnerving, illogical scenes with photographic precision, created strange creatures from everyday objects, and developed painting techniques that allowed the unconscious to express itself. Its aim was to \"resolve the previously contradictory conditions of dream and reality into an absolute reality, a super-reality\".\n\nWhich artistic movements were impacted by theories of the unconscious?\nSolution:OK... The relevant sentence in the passage is: Artists painted unnerving, illogical scenes with photographic precision, created strange creatures from everyday objects, and developed painting techniques that allowed the unconscious to express itself.\nSurrealism.\n\nProblem:The 2017 US Open was the 137th edition of tennis' US Open and the fourth and final Grand Slam event of the year. It was held on outdoor hard courts at the USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center in New York City. Experimental rules featured in qualifying for the main draw as well as in the junior, wheelchair and exhibition events.\n\nBased on this passage, where is the us tennis open being held this year?\nSolution:", "answer": "OK... The relevant information for answering this question is: It was held on outdoor hard courts at the USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center in New York City.\nUSTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center in New York City."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_186757", "question": "Person A and Person B are trying to create a puzzle game using Python that not only involves logical reasoning and mathematical calculations but also incorporates a visual component. Person A is struggling with understanding the project instructions and needs to create a game that caters to players of different skill levels. Person B decides to provide them with a code snippet that includes additional features such as a scoring system and a timer. \nPerson A: \nI'm having trouble coming up with a visually appealing puzzle game idea that involves logic, math, and caters to players of different skill levels.\nPerson B: \n```python\ndef puzzle_game():\n    # write your code here\n    score = 0\n    timer = 60\n    pass\npuzzle_game()\n``` \nCan you try implementing your game idea within this code structure? Remember, the game should challenge players to use their logical reasoning and mathematical skills to solve the puzzle, while incorporating a scoring system and a timer to create a competitive and engaging experience. Good luck!", "answer": "Certainly! Here's an example of a puzzle game that involves logical reasoning, mathematical calculations, and a visual component, all while catering to players of different skill levels:\n```python\nimport random\nimport time\ndef puzzle_game():\n    # generate a random number between 1 and 100\n    answer = random.randint(1, 100)\n    # set the initial score to 0\n    score = 0\n    # set the timer to 60 seconds\n    timer = 60\n    # start the timer\n    start_time = time.time()\n    while True:\n        # get the player's guess\n        guess = input(\"Guess a number between 1 and 100: \")\n        # check if the guess is valid\n        if not guess.isdigit() or int(guess) < 1 or int(guess) > 100:\n            print(\"Invalid input. Please enter a number between 1 and 100.\")\n            continue\n        # convert the guess to an integer\n        guess = int(guess)\n        # increment the score\n        score += 1\n        # check if the guess is correct\n        if guess == answer:\n            # calculate the time taken to solve the puzzle\n            elapsed_time = time.time() - start_time\n            # calculate the final score\n            final_score = score - int(elapsed_time)\n            # print the final score and time taken\n            print(\"Congratulations! You solved the puzzle in\", round(elapsed_time, 2), \"seconds.\")\n            print(\"Your final score is\", final_score)\n            break\n        # give the player a hint\n        elif guess < answer:\n            print(\"Too low. Try again.\")\n        else:\n            print(\"Too high. Try again.\")\n        # check if the timer has run out\n        if time.time() - start_time > timer:\n            print(\"Time's up! You ran out of time.\")\n            break\npuzzle_game()\n```\nIn this game, the player is asked to guess a number between 1 and 100. Each incorrect guess incurs a penalty of 1 point, and the final score is calculated by subtracting the time taken to solve the puzzle from the total score. The game also includes a timer that runs for 60 seconds, after which the game ends and the player loses if they haven't solved the puzzle yet.\nFeel free to modify this code to suit your specific game idea and skill level requirements. Good luck!"}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_364642", "question": "I'm trying to use cmpxchg with inline assembly through c. This is my code:\n\n```\nstatic inline int\ncas(volatile void* addr, int expected, int newval) {\n    int ret;\n    asm volatile(\"movl %2 , %%eax\\n\\t\"\n                \"lock; cmpxchg %0, %3\\n\\t\"\n                \"pushfl\\n\\t\"\n                \"popl %1\\n\\t\"\n                \"and $0x0040, %1\\n\\t\"\n                : \"+m\" (*(int*)addr), \"=r\" (ret)\n                : \"r\" (expected), \"r\" (newval)\n                : \"%eax\"\n                );\n    return ret;\n}\n```\n\nThis is my first time using inline and I'm not sure what could be causing this problem.\nI tried \"cmpxchgl\" as well, but still nothing. Also tried removing the lock.\nI get \"operand size mismatch\". \nI think maybe it has something to do with the casting I do to addr, but I'm unsure. I try and exchange int for int, so don't really understand why there would be a size mismatch.\nThis is using AT&T style.\nThanks", "answer": "You had the operand order for the cmpxchg instruction reversed. AT&T syntax needs the memory destination last:\n\n```\n\"lock; cmpxchg %3, %0\\n\\t\"\n```\n\nOr you could compile that instruction with its original order using `-masm=intel`, but the rest of your code is AT&T syntax and ordering so that's not the right answer.\n\nAs for why it says \"operand size mismatch\", I can only say that that appears to be an assembler bug, in that it uses the wrong message."}
