{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_374613", "question": "I have a column in my database with the data type NVARCHAR(20). When I try to enter a data in this column that contains more than 20 characters, the last 2 characters are ignored instead of throwing an exception. Is this normal behavior? How can I secure the database to prevent this issue?\n\nHere is the code I'm using to insert data into the database:\n\n```csharp\ntry\n{\n    using (SqlConnection conn = new SqlConnection(ConnStr))\n    {\n        string Command = \"SET NOCOUNT ON; INSERT INTO [Countries] (CountryName, IsVisible) VALUES (@Name, @IsVisible);\";\n\n        using (SqlCommand comm = new SqlCommand(Command, conn))\n        {\n            comm.Parameters.Add(\"@Name\", System.Data.SqlDbType.NVarChar, 20);\n            comm.Parameters[\"@Name\"].Value = Name;\n\n            comm.Parameters.Add(\"@IsVisible\", System.Data.SqlDbType.Bit);\n            comm.Parameters[\"@IsVisible\"].Value = IsVisible;\n\n            conn.Open();\n            comm.ExecuteNonQuery();\n\n            return \"Successfully added \" + Name + \" to the countries.\";\n        }\n    }\n}\ncatch (SqlException SqlEx)\n{\n    string ErrorMessage = \"\";\n\n    for (int i = 0; i < SqlEx.Errors.Count; i++)\n    {\n        ErrorMessage += SqlEx.Errors[i].Number + \" : \" + SqlEx.Errors[i].Message + \"\\n\";\n    }\n    return ErrorMessage;\n}\n```\n\nI tried to insert a larger data than the column's length directly from the SQL Management Studio and it displayed a message about truncating the data. How can I fix this issue and make the database throw an exception instead of truncating the data?", "answer": "The issue is occurring because of these lines of code:\n\n```csharp\ncomm.Parameters.Add(\"@Name\", System.Data.SqlDbType.NVarChar, 20);\ncomm.Parameters[\"@Name\"].Value = Name;\n```\n\nThe truncation of the data is happening in .NET, not in SQL Server. The SQL Server never gets to see more than 20 characters. To fix this, you need to specify the correct length for the `SqlParam` object.\n\nAccording to the documentation for `SqlParameter`, if you specify a length of 40 characters for the `SqlParam`, .NET will automatically truncate the string to 40 characters without raising an error.\n\nYou can refer to this [link](http://www.eggheadcafe.com/software/aspnet/30873895/sqlparameter-question.aspx) for more information.\n\nTo ensure that the database throws an exception instead of truncating the data, you should modify the code as follows:\n\n```csharp\ncomm.Parameters.Add(\"@Name\", System.Data.SqlDbType.NVarChar);\ncomm.Parameters[\"@Name\"].Value = Name;\ncomm.Parameters[\"@Name\"].Size = 20;\n```\n\nBy removing the length parameter in `Add` and setting the `Size` property separately, .NET will not truncate the string and the database will throw an exception if the data exceeds the specified length."}
{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_286693", "question": "Can you provide a C program that finds the common elements between two given arrays?", "answer": "Certainly! Here's a C program that accomplishes that:\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nint main()\n{\n    int arr1[] = {2,4,6,8,10};\n    int arr2[] = {2,5,6,9,10};\n    int k=0;\n    int common[20];\n    int m = sizeof(arr1)/sizeof(arr1[0]);\n    int n = sizeof(arr2)/sizeof(arr2[0]);\n    \n    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)\n    {\n        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)\n        {\n            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j])\n            {\n                common[k] = arr1[i];\n                k++;\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    printf(\"The common elements are:\");\n    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++)\n        printf(\"%d \", common[i]);\n    \n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nThis program compares each element in the first array (`arr1`) with each element in the second array (`arr2`). If a common element is found, it is stored in the `common` array. Finally, the program prints the common elements.\n\nHope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions."}
