{"id": "general_openhermes_2_5_2300_375062", "question": "Is there a way to determine the size of a MySQL database using a query or function? If not, what is the standard method for finding the size of a database in MySQL?\n\nI came across the following query while searching online:\n\n```\nSELECT CONCAT(sum(ROUND(((DATA_LENGTH + INDEX_LENGTH - DATA_FREE) / 1024 / 1024),2)),\" MB\") AS Size \nFROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES \nWHERE TABLE_SCHEMA LIKE '%YOUR_DB_NAME%';\n```\n\nHowever, when I ran this query for a database that I know is 400MB in size, it returned a result of `474989023196466.25 MB` which doesn't seem correct.", "answer": "You can try using the following query to determine the size of a MySQL database:\n\n```sql\nSELECT table_schema AS \"Data Base Name\", \nsum(data_length + index_length) / 1024 / 1024 AS \"Data Base Size in MB\" \nFROM information_schema.TABLES \nGROUP BY table_schema;\n```\n\nThis query calculates the size of each database by summing the data length and index length of all tables within that database. The result is then divided by 1024 twice to convert it from bytes to megabytes.\n\nIf you prefer to round the size to two decimal places, you can use the following query:\n\n```sql\nSELECT table_schema AS \"Data Base Name\", \nROUND(SUM(data_length + index_length) / 1024 / 1024, 2) AS \"Data Base Size in MB\" \nFROM information_schema.TABLES \nGROUP BY table_schema;\n```\n\nBoth of these queries utilize the `information_schema.TABLES` table, which stores information about all the tables in the MySQL server. By grouping the results by the `table_schema` column, you can get the size of each individual database.\n\nRemember to replace `'YOUR_DB_NAME'` with the actual name of your database in the `WHERE` clause if you want to filter the results for a specific database."}
